<SECOND>PM-BRF--Debt Help,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women's Club Wants To Help Cut National Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a Shelby County women's club say
they can help reduce the national debt, and they've got $83 to prove
it.
   ``Shelby County is going to challenge all the little white-haired
ladies across the country to help out, all the Republican clubs,''
said Dana McKelvy, publicity chairwoman for the group.
   Ms. McKelvy's club, the Shelby County Republican Women, began a
fund drive at its monthly meeting Monday with plans to help reduce
the nation's $2.6 trillion debt. The opening collection drew $83.
   While club members realize their initial contribution is somewhat
small, they hope it is the start of bigger things.
   ``You don't become a millionaire until you save your first
nickel,'' said club president Dot Wieters.
</TEXT>
