<FIRST>r i PM-MeteorologistsStrike     02-15 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Meteorologists Strike,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>France's National Weather Service On Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cloud is hanging over negotiations between the
government and 3,000 National Weather Service employees who are
striking for higher wages.
   ``Negotiations are blocked,'' said a spokesman Tuesday for one of
four unions representing the striking meteorologists.
   The unidentified spokesman, quoted by the French news agency
Agence-France Presse, said the unions have no meetings scheduled
until Thursday with government officials responsible for the weather
service.
   Meteorologists, however, continued to provide critical aviation
and marine forecasts during the walkout.
   Before the walkout began Sunday night, meteorologists graciously
prepared a five-day forecast that runs through Thursday. After that,
the weather is anybody's guess.
   Television and radio weather forecasters have had to be
resourceful in the absence of the standard weather service bulletins
and charts.
   ``What we are doing is very rudimentary,'' said Laurent Cabrol,
chief weatherman at the network Antenne 2. ``Like some skippers, we
are capturing a few weather charts transmitted by short and medium
wave radio as facsimiles.''
   He added that he is getting some help from his colleagues in
Britain and West Germany.
   Weather service meteorologists currently earn about $1,000 a
month at the beginning of their careers.
</TEXT>
