<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SovietInspection     02-15 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Inspection,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Complete First Short-Notice Check of U.S. Compliance To Arms
Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet inspectors completed a tour Tuesday of a
former cruise missile production plant, the first such survey on
American soil under a treaty reducing medium-range nuclear missiles.
   The 10-member Soviet delegation arrived in San Diego on Monday
and completed the inspection of Air Force Plant 19 within 24 hours
as prescribed by terms of the 1987 Intermediate Nuclear Forces
Treaty.
   Soviet inspectors did not comment publicly on their findings,
which are part of a verification process to make sure the two
superpowers are abiding by their agreement, officials said.
   They were to prepare a report, a copy of which will be left with
U.S. officials, and then fly on an Air Force transport to San
Francisco. From there they were to board a Soviet plane in the next
day or so and return home, said Navy Cmdr. Ken Pease, chief
spokesman for the On-Site Inspection Agency in Washington, D.C.
   ``The Soviets are escorted 100 percent of the time they are in
the United States,'' Pease said. ``Both parties have not commented.
We feel that these inspections are a privileged function of the
treaty. The inspections are just a small part of the INF treaty.
   ``Inspectors' reports are sent back to the various governments,
both ours and theirs, and analyzed along with other inputs from
other sources.''
   The inspection at the plant, operated by General Dynamics Convair
Division, was to verify that components of the banned Air Force
Tomahawk missile system are no longer being produced there.
   ``It went in accordance with the provisions of the treaty,''
Pease said. ``The time lines have been meet. The professionalism on
both sides has been exemplary. That's about all I can say.''
   The United States and the Soviet Union are each allowed 20 annual
``quota'' or short-notice visits of certain defense plants through
1992, when the number drops to 15 per year. It will be reduced again
in 1997 to 10 visits annually for the remainder of the 13-year pact.
   U.S. inspectors have made six of their short-notice visits to
Soviet defense since August, while the Soviets have conducted four
previous short-notice inspections of U.S. installations in Europe,
Pease said.
   The inspection in San Diego was the first by the Soviets in
American territory, however, Pease said.
   Tranporter-erectors used for the ground-launched Air Force
Tomahawk missile, which has a range of 1,500 miles, had been
produced at leased areas of Air Force Plant 19 in downtown San Diego.
   The 1987 treaty calls for eliminating the U.S. military's
stockpile of 859 Air Force Tomahawk cruise missiles and Army
Pershing 2 missiles in exchange for the elimination of the Soviet
Union's 1,752 intermediate- or shorter-range nuclear missiles.
   Navy Tomahawk models, which can be fired from surface warships or
submarines, are not addressed in the accord.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
