<FIRST>r w PM-BarbaraBush     02-15 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barbara Bush,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Passes out Valentines at Nursing Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush paid a Valentine's Day
visit to a nursing home where she worked as a volunteer while
President Bush was in Congress, and told the residents that ``his
success is yours and my success.''
   The first lady, in a red blazer and black-and-white checked
skirt, took a basketful of signed, handmade valentines on Tuesday
for the patients at the Washington Home for the elderly and
terminally ill.
   ``That really means I love you all,'' Mrs. Bush told a group of
patients who chatted with her.
   She was given a large poster-board valentine reading: ``To Mrs.
Bush. Always the first lady in our hearts.''
   Mrs. Bush is a board member of the non-profit, 189-bed facility.
   Mrs. Bush told her press secretary, Anna Perez, that as a
volunteer she helped out with whatever the nurses wanted her to do,
including such tasks as doing the patients' fingernails.
   For her visit Tuesday, however, it was a different setting. She
sat and answered questions from about two dozen patients, some in
wheelchairs, while board members and others looked on.
   When one man wished success for the new president, Mrs. Bush
replied:
   ``I appreciate that and remember, his success is yours and my
success, too ... He's a good man and he won't let you down.''
   ``I love being married to the president,'' she said. ``I love my
house, and I love my life so I feel pretty good.''
   As first lady she said she wants to continue focusing attention
on literacy, and: ``I hope I'll make people care more about one
another. I think that's very important.''
   Mrs. Bush called the White House ``the most beautiful house you
could possibly believe,'' and said she would change little from the
redecorating done by former First lady Nancy Reagan.
   ``It's filled with beautiful paintings, lovely furniture and
bright sunshine,'' she said. ``If you couldn't be happy in the White
House, you just couldn't be happy anyplace.''
   One elderly man, Nathan Scott, showed her two letters he got from
Bush last year. One, dated Oct. 31, thanked him for donating to
Bush's campaign fund. The other, from July, thanked him for
contributing to the debt retirement fund of one of Bush's rivals for
the Republican nomination, Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas.
   ``He wrote you and asked you for money?'' Mrs. Bush said. ``You
ought to scold him.''
</TEXT>
