<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Moonlighting     02-15 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Moonlighting,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lack of Scripts Keeps ABC's `Moonlighting' Off the Air Until Spring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The inventive television series
``Moonlighting'' is suspending broadcast until April because of a
lack of scripts stemming from last year's scriptwriters' strike, the
executive producer said.
   ``The rumor of our death is greatly exaggerated,'' executive
producer Jay Daniels said Tuesday. ``There has been absolutely no
discussion. The word `canceled' has never been broached.''
   ABC executives said they are putting the hit comedy ``Roseanne''
in half of the show's hour-long time slot on Tuesday nights,
beginning at 9 p.m. EST on Feb. 28.
   Another popular comedy, ``The Wonder Years,'' is moving to 8:30
p.m. EST Tuesday, the spot ``Roseanne'' had occupied.
   ``Moonlighting'' has fallen in the ratings and was being beaten
regularly by NBC's ``In the Heat of the Night.'' Glenn Caron,
creator of ``Moonlighting,'' has left the show, reportedly over
creative differences with star Cybill Shepherd.
   Producers have had scheduling problems because of the 22-week
strike, Daniels said. Each episode takes nine days to shoot when
they are on schedule.
   ``We just couldn't shoot episodes fast enough, even staying on
schedule as we are,'' he said.
   The tongue-in-cheek detective show starring Bruce Willis and Miss
Shepherd will return in the spring with all new episodes, said
Brandon Stoddard, president of ABC Entertainment.
   Some say the show has suffered creatively. When Miss Shepherd
became pregnant, the producers made her character pregnant. And when
the actress' real pregnancy cut back her appearances, several
episodes featured the show's secondary stars, Allyce Beasley and
Curtis Armstrong.
   ``We've tried to get back to entertaining shows and cases pretty
much as David and Maddie have been,'' Daniels said. ``We do think
it's time for David and Maddie to start dealing with their
relationship again.''
   The absence of ``Moonlighting'' makes room for ABC to introduce
two new half-hour comedy series, ``Anything But Love,'' starring
Jamie Lee Curtis and Richard Lewis, and ``Coach,'' starring Craig T.
Nelson, Jerry Van Dyke and Shelley Fabares.
   ``Anything But Love'' will premiere Tuesday, March 7, in its
regular time slot at 9:30 p.m. EST. ``Coach'' will have a sneak
preview at 9:30 p.m. EST Feb. 28, then move into its regular 9 p.m.
time slot on March 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890215-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Housing     02-15 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales in 1988 at Highest Level in Nine Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes in 1988 hit their
highest level in nine years as purchases shifted to the lower-cost
South and Midwest and consumers opted to buy less costly dwellings
rather than leave the market, a real estate trade group reported.
   Despite the dampening effect of rising mortgage interest rates,
sales for 1988 totaled 3.99 million units, up 2.6 percent from the
previous year and the highest since 4.05 million sales were recorded
in 1979, the National Association of Realtors said Tuesday.
   ``We underestimated the buying power strength of the baby boom
generation,'' said Ira Gribin, president of the Realtors group.
``The market is being driven by people who are buying in spite of
rising rates.''
   The biggest sales gains were posted in the least expensive
regions of the country.
   Sales in the Midwest were up 6.1 percent during the last quarter
of 1988 from the previous three months and sales in the South rose
5.4 percent. The Northeast, meanwhile, posted a 2.4 percent decline
in sales, while the West recorded a 1.4 percent increase.
   ``The Midwest was a bright star of the nation's housing sector
last quarter, and we think its improvement will continue this
year,'' said John A. Tuccillo, the Realtors' chief economist. ``We
have seen activity pick up in the Midwest and South and subside in
the high-cost areas of the Northeast.''
   Prices of existing homes, meanwhile, rose 4.1 percent in 1988 to
a national median of $89,100, meaning half the homes cost more and
half cost less. For the fourth quarter of 1988, the median price was
down to $87,900.
   The group's survey of 62 metropolitan areas found stark
differences in median home prices around the nation, ranging from a
high of $231,200 in California's Orange County, which includes
Anaheim and Santa Ana, to a low of $53,500 in Oklahoma City.
   Two other California markets, San Francisco and Los Angeles,
ranked second and fourth in cost with median resale prices of
$228,100 and $191,200. Honolulu, with a median price of $225,000,
was third.
   The hot markets in California and Hawaii also recorded the
nation's largest price increases between the fourth quarter of 1987
and the same period last year.
   Prices in Orange County were up 32.2 percent, while they rose
29.6 percent in San Francisco, 24.6 percent in Los Angeles, and 18.6
percent in San Diego. In Hawaii, prices were up 16.4 percent.
   The increased sales activity in the Midwest resulted in healthy
price appreciation in several cities in that area, including
Chicago, where the median price last quarter rose to $101,400, up
10.8 percent from the fourth quarter of 1987.
   The $87,200 price in Minneapolis-St. Paul was up 8.2 percent and
Detroit's median of $73,400 was up 10.7 percent.
   ``In the Midwest, we are seeing prices increase in areas that
were largely bypassed by the housing expansion earlier in the
1980s,'' Tuccillo said.
   While prices in the Northeast remained high, costs in several
cities there showed little escalation and even dropped in some cases.
   Prices in fifth-ranked Boston moved up a modest 3 percent to
$182,800.
   In the New York metropolitan area, which includes Long Island and
northern New Jersey, prices were down 3.6 percent in the last
quarter of 1988, but still ranked sixth in the nation at $178,500.
   Seventh-ranked Hartford, with a median home price of $165,000,
saw prices edge up just 0.7 percent.
   ``In the Northeast, prices have basically run away from family
income,'' Tuccillo said. ``The market is slowing down there until
incomes can catch up.''
   The least expensive places to live were led by Oklahoma City,
where the median price was $53,500; followed by Des Moines, Iowa, at
$54,800; Louisville, Ky., at $55,600; Toledo, Ohio, at $56,400; and
Lansing, Mich., at $56,700.
   Prices in Oklahoma City fell 10.1 percent from the fourth quarter
of 1987, the sharpest drop in the survey. Other oil-dependent areas
also recorded falling prices, including Houston, where the median
dropped 9.6 percent to $56,800, and San Antonio, Texas, where the
median fell 8.1 percent to $62,100.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
