<FIRST>u a AM-HelicopterCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0725 02-15 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helicopter Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0725,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army National Guard Helicopter Crashes In Nevada Desert</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with victim IDs, add background
on copter and mission. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `Bloise said...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIAN SPRINGS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army National Guard helicopter
based in Colorado crashed Tuesday while en route to war games in the
desert, killing one crewman and injuring the other, the Air Force
said.
   The AH-1 Cobra gunship went down at 1:30 p.m. about 50 miles
northwest of Las Vegas while on its way to an exercise at the Nellis
Air Force Base range, Air Force Sgt. Ronald Bloise said.
   The dead crew member was identified as Chief Warrant Officer
Howard P. Osterlin, 47, of Lakewood, Colo. Osterlin was the co-pilot
and had 24 years of military service, National Guard spokesman Bruce
Collins said.
   The pilot, Warrant Officer Craig A. Temmer, 28, of Denver, was
taken to the Nellis hospital, where he was treated for minor
injuries.
   Collins said the two-seat attack helicopter was assigned to the
2nd Battalion 135th Aviation unit at Buckley Air National Guard base
in Aurora, Colo., and had been participating in Red Flag exercises
at Nellis since Feb. 4.
   Red Flag is a simulated war games program conducted several times
each year at the southern Nevada base. The exercise draws Air Force
units from around the world for mock combat.
   Bloise said an emergency response team was dispatched to the
crash site, about five miles west of an auxiliary air field in
Indian Springs.
   Bloise said a board of Army officers will investigate the
accident.
</TEXT>
