<DOCNO> AP890215-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0256EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-NorthTrial-Chronology     02-15 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-North Trial-Chronology,780</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of key events in the
Oliver North Iran-Contra case, from his indictment through Tuesday's
developments.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1988</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   March 16 _ North, former national security adviser John M.
Poindexter and two others are indicted on charges they conspired to
divert Iranian arms sales profits to the Contras. ``I can assure you
I will never give up, we will win, I just cannot tell you how
soon,'' North says.
   March 18 _ North announces his retirement from the Marine Corps
because he may subpoena ``the highest ranking officials in our
government.''
   June 6 _ U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell, who authorized
turning over 300,000 documents to the defense, warns that the danger
of exposing the nation's most sensitive secrets poses a serious
obstacle to pursuing the conspiracy charges against the four
defendants.
   June 8 _ Gesell orders separate trials for the four defendants;
independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh, the next day, chooses North
for the leadoff trial.
   Sept. 30 _ An appeals court rebuffs an attempt by North and two
other defendants to stop the prosecution.
   Nov. 7 _ One of 16 criminal counts, fabricating a document, is
dismissed.
   Nov. 21 _ Gesell warns that if North stands trial, the court will
have little control over the testimony of witnesses ``acquainted
with high security matters.'' He appeals to President Reagan to
decide whether North is to be pardoned.
   Nov. 29 _ Gesell refuses to dismiss two of the central charges
against North, conspiracy to defraud the government and theft of
government property. He dismisses a third, wire fraud.
   Dec. 1 _ Reagan rules out a North pardon but says ``duty
requires'' his administration to block release of secret documents
North wants for his trial.
   Dec. 1 _ Mexican officials disclosed that Amiram Nir, the Israeli
go-between in secret U.S. arms deals with Iran, died Nov. 30 in a
plane crash in Mexico while traveling under an assumed name.
   Dec. 12 _ Gesell tells North he can't use 3,500 secret documents,
that he can use more than 300, roughly the same number planned to be
introduced as evidence by the prosecution. The decision removes a
major obstacle to the trial going forward.
   Dec. 30 _ North subpoenas Reagan and President-elect Bush as
defense witnesses. Gesell, after Bush is sworn in the following
month, rules that the sitting president cannot be called. He
postpones a decision regarding Reagan pending further hearings.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1989</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 5 _ Prosecutors ask Gesell to dismiss conspiracy and theft
charges, citing North's ``insistence on introducing classified
information in his defense'' and the Reagan administration's refusal
to release material the judge ruled North would need. Gesell later
dismisses those counts.
   North remains charged with 12 crimes, including lying to Congress
in 1985 and 1986 about his efforts on behalf of the Contras and
lying to the attorney general about the National Security Council's
role in diverting money from the Iran arms sales.
   He also is accused of illegally accepting a $13,800 security
system at his home from co-defendant Richard Secord, converting to
his own use at least $4,300 in traveler's checks from Contra leader
Adolfo Calero, and conspiring to defraud the government of tax
revenue by using a tax-exempt foundation to funnel money to the
Contras.
   Jan. 31 _ Jury selection begins.
   Feb. 7 _ Lawyers for North move to stop the trial on grounds that
the jury selection process failed to meet legal requirements. Gesell
takes no immediate action.
   Feb. 8 _ The Justice Department interrupts North's trial, urging
new safeguards to prevent him from making surprise disclosures of
classified information. Gesell denies the request.
   Feb. 9 _ A federal appeals court denies the Justice Department's
attempt to stop North's trial on national security grounds, but the
Bush administration vows to continue trying to put the proceeding on
hold.
   Feb. 10 _ The Justice Department seeks for a third time to delay
North's trial, contending that defense lawyers would hurt national
security by spilling state secrets onto the public record. A federal
appeal court panel again denies the request.
   Feb. 11 _ The Justice Department asks the Supreme Court to delay
North's trial on national security grounds.
   Feb. 12 _ Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist grants a delay in
North's trial until the full Supreme Court can consider on Feb. 17
the Justice Department's objections to the planned release of
classified material by North's defense.
   Feb. 14 _ Gesell rejects an agreement that would have allowed the
Justice Department to object at any time to defense disclosures of
classified material. Gesell ruled that Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh may not file a series of affidavits in ``bits and
pieces'' during North's trial.
</TEXT>
