<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Appointments     02-15 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Appointments,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Still Behind on Appointments, Calls for Quicker Background Checks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is still trying to fill scores
of top government posts and has asked his legal counsel to look into
ways to speed up background checks on people he wants to appoint, a
White House source said.
   Bush is frustrated by a drawn-out process that is keeping him
from putting people in place and moving his agenda forward, said the
source, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The president, at a Tuesday meeting of his top assistants,
expressed impatience and told White House counsel C. Boyden Gray to
see what he could do about speeding up the process, the source said.
   That source and another official said much of the problem
involves the lengthy FBI background-checking process and the
requirement that a person who worked for one government agency in
the past must start anew in the process when picked for a different
agency.
   But White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush is
moving slowly in making nominations partly because of attempts to
recruit women and minorities, people from outside government who are
undergoing checks for the first time.
   ``We're in no particular hurry,'' Fitzwater told reporters at the
daily White House briefing.
   He said some 130 appointments were being checked by the FBI, and
the administration was ``particularly trying to find women and
minorities for many of these positions.''
   ``Some of the background checks are taking longer than has been
the case in the past,'' he said.
   In the meantime, many of these key jobs are being held by Reagan
administration holdovers.
   In the first weeks of the Reagan administration in 1981, dozens
of such key nominations had been confirmed by the Senate. There so
far has been no confirmation of anyone but some Cabinet nominees.
   The Washington Post reported Tuesday that Commerce Secretary
Robert Mosbacher complained to White House staff chief John Sununu
about the selection process.
   Fitzwater said he believed that the report overstated Mosbacher's
frustration with the situation.
   On another matter, Fitzwater said that in selecting people for
ambassadorial posts, Bush wants to find the best-qualified
candidates, not necessarily use the posts to reward old friends and
supporters.
   Few ambassadorial appointments have been announced. The New York
Times reported Tuesday, however, that Bush has honored tradition by
rewarding major campaign contributors with plum assignments.
   The newspaper mentioned the appointment of J.P. Curley Jr. of New
York, a fund-raiser and family friend, to become ambassador to
France; Peter Secchia, the Republican national committeeman from
Michigan, ambassador to Italy; investor and developer Joseph Zappala
of Tampa, Fla., ambassador to Spain; Florida developer Melvin F.
Sembler, ambassador to Australia; and Fredrick Bush, deputy finance
chairman of the campaign and no relation to the president,
ambassador to Luxembourg.
   Fitzwater said Bush wants ``qualified men and women of recognized
leadership and ability. And we think all our ambassador appointments
will be of the highest quality.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
