<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HealthPolicy-Diabetes     02-15 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Health Policy-Diabetes,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Studies Look at Long-Term Economics of Prevention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government could save more money in the
long run if it paid for the early detection and treatment of a
blinding disease in diabetics, says a study that is one of a growing
number to stress the economics of health care.
   ``The cost of saving a year of sight is substantially less _
approximately one seventh _ the cost of a year of disability paid by
the federal government (to the blind),'' Dr. Jonathan C. Javitt, an
ophthalmologist at the Wilmer Eye Institute at Johns Hopkins
University and principal author of the eye disease study, said in an
interview Tuesday.
   In the face of soaring health care costs, more researchers are
considering the financial implications of expensive medical
treatments and the savings that can be had through preventive
measures.
   This growing new class of research based on financial as well as
clinical considerations of treatment comes from the ``recognition
that just outcomes of care without sensitivity to cost is not
enough,'' said Jonathan Weiner, associate professor of health policy
at Johns Hopkins.
   The studies come in response to increasing pressures from the
federal government and other health-care payers in the face of
escalating health care costs and the consequences for an estimated
35 million Americans who don't qualify for government health
assistance and can't afford private insurance.
   ``More and more clinical journals are talking about cost
effectiveness,'' Weiner said, and doctors are increasingly looking
at ``dollars along with their doses.''
   The eye disease that was the subject of the study, diabetic
retinopathy, is the leading cause of new cases of blindness among
working-age Americans. The study said more than 70 percent of
diabetics will develop the disease in their lifetime.
   Early detection and treatment of the eye disease, though, can
reduce the likelihood of severe vision loss by 60 percent, said the
study published in the February issue of Ophthalmology, the journal
of the American Academy of Ophthalmology.
   As many as 880,000 of the 11 million Americans who have diabetes
have no medical insurance, and many more may be underinsured, the
study said. These people are less likely than insured diabetics to
seek medical care for screening and treatment of the eye disease.
   Early screening and treatment could save an average three years
of sight for each diabetic, the study said. Adding up the costs of
screening and treatment for all diabetic patients, this amounts to
an average savings of $966 for each year of sight saved per person,
the study said.
   In contrast, the average annual cost of Social Security
disability payments made to each American worker disabled by
diabetes-related vision loss is $6,900, the study said. In addition,
anyone who remains eligible for Social Security disability insurance
for two years automatically becomes eligible for Medicare benefits.
   Javitt and his colleagues at Johns Hopkins' Dana Center for
Preventive Ophthalmology developed a computer model that analyzed
progression of the disease, vision loss in afflicted patients,
treatment outcome and mortality.
   These disease-related events were applied statistically to 31,000
cases _ the estimated number of new cases of juvenile-onset,
insulin-dependent diabetes each year in the United States. People
with this kind of diabetes generally get the disease before age 30.
   Diabetes deteriorates small blood vessels in the body, including
those in the retina at the back of the eye. In the early stages of
the eye disease, weakened blood vessels may leak, causing the retina
to swell and resulting in blurred vision.
   In more advanced stages of the disease, the retina becomes so
starved of oxygen-carrying blood, new blood vessels begin to grow,
but they tend to rupture and bleed. This results in more scarring
and blurred vision and can cause the retina to detach from the back
of the eye, which often leads to severe vision loss or blindness.
   The most common treatment for the eye disease is laser therapy,
which seals the blood vessels and halts the disease's progress.
   The computer model predicted that 54 percent of the 31,000 people
studied would have severe vision loss if not screened or treated for
the eye disease, compared with 28 percent who received early
treatment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
