<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     02-15 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUPERIOR, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some grassroots lobbyists are bound for the
nation's capital to wine and dine lawmakers _ well, dine them anyway
_ on one of those products you just can't find in fancy Georgetown
bistros.
   We're talking about venison sausage.
   About three dozen folks from Superior, a blue collar town of
27,000 on the shore of Lake Superior, are taking suitcases full of
the stuff to Washington on Monday in hopes of influencing as many
Wisconsin congressmen and staff members as they can on a $1,000
budget.
   They'll also bring smoked salmon, wild rice, smoked turkey and
artificial crabmeat, paper plates to eat it on and plenty of
Wisconsin beer and mineral water to wash it all down.
   ``It'll be the lobbying event of the year,'' promised state Rep.
Frank Boyle, who spent Thanksgiving weekend negotiating icy
northwoods roads in his pickup, collecting the carcasses of
illegally killed deer to make sausage for the trip.
   The Superior lobbyists plan to talk to lawmakers about Food for
Peace shipments, federal procurement and the possibility of locating
a federal penitentiary in Superior, which is known for punishingly
cold winter weather.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>THOMASVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Len Powell is building a business,
selling what appears to be one of the most abundant products in
Georgia _ road kill opossum.
   His 3-ounce cans are labeled ``Sun Dried Georgia Possum.
Contents: Pure Possum killed by a log truck on U.S. 19 South in
Thomasville, Ga.''
   The novelty items, a salable embodiment of every 'possum pancake
joke ever heard, are being sold around Georgia, Powell said. He
quickly added that they're just a joke and don't really contain
road-killed marsupial meat.
   ``It's just potted meat. It wouldn't hurt somebody to eat it,''
he said. But after a pause, he added, ``Between the two, you'd
probably rather have 'possum.''
   The label _ which reads ``GUARANTEED SUN-CURED FOR ONE DAY'' _
also has serving instructions: ``Serve on crackers. Goes best with
sweet potatoes, R.C. Cola and a Moon Pie.''
   Powell said he modeled his product after a similar one he saw in
Alabama, and initially gave them away to customers at his
Thomasville nursery.
   ``People started wanting 'em so much I started selling 'em,'' he
said, adding that they're now sold in about 70 stores around the
state.
   Powell said he's expanding with labels for Mississippi,
Louisiana, Alabama, Tennessee and South Carolina. In addition, he
markets cans of ``road-killed'' armadillo, which he calls, ``possum
on the half shell.''
</TEXT>
