<FIRST>r i PM-China-Priest     02-15 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Priest,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priest Accused Of Vatican Ties Released From Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly priest in the underground Roman
Catholic church who was alleged to have received money from the
Vatican has been released from jail after 2{ months, a Chinese
official said.
   The Rev. Liu Shuhe, 69, who also uses the name Paul, was arrested
in October after allegedly meeting with an unidentified Italian.
   The Italian Embassy said today it did not know of any Italian
having been in contact with Liu and was not familiar with the case.
   Police confiscated $12,000 he was carrying and alleged that it
was sent from the Vatican, an official of Liu's home county said
Tuesday.
   Contacts with the Vatican, with whom China has no relations, are
illegal.
   Shen Rongbin of the Civil Affairs Committee in Yi County, about
60 miles south of the capital, said Liu was jailed there and
released Jan. 16.
   Shen said Liu maintained that the money was mailed to him by a
former classmate now in the Philippines. But Shen said Liu was known
to be in contact with the Vatican through foreign travelers to China
and the mail.
   The Vatican, a sovereign state within Italy, still recognizes the
Nationalist Chinese on Taiwan as the rightful rulers of all China.
   The Communists who took power in 1949 set up their own Catholic
Patriotic Association to manage Catholic church affairs, and ordered
all Chinese Catholics to renounce allegiance to the Vatican.
   Liu was among hundreds of priests, nuns and laymen who were
arrested in the 1950s and released only in the 1970s because of
their refusal to renounce the Vatican.
   An unknown number of Catholics still loyal to the Vatican
continue to worship in the underground church. China's official
Catholic church claims more than 3 million members.
   An undetermined number of Protestants also hold illegal services
at ``house churches'' because they reject the government-run
Protestant church organization.
   Foreign Catholic and Protestant groups supply underground
worshipers with Bibles and other religious materials carried in by
tourists.
   China and the Vatican have held behind-the-scenes talks for
several years but do not appear near reaching agreement on
rapprochement.
</TEXT>
