<DOCNO> AP890215-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SoutheasternForests     02-15 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Southeastern Forests,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservation Group Criticizes Government Handling of National Forests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 11 a.m. EST Wednesday; time set by source.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM E. SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government must stop trying to turn national
forests in the mountains of southern Appalachia into tree farms,
says a conservation group which calls the U.S. Forest Service's
plans for them ``seriously flawed.''
   The service's plans for the six forests in Virginia, the
Carolinas, Tennessee and Georgia ``continue to threaten the region's
environment'' with extensive clearcutting, road construction and
other actions, the Wilderness Society said in a report released
today.
   The government must begin developing a regional approach to
protecting the forests, which offer recreational and wildlife
benefits not found anywhere else in the area, the Washington-based
group said.
   ``We want them to manage them as an ecosystem, not just isolated
units,'' said Peter Kirby, the society's Southeastern regional
director.
   Sen. Wyche Fowler, D-Ga., chairman of the agriculture
subcommittee on conservation and forestry, said in a statement that
he was greatly disturbed by the report, ``Mountain Treasures At
Risk,'' and his panel would examine some of its findings.
   The report, released today at the group's southeastern regional
headquarters here, covers the Jefferson National Forest in Virginia,
the Cherokee, Pisgah and Nantahala in Tennessee and North Carolina,
the Sumter in South Carolina and the Chattahoochee in Georgia, which
essentially surround the Great Smoky Mountains National Park.
   The forests cover about 4,700 square miles, roughly the size of
Connecticut.
   ``The Wilderness Society maintains that plans for the Southern
Appalachian national forests are seriously flawed,'' the report said.
   While demand for wilderness recreation is increasing, the Forest
Service plans to designate 60 percent of the areas suitable to be
made wilderness areas as suitable for timber production instead, the
report noted.
   In the past decade, the service doubled the volume of timber sold
from the six forests, from 63 million board feet in 1977 to 126
million in 1986. Plans call for doubling it again in 10 years and
increasing it more than 350 percent by 2030.
   The forests provide essentially the only wilderness areas in the
region. The service plans to build roads and cut old trees in remote
areas which do not yet have official wilderness designation from
Congress and are essentially the only old-growth forests in the area.
   It plans to build 3,263 miles of roads, which are built for
logging, in addition to the current 4,951 miles. Balancing the cost
against the sale price, the agency reported a $5.5 million loss on
timber sales from the six forests in fiscal 1987, the report said.
   The service itself has admitted private forests could produce the
timber it sells, the report said.
   The study said the service views wildlife management ``primarily
as an adjunct of timber production'' in each individual forest when
a regional approach is needed.
   The society recommended an outside task force to evaluate the
service's plans, establishing more wilderness areas, phasing out
timber sales, stopping road construction, reforming forestry
practices and restructuring the agency's budget to provide more
balance among the uses of the forests.
   The Forest Service has previously defended its handling of
national forests by pointing out that they have multiple uses:
logging, recreation and wildlife management.
   ``We get confused with national parks that are managed strictly
for non-timber purposes,'' Cherokee National Forest planning officer
Bob Larkey said after conservationists appealed the plan for that
forest in 1986. ``It's very difficult to give everybody what they
want.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890215-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--BusFlip     02-15 0116</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Bus Flip,0119</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thirteen Killed As Bus Flips Into Ditch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crowded bus traveling in southern China
flipped over into a deep ditch, killing 13 people and injuring 33,
according to an official Chinese report that appeared today.
   The accident occurred early Tuesday in Zengcheng county about 40
miles northeast of Canton, the capital of coastal Guangdong
province, the China News Service said in a report appearing in Hong
Kong newspapers.
   The pro-Beijing Wen Wei Po newspaper said the bus, which was
traveling from Jieyang county in northeastern Guangdong to Canton,
was carrying 50 people, or five more than its capacity.
   An initial investigation indicated the brakes failed, the
newspaper said.
</TEXT>
