<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     02-15 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Lonesome Dove' Rounds Up CBS' Highest Weekly Rating in Two Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was ``The Case of the Much-Watched
Miniseries,'' and Perry Mason came to the defense of NBC.
   Because of the unexpected success of CBS' Western miniseries
``Lonesome Dove,'' NBC fully expected to come in second after
winning 33 consecutive weeks in the A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings.
   NBC led by less than a rating point going into Sunday, CBS' best
night for ratings. But ``Perry Mason: The Case of the Lethal
Lesson'' defended the network against CBS' weaker made-for-TV movie,
``Outside Woman,'' and NBC eked out a tie with CBS for first place
for the week.
   The final episode of ``Lonesome Dove'' was last week's
highest-rated, prime-time show. The four-part series corralled CBS'
highest rating in two years.
   Monday's and Tuesday's installments of the eight-hour miniseries
landed in the top 10. But `Mason' and `Cosby,' et al, helped NBC
extend its unbeaten streak to 34 weeks.
   ``The Cosby Show'' was on twice last week and came in second and
third. There was a special Monday episode as part of NBC's
programming against ``Lonesome Dove.''
   ``Lonesome Dove, Part 4'' had a 27.3 rating and 41 share. The
miniseries wound up with a four-night average rating of 26.1 and a
39 share, good enough for 14th on the all-time-high miniseries list.
It is the highest-rated multi-part movie in 4{ years. The first
night of the miniseries, on a Sunday, was included in the previous
week's Nielsens.
   Each rating point represents 904,000 households with televisions.
The share is a percentage of sets in use.
   NBC also expected trouble because President Bush's address to
Congress pre-empted more than an hour of its high-rated Thursday
lineup.
   NBC and CBS had a 16.7 rating for the week; ABC 12.8. It as CBS'
highest since March 1987. Thanks ``Lonesome Dove,'' the three
networks had their highest combined share of the season, 72,
compared with the season-to-date average of 68.
   Last week's top 10 shows were: ``Lonesome Dove, Part 4,'' CBS;
``The Cosby Show,'' NBC; ``The Cosby Show Special,'' NBC; ``Lonesome
Dove, Part 3,'' CBS; ``Roseanne,'' ABC; ``60 Minutes,'' CBS; ``A
Different World,'' NBC; ``Golden Girls,'' NBC; ``Lonesome Dove, Part
2,'' CBS; and ``ALF,'' NBC.
   ABC's new ``Columbo'' premiered Monday against ``Lonesome Dove''
and NBC's special comedy lineup, but came in a respectable 26th with
a 16.3 rating.
   NBC couldn't count the whole rating for ``L.A. Law'' on Thursday,
because 25 minutes of it was after prime time, and it ended up 25th,
the first time in recent memory it's been out of the top 20.
   In the news category, CBS won the week with a 12.0 rating and a
20 share. ABC and NBC were in a virtual tie, with an 11.0 and a
10.9, respectively, and a 19 share each.
</TEXT>
