<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-15 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges, Stocks Hit Another Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged against the Japanese yen for the
second consecutive day today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's
leading index climbed to another record high in active trading.
   The dollar closed at 125.90 yen, down 1.30 yen from Tuesday's
close of 127.20 yen and down 2.40 yen from Monday's finish. It
opened at 126.30 yen, the day's high, and plunged at one point to
125.80 yen.
   The U.S. currency thus has fallen 4.50 yen since hitting this
year's highest close of 130.40 yen on Feb. 1.
   Dealers said the dollar's decline today was due to growing
pessimism in the market over U.S. trade figures to be announced
later this week.
   They added that the weaker dollar led to expectations of a
sell-off by investment trusts before they closed their books for the
year at the end of March.
   Exchange dealers said volume totaled $10.582 billion, second
largest this year. The previous high of $10.70 billion was set
Friday, when the dollar fell 1.74 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Average, a
2.43-point loser Tuesday, gained 166.59 points, or 0.52 percent,
closing at a record 32,149.48 points.
   Stock traders said volume was estimated at 1.6 billion shares in
the first section, compared with 1.56 billion Tuesday.
   Individual and foreign investors showed strong buying interest,
with their concern over political uncertainty linked to the
so-called Recruit scandal apparently subsiding, the traders said.
   Prosecutors have arrested several people, including Hiromasa
Ezoe, founder of the information services conglomerate Recruit Co.,
on suspicion of giving bribes by offering bargain-priced stock to
influential politicians and businessmen. The scandal has rocked the
government of Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita.
</TEXT>
