<FIRST>r a PM-People-HastyPudding     02-15 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Hasty Pudding,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kathleen Turner Gets 1989 Hasty Pudding Award</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Movie heartthrob Kathleen Turner accepted
the Hasty Pudding Theatricals' 1989 Woman of the Year wearing a
rhinestone tiara and garlanded in a string of sizzling, sexy
adjectives.
   Ms. Turner joined in a chorus of ``Wild Thing'' and engaged in
off-color banter with the Harvard University students who since 1951
have given the award annually to the performer ``who makes a lasting
and impressive contribution to the world of entertainment.''
   The students suggested the title of Tuesday's ceremony should
have been, ``Peggy Sue gets verbally lambasted by a bunch of
snot-nosed Harvard guys.''
   They compiled a list of adjectives to describe Ms. Turner: ``Hot,
steamy, smouldering, sizzling, torrid, blazing, sweltering,
simmering, seething, balmy...''
   ``Oh, that was Sesame Street,'' the actress interrupted.
   Ms. Turner made her 1981 film debut in ``Body Heat,'' starred in
``Peggy Sue Got Married'' and was recently featured in ``The
Accidental Tourist.'' She also was the voice of Jessica Rabbit in
the cartoon, ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' in which her most
memorable line was: ``I'm not bad; I'm just drawn that way.''
   Ms. Turner said her roles in ``Accidental Tourist'' and ``Roger
Rabbit'' may compete for this year's Academy Awards.
   ``I'm told I may be up against myself for supporting actress as
both Sarah and Jessica Rabbit,'' she said before accepting the small
brass Hasty Pudding pot.
   Asked by reporters about her throaty voice and faintly foreign
accent, Ms. Turner replied, ``It's because I grew up in South
America and England and because I'm a little affected.''
   Ms. Turner said she plans to start rehearsals in December for a
New York stage production of Tennessee Williams' Cat on a Hot Tin
Roof, in which she will plays the part of Maggie.
   Before the ceremony, Ms. Turner was paraded through Harvard
Square on the back of a 1947 Lincoln Contintental convertible.
Wearing a red dress and rhinestone tiara, she was flanked by male
Harvard students in drag, a tradition that dates back to the days
when the university's constitution forbade men to wear women's
clothes.
   Previous recipients of the award include Lucille Ball, Katherine
Hepburn, Meryl Streep and Elizabeth Taylor.
   Actor Robin Williams is scheduled to accept Hasty Pudding's 1989
Man of the Year Award on Feb. 21 at the opening of the annual
student production, ``Whiskey Business.''
</TEXT>
