<FIRST>r i PM-Vietnam-USDoctors     02-15 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-US Doctors,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Doctors Go To Vietnam To Perform Plastic Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first organized group of American
doctors to go to Vietnam since the war ended in 1975 left for that
country today to perform surgery on children with congenital mouth
deformities.
   The first 12 members of the 34-person surgical team, which
includes plastic surgeons, anesthesiologists and pediatricians,
departed for Vietnam's capital of Hanoi. The rest are to join them
Saturday.
   The group, ``Operation Smile,'' is one of various charitable
groups responding to the U.S. government's recommendation that
Vietnam be given private aid in humanitarian fields.
   At the Olof Palme Institute for the Protection of Children in
Hanoi, the Americans will spend the first three days examining young
children whom Vietnamese doctors screened for the free operations.
   They will stay in Hanoi until Feb. 25, performing reconstructive
surgery to correct cleft lips and palates and burned scar
contractures, said chief surgeon Dr. Craig Merrell, spokesman for
the Norfolk, Va.-based non-profit group.
   ``When you fix the face of a child, nobody can take that away
from him ... he's changed forever,'' said one group member, Dr.
Frank Yeiser.
   ``If we can begin by helping each other through the face of a
child, then let us try,'' Yeiser quoted a Vietnamese plastic surgeon
as saying on a recent exchange program to the United States.
   The United States and Vietnam do not have diplomatic relations,
but Washington has encouraged more humanitarian aid since Vietnam
pledged in August 1987 to speed up an accounting of Americans
missing from the war.
   The Americans are taking to Vietnam hundreds of thousands of
dollars worth of surgical equipment and medical supplies, mostly
donated by large American pharmaceutical companies. Some items will
be donated to the hospital there.
   In Hanoi, seven plastic surgeons will operate on six patients at
a time for five days, adding up to some 400 man-hours, Merrell told
a news conference.
   Group members who left for Hanoi today included Dr. Craig Merrell
of Chesapeake, Va.; Yeiser of Norfolk; pediatrics dentist Dr. John
Moffitt of Spokane, Wash.; pediatrician Dr. Mike Solhaug and
clinical nurse specialist Valre Buchholz, both from Virginia Beach,
Va.; and Vietnam war veteran Steve Hayes, from Washington, D.C. who
was to handle logistics.
   They are to be joined Saturday by William Magee, the founder of
Operation Smile and Mary Stout, president of the Vietnam Veterans of
America.
   Solhaug, a former combat soldier in Vietnam, said he had ``mixed
emotions'' about returning to the country.
   But going back as a pediatrician presents a ``marvelous
opportunity to revisit my old memories .. a sort of dangerous
prospect on one hand and yet a healing process,'' he said.
</TEXT>
