<FIRST>r p PM-AlabamaPrimary     02-15 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alabama Primary,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Runoff Will Pit Secretary Of State, Tuskegee Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State Glen Browder led a
Democratic primary election but will face a runoff with Tuskegee
Mayor Johnny Ford, who is seeking to become Alabama's first black
congressman since Reconstruction.
   The winner of their March 7 runoff will face Republican state
Sen. John Rice in a special election in the 3rd Congressional
District, which stretches through the mostly rural counties to the
east and north of Montgomery.
   The April 4 election is being held to select a successor to
Democratic Rep. Bill Nichols, who died in December at age 70 after
serving 21 years.
   Browder, 46, a former Jacksonville State University professor who
vaulted from the Legislature to his statehouse post in 1986, edged
Ford by a 25-to-24 percent margin in Tuesday's primary despite
trailing in district-wide surveys in recent weeks.
   ``It was a very competitive campaign,'' Browder said. ``Nobody
walked away with this race. I respect Mayor Ford very much, and I
think that we'll have a pretty sprited campaign.''
   Ford, 46, ran strongly in predominantly black Macon County and
drew well enough elsewhere to beat out state Sen. Jim Preuitt of
Talladega and state Rep. Charles Adams of Phenix City.
   ``We obviously received overwhelming support from the
African-American community, which is good,'' Ford said Tuesday
night. ``Now that we're in the runoff ... much of the quiet white
support we got will come out openly.''
   Rice, 37, seeking to claim a traditionally Democratic district,
said the general election race will pit a conservative against a
liberal.
   The Opelika real estate developer won his GOP race without a
runoff, pulling about 62 percent of the vote.
   Blacks make up about 25 percent of the district. The last time a
black won a primary runoff spot for Congress in Alabama was in 1978,
when Chris McNair of Birmingham ran against the eventual winner,
Richard Shelby of Tuscaloosa, in the 7th District.
</TEXT>
