<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0552EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BhopalSurvivors     02-15 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bhopal Survivors,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors Welcome Cash Settlement But Skeptical</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHARAT DESAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shantytown dwellers who lost loved ones when
deadly gas from a Union Carbide plant enveloped the neighborhood in
1984 say the $470 million settlement the company has agreed to is
not punishment enough.
   ``We have often been promised money, but for us it was more
important that those who killed our brothers and sisters should be
hanged,'' said Sunil Kumar.
   The 15-year-old Kumar lost his parents and five siblings to the
cloud of methyl isocyanante that escaped from a storage tank in the
world's deadliest industrial disaster.
   At least 3,329 people died from exposure to the gas released from
a pesticide plant owned by the Danbury, Conn.-based company's Indian
subsidiary.
   The government says at least 20,000 survivors still suffer
shortness of breath, eye problems and other ailments.
   On Tuesday, the Supreme Court of India ended four years of legal
wrangling and ordered Union Carbide to pay the $470 million in
compensation.
   The settlement was acceptable to both the company and India,
which had sought $3 billion.
   Today, the court agreed to advance the date of payment from March
31 to March 23 and to allow the company's Indian subsidiary to pay
$45 million of the settlement with the parent company responsible
for the remaining $425 million.
   The news was slow to sink in at the Jai Prakash Nagar shantytown
across the road from the deserted Union Carbide plant, which closed
after the Dec. 3, 1984, gas leak.
   Kumar still lives with a younger brother in the shack where his
family slept as the white killing vapor wafted across the teeming
squatter settlement.
   This morning, he was studying for high school examinations _ one
of the few teen-agers in the shantytown who can afford not to work.
   He achieved this relative affluence soon after the disaster when
the Indian government gave next-of-kin 10,000 rupees (then worth
$833) for each gas death in the family. Kumar received 70,000 rupees.
   Throughout the shantytown today, many people seemed unable to
comprehend what the settlement would mean for them.
   One man, Shanker Lal, said there had been promises of money in
the past but he had yet to receive anything.
   At a hospital near the camp, Shaukat Bai, a veiled woman in her
mid-20s, waited for treatment for respiratory problems blamed on the
gas. Pregnant at the time of the disaster, she lost her unborn child
in a miscarriage health workers blamed on the gas. Her husband was
killed by the gas.
   ``Union Carbide should have been stripped of its assets,'' she
said. She said she thought pregnant women who suffered miscarriages
or gave birth to stillborn babies should be given compensation.
   Local politicians who crusaded on the victims' behalf were more
vehement.
   ``The Rajiv Gandhi government has committed an inhuman crime by
undermining the extent of the disaster,'' Giriraj Kishore, president
of the Slum Dwellers Federation said, referring to the prime
minister and his Congress Party.
   Satinath Sarangi, a scientist and member of the Bhopal Group for
Information and Action, said: ``This settlement is the final
testimony to the anti-people collusion between the government of
India and the Union Carbide Corp.''
   Alok Pratap Singh, a leader of the Poisonous Gas Episode Struggle
Front that often organized anti-Carbide demonstrations, called the
$470 million agreement ``a shameless settlement.''
   Vibhuti Jha, a young lawyer for the front, said the government
had committed a ``criminal offense'' by agreeing to drop criminal
charges against Union Carbide, its Indian subsidiary and corporate
officials.
   Warren Anderson, chairman at the time of the gas leak, and eight
officials of Union Carbide of India Ltd. were charged in 1987 with
culpable homicide in the disaster.
   They never appeared for trial, and the Supreme Court quashed the
charges when it ordered Union Carbide to pay the ``full and final
settlement.''
   Dainik Bhaskar, a Bhopal daily newspaper, called the settlement
``niggardly and inadequate'' and said it set a dangerous precedent
for the Third World where ``people are considered guinea pigs by the
multinationals.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890215-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0553EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChicagoSymphony-Barenboim     02-15 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicago Symphony-Barenboim,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barenboim Charts Path for Post-Solti Chicago Symphony Orchestra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Symphony may have made its reputation
playing Mahler, Wagner and Beethoven, but it will make contemporary
works an important part of its future, says newly appointed music
director Daniel Barenboim.
   The 46-year-old Barenboim, meeting with reporters for the first
time since being named Jan. 30 to replace Sir Georg Solti in
September 1991, said he doesn't plan any sweeping changes.
   But, he added, ``I don't want to pay lip service to contemporary
music ... and I don't expect everybody to agree with my choices and
like them. ...
   ``If we are limited to the music of the past, all our
institutions ... (will become) like well-equipped museums.''
   Barenboim said he has planned world or American premieres for
each of the five subscription weeks that he will work as a guest
conductor next season.
   In March for instance, the CSO under Barenboim's guidance will
play four works by composer Maurice Ravel, but also unveil a work by
Toro Takemitsu commissioned in honor of the orchestra's centennial.
   Barenboim cautioned Tuesday he won't undertake the new works
simply to tinker.
   After spending the last 13 years as musical director of
L'Orchestre de Paris, a post in which Solti also preceded him,
Barenboim has nothing but the utmost respect for the master. Solti,
who led the CSO since 1969, will become conductor laureate beginning
with the 1991-92 season.
   ``Because of its association with Sir Georg, I find an orchestra
at a level of excellence that is very rare and it would be
presumptuous of me to say I'm going to change that,'' said Barenboim.
   ``But it is also true that when you find something very good, you
cannot simply hope to gain hold of it and keep it like that. There
is a fluidity to life as well and it is important to keep that in
mind,'' Barenboim said.
   At the hour-long news conference, Barenboim was asked repeatedly
whether there had been a resolution of his much-publicized dispute
with officials of the Bastille Opera in Paris.
   Barenboim was fired last month as musical and artistic director
at the new Paris opera house, losing a salary of $1.1 million over
four years, as well as the chance to guide the ambitious project in
its infancy.
   He declined to discuss the matter in detail, but hinted that one
of the Mozart operas that was being considered for the opening of
the Paris opera house may well wind up elsewhere.
   Barenboim _ born in Argentina and raised in Israel _ was already
a world-famous pianist when he performed as a guest conductor in
1970 with the Chicago Symphony.
   ``My weaknesses are known to them, their strengths are known to
me,'' he said of the Chicago musicians. ``That should augur well for
the future.''
</TEXT>
