<DOCNO> AP890215-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0554EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MiamiVice     02-15 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miami Vice,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miami Bids Vice Fond Goodbye?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vice that made Miami famous was celebrated by
fans, city officials and the show's cast in a gala that may well
have served as a joyous wake for television detectives Sonny
Crockett and Rico Tubbs.
   The 100th show of ``Miami Vice'' was broadcast Feb. 10 amid
complaints by critics that, after five seasons, the NBC series has
lost its spirit of innovation and zest.
   But it remains popular enough in its home city that this week was
declared Miami Vice week. The crowning event was a party Tuesday
night.
   Several hundred people gathered at the Biltmore Hotel in Coral
Gables wearing everything from formal wear to jeans and high-topped
tennis shoes. They watched fireworks, met the cast and craned their
necks for Don Johnson, who played Crockett, and fiancee Melanie
Griffith, the star of the film ``Working Girl.''
   The publicist for both said earlier in the day that they are
expecting a child. However, the publicist, Elliott Mintz, said
rumors they would marry on Valentine's Day were untrue. He said no
date has been set.
   ``Miami Vice'' catapulted Johnson, co-star Philip Michael Thomas
and several other regulars to stardom.
   For years it stayed near the top of the ratings and
revolutionized men's fashion, television filming techniques, and
rock music scores for television.
   Olivia Brown, featured regularly on the show, said executive
producer Michael Mann encouraged creativity on the set and made it
fun.
   ``They allowed each of us to take chances,'' she said. ``It's
been the best experience of my life. I'm gonna cry a lot when it's
over.''
   Thomas, who played the cool and savvy Tubbs, said he doesn't plan
to leave Miami and hopes a theater he's starting here will help
other young actors get an opening.
   Emmy-winning actor Edward James Olmos, Lieutenant Castillo on the
show, told the crew goodbye, saying he was off to Poland to work on
a movie about the Nazi death camp Auschwitz.
   ``Tomorrow is my final day on Miami Vice,'' he said. ``I will put
to rest Lieutenant Castillo.''
   But Johnson and some others were not so willing to say last rites.
   ``I have learned very definitely in this business, never say
never,'' Johnson told his fans and coworkers. ``This isn't goodbye.
This is a celebration of 100 shows. We'll see what happens after
that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
