<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0554EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HealthCare     02-15 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Health Care,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Most Americans Dissatisfied With US Health Care System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A vast majority of Americans favor a major overhaul
in the U.S. health care system, according to the first simultaneous
study of Canadian, British and U.S. attitudes about the issue.
   ``Americans apparently are so frustrated and discouraged with
their existing health care arrangements that a large majority say
they would favor a system like that in place in Canada,'' Robert J.
Blendon, chairman of the Department of Health Policy and Management
at Harvard University's School of Public Health, said Tuesday.
   Eighty-nine percent of Americans said there is room for a major
overhaul in the U.S. system, according to the Louis Harris survey
commissioned for Health Management Quarterly.
   Given a description of the Canadian and British systems, 61
percent of Americans said they would prefer to adopt the program
used by their neighbors to the north and 29 percent said they would
opt to try the British system, according to the poll.
   ``Americans are clearly disenchanted with the direction of their
nation's recent health policies, despite the fact that the United
States spends more for health care than Canada or Great Britain,''
said Blendon, principal analyst of the survey.
   About 7.5 percent of surveyed Americans also reported they were
not receiving necessary medical care for financial reasons, whereas
fewer than 1 percent of Canadians and Britons said financial
constraints kept them from obtaining care.
   Combined public and private funding provide the U.S. system's
foundation. Canadian health care is totally underwritten by the
government-funded national health insurance system. Under the
British National Health Service, doctors and hospitals work for and
are funded by the government.
   Only 3 percent of Canadians and 12 percent of the British said
they would prefer the U.S. system, the study said.
   The survey, which has a margin of error of 5 percentage points,
polled a nationwide cross-section of 1,250 adults in America, 1,026
Canadians and 1,667 Britons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
