<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     02-15 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady In Late Morning European Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was trading today at lower levels in
thin late morning European dealings.
   Gold prices fell.
   The dollar was being undermined by a growing feeling that any
discount rate hike by the U.S. Federal Reserve would be matched by
the West German Bundesbank, said one trader with a major Italian
commercial bank in Milan.
   In addition, it was being pressured by statements by President
Bush indicating he wasn't unduly worried by inflation fears, he said.
   ``Bush's statement was received fairly neutrally in Europe on
Tuesday, but not in New York, they really sold the dollar off,'' the
trader said.
   The dollar has been strong recently, primarily due to
expectations of a tighter monetary policy by the Fed.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 1.30 yen to close at 125.90 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 126.10 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8408 West German marks, down from 1.8615
   _1.5622 Swiss francs, down from 1.5815
   _6.2650 French francs, down from 6.3325
   _2.0782 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1015
   _1,342.25 Italian lire, down from 1,355.05
   _1.1830 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1835
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7730 from $1.7588 Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $382.75 a troy ounce,
down from $386.25 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $381.70.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $381.85, down from $385.50 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $4.02 to close at a bid $384.66.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.79 a troy ounce,
down from Tuesday's $5.83.
</TEXT>
