<FIRST>r a PM-MiamiRiot     02-15 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miami Riot,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Shooting Victim's Family Files $10 Million Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of a motorcycle passenger who was killed
in the incident that touched off three days of race riots last month
has filed a $10 million lawsuit against the city.
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court by the family of Allan
Blanchard, accuses Miami police of allowing a pattern of activity
that has violated suspects' civil rights during the past decade.
   Tuesday's lawsuit names as defendants the city, Mayor Xavier
Suarez, Police Chief Perry Anderson and his department, and Officer
William Lozano, a Hispanic who shot the driver of the motorcycle on
which Blanchard was riding.
   Also Tuesday, Anderson said he will not consider a request by
Hispanic officers for reassignment from black neighborhoods because
of tension following the shooting of the black motorcyclist.
   ``They have a responsibility as police officers to serve this
community, even throughout the rough times,'' Anderson said. ``I
would never even contemplate any type of reassignment.''
   An attorney for the Hispanic Officers Association had written a
letter to Anderson complaining that tension for Hispanic officers in
black neighborhoods ``is becoming unbearable.''
   Miami police say 25 Hispanic officers work in the Liberty City
and Overtown sections, two predominantly black areas where looting
and violence erupted after the shooting of motorcyclist Clement
Lloyd on Jan. 16.
   In the lawsuit, attorney Mark Rubin said Blanchard, who also was
black, was the victim of wrongful death and deprivation of civil
rights. He was fatally injured in an accident that immediately
followed Lloyd's shooting.
   In describing the alleged pattern of police behavior, Rubin cited
the 1979 police beating death of a black insurance executive, the
1986 drownings of three drug suspects and the 1988 police shooting
of a black man who washed car windshields for money.
   Lozano pleaded innocent Monday to criminal charges of
manslaughter with a firearm in the deaths of Lloyd, 23, and
Blanchard, 24. A June 19 trial date has been set.
</TEXT>
