<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0713EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Khrushchev'sSon 1stLd-Writethru a0466 02-15 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Khrushchev's Son, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0466,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khrushchev's Son Says Misunderstanding Plagues Superpower Relations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 17th graf, `Sergei Khrushchev ...', with 5 grafs to UPDATE
with report of planned U.S. attack on Cuba; deletes last 4 grafs to tighten</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sergei Khrushchev was on a roll.
   The son of former Soviet Premier Nikita Khrushchev was telling a
story about a bit of advice his father once gave him. He looked up
at the audience, chuckled, paused for effect ...
   And the translator muffed the punch line.
   Though flustered by the audience's silence, the 54-year-old
Soviet computer scientist really could not have made his point more
eloquently.
   He was giving a news conference Tuesday on his first trip to the
United States in 30 years, and the main thrust of his remarks was
that Soviets and Americans still have great difficulty understanding
each other.
   ``It seems to me that the main thing is, we've come to understand
how poorly we actually understand each other, and those
misunderstandings have led to missteps even at the highest levels,''
he said.
   It is a point of particular importance to Khrushchev these days,
because he has been vigorously denying American news reports that he
said Cuban leader Fidel Castro urged his father to launch a nuclear
strike on the United States during the 1962 Cuban missile crisis.
   Those reports came out of a historic three-day conference in
Moscow last month that brought Soviet, Cuban and American
policymakers from that era together to discuss the missile crisis.
   Several newspapers reported that Sergei Khrushchev dropped a
bombshell on the conference by privately telling participants that
on Oct. 26, 1962, near the height of the crisis, Castro sought a
pre-emptive nuclear strike on the United States to forestall what he
believed was an imminent invasion of Cuba.
   After the translator botched Khrushchev's story Tuesday, the
Soviet said he thought a similar loss in translation may have
resulted in the disputed reports from Moscow.
   David A. Welch, a Harvard research fellow who attended the
conference, gave a possible explanation for the reports.
   He said many U.S. scholars believe Castro asked for Soviet troops
to fire anti-aircraft missiles at American military jets flying over
Cuba.
   ``When someone said Castro asked Khrushchev to fire the missiles,
(journalists) may have thought he was talking about the nuclear
missiles,'' Welch said.
   Welch added, however, that ``I wouldn't rule out entirely the
possibility that Castro asked for a nuclear strike ... If Castro did
make that request, it would be a politically very awkward fact to
admit.''
   The Moscow conference was the culmination of a six-year Harvard
study of the missile crisis, which brought the superpowers to the
brink of nuclear war as President John F. Kennedy ordered a naval
quarantine of Cuba and demanded that the Soviets remove their
nuclear rockets from the island.
   The world sat glued to televisions and radios as Soviet ships
steamed toward the quarantine line and what seemed like an
inevitable military confrontation. But Nikita Khrushchev eventually
backed down and pulled out the missiles in return for an American
pledge not to invade Cuba.
   The Boston Globe reported today that the United States was
considering attacking Cuba and had aircraft and ammunition in place
before the Soviet missiles were discovered there.
   One document said plans for an air attack, an invasion or both
were finished and troops were ordered into final readiness for
combat between Oct. 8 and Oct. 12, 1962, the Globe said.
   Robert S. McNamara, secretary of defense at the time, and
McGeorge Bundy, Kennedy's national security adviser, have said the
administration had no thoughts of invading Cuba at the time.
   The newspaper said it got a copy of the report from Graham
Allison, dean of Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government,
where Khrushchev spoke.
   Sergei Khrushchev, whose father died in 1971, said Tuesday that
the crisis illustrated the danger of misunderstandings between the
superpowers. He also said there is a better opportunity today than
at any time in the past 25 years for an improvement in
Soviet-American relations.
   ``In the past, unity between peoples was considered science
fiction. But today, we see that as a real possibility,'' he said.
</TEXT>
