<SECOND>PM-Stepfather Charged,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Given Life Prison Term For Sexually Assaulting Stepdaughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been sentenced to life in prison for
sexually assaulting his 9-year-old stepdaughter, a leukemia victim.
   Authorities say the 31-year-old man, whose name was withheld to
protect the victim's identity, assaulted the girl several times,
including once while he was free on bond awaiting sentencing on a
charge of sexually assaulting her.
   He pleaded guilty to two counts of sexually molesting his
daughter. State District Judge Frances Maloney announced the
sentence Tuesday.
   Defense lawyers had asked that the man be placed on probation so
that he could get psychological help, but prosecutor Lynne Cartsunis
had asked for the life term.
   The sentence was ``completely appropriate for what he did to this
child,'' Cartsunis said. ``I hope it tells that child and other
children that they will be protected from this kind of abuse.''
   The man, who lost his job as a baggage handler for American
Airlines following his arrest last December, had pleaded guilty last
September to fondling the child four times between July and October
1987. But he was allowed to remain free on bond while awaiting
sentencing.
   When authorities discovered that he had allegedly raped the girl
in November, Maloney ordered him arrested and set his bond at
$500,000.
   The man testified Monday that the attacks were a form of
``compassion'' that ``went the wrong way.''
   He agreed to plead guilty to the charges stemming from the
attacks in 1987 and last November in a deal that prosecutors said
would keep the child from having to testify against him. The only
issue during the trial was the length of his sentence.
