<FIRST>r a PM-HackerJailed     02-15 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hacker Jailed,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Whiz Gets Prison Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has sentenced a teen-ager to nine
months in prison for tapping into U.S. military computers and
copying highly sensitive computer programs valued at $1.2 million.
   Herbert Zinn Jr., 18, of Chicago, was also ordered Tuesday by
U.S. District Judge Paul Plunkett to pay a $10,000 fine and serve 2{
years' probation.
   Zinn was 17 when he broke into computers at AT&amp;T, NATO and the
Defense Department. His case is one of the first ever brought under
the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of 1986.
   ``Our intention is to prosecute such cases aggressively in the
future,'' said U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas.
   In sentencing Zinn, Plunkett said he hoped that the young man's
brush with the law would direct his extraordinary computer skills
toward legal outlets.
   Zinn was convicted Jan. 23 of breaking into AT&amp;T and U.S.
government computers in three states, illegally copying more than
$1.2 million worth of computer software, and of illegally publishing
computer passwords on computer bulletin boards in Chicago and Texas.
   Court documents indicate that Zinn, a high school dropout who
used the name Shadow Hawk, broke into AT&amp;T computers in suburban
Naperville and New Jersey, as well as NATO computers run by AT&amp;T in
Burlington, N.C., and at Robbins Air Force Base in Georgia. The
intrusions took place from July to September 1987.
   Zinn stole an estimated 55 computer programs, including complex
programs relating to artificial intelligence and computer designs,
according to the court documents. No classified materials were
obtained, but the government regards the programs obtained by Zinn
as ``highly sensitive.''
   By entering the computers, Zinn caused $174,000 worth of damage
to AT&amp;T equipment, according to the court documents.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney William Cook said Zinn obtained access to
the AT&amp;T computers from underground computer bulletin boards.
   Zinn was uncovered in 1987 when AT&amp;T security officials spotted
his telephone number and his messages in the computer bulletin board
system.
</TEXT>
