<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka-Election 1stLd-Writethru a0494 02-15 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0494,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Extremists Kill At Least 47 During Balloting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with polls closed, higher death
toll, other details. Picks up graf 15 pvs `The United....' DELETES grafs
20-21 pvs to TRIM</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese gunmen killed the son of a
Cabinet minister and at least 46 other people today, but millions of
people voted for a new Parliament despite the violence, officials
said.
   Police shot and killed at least seven Sinhalese extremists who
tried to disrupt voting at various places across the country, police
reported. Tamil militants killed two other people, the police said.
   An estimated 65 percent of 9.3 million eligible voters cast
ballots by the time the polls closed, according to Deputy Election
Commissioner Lakshman Perera. No results are expected until Thursday.
   Only 55 percent of those eligible cast ballots in the
presidential election last December.
   More than 1,000 people, including 14 candidates, have been slain
since campaigning started Jan. 6. Sinhalese and Tamil militants
vowed to disrupt the election and threatened to kill voters.
   Both groups oppose a plan to grant the country's ethnic Tamil
minority greater autonomy. The Sinhalese say it is too generous, and
the Tamils say that it is inadequate.
   More than 80,000 soldiers and policemen took up positions across
the island to ensure calm balloting, government officials said.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa predicted victory for his United
National Party in the 225-seat Parliament where it has held a strong
majority.
   ``We have given maximum protection to the voters,'' Premadasa
told reporters as he walked 500 yards to a Colombo polling station
to cast his ballot.
   A few hours later, police reported that Jayantha Mallimarachchi,
son of Fuel Minister Weerasinghe Mallimarachchi, was killed when
Sinhalese extremists ambushed his jeep in a Colombo suburb.
   They said the extremists killed 46 other people in a series of
election day attacks across the Sinhalese heartland of central and
southern Sri Lanka.
   The victims included two election officials and a soldier whose
jeep was ambushed while they were taking ballot boxes to a polling
center near Bandarawela, 80 miles east of Colombo, the police said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Five other election officials were reported missing after their
two jeeps and several ballot boxes were found burned in the
Mahiyangane district in the middle of the island nation.
   Police blamed all the attacks on the People's Liberation Front, a
Sinhalese group.
   The United National Party held 139 of the 168 seats in the
outgoing Parliament. The chief opposition group, former Primer
Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike's Sri Lanka Freedom Party, held only
eight.
   Smaller parties and independents had the rest.
   Sinhalese militants oppose the elections as part of an
anti-government campaign launched in July 1987.
   They say the government gave away too much to autonomy-seeking
rebels of the minority Tamil community in a largely unsuccessful
attempt to bring an end to the six-year-old Tamil insurrection.
   The elections also are opposed by the Tamil guerrillas, who are
fighting for an independent homeland in the north and east.
   Tamils form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and say
they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who make up 75
percent of the population and control the government and military.
</TEXT>
