<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   02-15 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0518,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Least 40 Killed In Battles Between Army, Christian Militiamen</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout with Moslem forces declaring support for Aoun, details
on battle. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 40 people were killed today in
tank and artillery battles between army troops and Christian
militiamen in east Beirut and the hills above the capital, police
reported.
   A communique from the army command of Gen. Michel Aoun said seven
soldiers and officers were killed, 14 were wounded, and three were
missing and presumed kidnapped in the latest battle for control of
Lebanon's Christian heartland.
   Police said most of the other casualties were from the Lebanese
Forces, the main Christian militia in the nearly 14-year-old civil
war against the Moslems. They said at least 90 people were wounded.
   Maj. Gen. Sami Khatib, who commands Moslem units of Lebanon's
divided army, declared support for Aoun, saying ``the Lebanese
Forces are our common enemy.''
   Khatib's statement was broadcast by Moslem-controlled radio
stations. He has about 22,000 soldiers under his command. Aoun has
an estimated 20,000 Christian soldiers under his command.
   Fires burned out of control as tank-led Christian army units
rolled down from the central mountains into east Beirut behind a
heavy barrage of artillery on the militia's seaside war council
command headquarters, police said.
   The stench of cordite wafted across the city.
   Police said Aoun's units drove the Lebanese Forces from their
main barracks in east Beirut's densely populated Ein Rummaneh
district and circled another barracks in the sprawling Ashrafiyeh
neighborhood.
   ``The army is pushing hard to capture the whole of east Beirut,''
said a police spokesman, who under standing rules could not be
identified.
   He said the army was trying to seize sections of the northern
coastal highway to block the Lebanese Forces' supply routes between
their strongholds of Byblos and Jounieh.
   The spokesman said army commandos stormed the headquarters of the
Lebanese Forces' French-language newspaper Le Reveil in east Beirut
and also flushed out militiamen from villages around the mountain
towns of Souk el-Gharb, Beit Meri and Bekfaya above Beirut.
   Christian militiamen mounted grenade assaults on army barracks in
Sarba and a nearby air base in the coastal town of Edma, 15 miles
north of Beirut, a police spokesman said.
   Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir, spiritual guide of the dominant
Maronite Catholic community to which most of the belligerents
belong, appealed for a cease-fire.
   ``From the hell of this disastrous bloody battle throughout the
Christian hinterland, we appeal to the warring brethren to stop
shooting at once and allow peace negotiators to avert further
bloodletting and destruction,'' Sfeir said in a statement.
   The command of the 6,000-strong Lebanese Forces, which is led by
Samir Geagea, announced its ``full preparedness to abide by a
cease-fire on all warfronts.''
   Aoun's command in suburban Yarze, five miles east of Beirut, said
the general told the patriarch also was willing to stop shooting.
   Fighting subsided after the announcements, but police said the
lull was short-lived, and fierce battles broke out at midday.
</TEXT>
