<FIRST>r a PM-GreylordSentence     02-15 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greylord Sentence,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Judge Caught in Court Scandal Sentenced to Six Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former judge was sentenced to six years in
prison for paying bribes, becoming the 15th former judge punished in
the Operation Greylord crackdown on court corruption.
   James Oakey, 57, told U.S. District Judge James Holderman before
sentencing Tuesday that he had ``sunk as low as I can sink.''
   ``It's a terrible way to end a legal career,'' said Oakey, a
former Cook County circuit judge.
   Under a plea-agreement, Holderman could have sentenced Oakey to
up to eight years in prison on racketeering charges involving bribes
he admitted paying to the former chief judge of the Traffic Court,
Richard LeFevour.
   LeFevour was convicted of corruption in another Greylord case and
is serving a 12-year federal prison sentence.
   In 1982 and 1983, Oakey had left the bench and was practicing
law. He admitted paying $200 to $300 a week so he could drum up
business from defendants in the courtrooms.
   Oakey said he started hustling defendants in the courtroom after
he lost his judgeship in 1975, following allegations that he had an
improper relationship with a private security firm.
   However, Assistant U.S. Attorney Scott Mendeloff said the
prosecution had evidence that Oakey was taking money to fix cases
even while on the bench.
   Mendeloff said nearly 100 people have been sentenced in the
Operation Greylord investigation of corruption in the Cook County
court system.
   Oakey's six-year sentence will run concurrently with an 18-month
prison term he is already serving for tax evasion.
</TEXT>
