<FIRST>r a PM-Kemp 1stLd-Writethru a0426 02-15 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kemp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0426,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Promises Vigorous Effort to Expand Housing Stock</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with Kemp speech; picks up 2nd graf pvs, Areas
that were. Removes last 2 grafs pvs to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   HUD Secretary Jack Kemp, taking a first-hand look
at inner city problems, said today he was ``committed to a vigorous
effort to expand the housing stock, both public and private.''
   Kemp told a meeting of black Atlanta leaders arranged by Coretta
Scott King, ``There are fiscal restraints I am going to be
considerate of...but we're going to make a difference.''
   Mrs. King, widow of the slain civil rights leader Martin Luther
King Jr., said, ``From everything we've heard you say, we think you
mean business. If something happens and there is not a
follow-through, you're going to have a lot of disappointed people.''
   Kemp said he hoped to expand affordable housing for low-income
people through both federal projects and incentives to encourage
private development.
   On Tuesday, Kemp offered tax incentives and enterprise zones to
fight ``distress and despair'' among the urban poor, but made no
promise to spend more on housing as he toured this city's poor
sections.
   ``Areas that were at one time redlined for despair need to be
greenlined for success,'' Kemp said Tuesday, referring to the
practice by lenders of refusing to grant housing loans in
neighborhoods they considered undesirable.
   Kemp was spending a second day today visiting Atlanta's poor
neighborhoods on what he said was the first in a series of visits to
troubled inner cities as the administration's new secretary of
Housing and Urban Development.
   He was led on his tour by the city's black Democratic leadership,
including Mayor Andrew Young and Rep. John Lewis on Tuesday, and
today was being shown more troubled areas by Coretta Scott King,
wife of the late Martin Luther King Jr. He also met with community
leaders and developers.
   ``We've had a national recovery, but folks have been left
behind,'' said the former pro football player, congressman and
unsuccessful Republican presidential candidate.
   ``There is distress and despair in many of those areas of the
economy that have been left behind, and that's where I definitely
want to focus my attention,'' he said.
   Kemp brought the leaders no pledges of more federal money for
permanent housing, which the nation's mayors have said is needed to
fight homelessness. But he said he would push for ``dramatic
incentives'' to attract business investment into inner cities, and
consider other innovative public and private inducements to bring
jobs and housing to blighted areas.
   He said he would seek enactment of specific tax incentives,
including breaks on capital gains, to create the urban enterprise
zones in troubled inner cities. The tax breaks would be contingent
on the businesses hiring people who otherwise would be on welfare
rolls.
   Congress has passed enterprise zone legislation, but without the
tax incentives. President Bush's 1990 budget proposal includes such
tax incentives.
   Some of the redeveloped projects Kemp visited were accomplished
with local versions of that _ abatements in property taxes.
   ``We've got to do it at the federal level because only the
federal government can provide dramatic incentives,'' he said.
   Kemp was warmly greeted and met bipartisan encouragement,
although several local leaders suggested there were needs that
exceeded the ability of enterprise zones.
   Eugene Bowens, president of Interfaith Inc., a church group, said
that around the country many 15- to 30-year agreements with owners
of existing subsidized rental housing are due to expire soon. As a
result, the units could no longer be available to low-income people.
   ``That is a big problem and it's going to be happening on my
watch,'' Kemp said, adding that he wants to find ways to
``reincentivize'' both taxes and housing.
</TEXT>
