<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-Carter,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carter Hails Soviet Pullout As Victory For Democracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Carter, who protested the Soviet
Union's invasion of Afghanistan by keeping U.S. athletes out of the
1980 Olympics in Moscow, called the Soviet pullout a victory for
democracy.
   As the last Soviet troops left Afghanistan aboard military
transports Tuesday, Carter said in a prepared statement that the
Soviet occupation was wrong from the beginning.
   ``The Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in December 1979 was an
international tragedy,'' Carter said. ``The heroism of the Afghan
men and women who fought against foreign subjugation has forced
Soviet forces to withdraw in defeat.''
   The former president said the U.S. support given to the Afghan
rebels was vital to their success.
   ``I am proud of the support the United States gave from the
earliest day to those who offered their lives for freedom,'' Carter
said. ``We now hope that they and their fellow citizens can forge a
society based on peace, justice and democracy.''
