<FIRST>r i PM-Mandela 3rdLd-Writethru a0562 02-15 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mandela, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0562,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Announce Murder Inquiry in Mandela Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with detention of man with Mrs.
Mandela. Pickup 4th pvs, `Police said... </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A murder investigation has been
launched in the death of a boy who allegedly was abducted and beaten
at the home of black activist Winnie Mandela, police announced today.
   Mrs. Mandela met for 80 minutes at a prison farm near Cape Town
with her husband, African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela.
She refused to disclose any details of their conservation when she
returned to Johannesburg with her daughter, Zindzi, later in the day.
   As she was driven away from Johannesburg's airport, police
stopped the mini-bus she was in and took into custody a young man
who had met her. Police said only that the man, whose name was not
disclosed, was needed for questioning. Mrs. Mandela raised no
objections, according to journalists who saw the incident.
   While the Mandelas were meeting at the prison farm, police
headquarters announced that the body of a boy found in Soweto last
month had been positively identified as Stompie Seipei. The boy, 14,
allegedly was abducted and beaten at Mrs. Mandela's house by young
men who have served as her unofficial bodyguards.
   Police said a murder investigation would be conducted because the
decomposed body appeared to have stab wounds in the neck. All people
who might be able to assist the investigation would be questioned,
police headquarters said without elaborating.
   Mandela's husband is serving a life sentence for planning
anti-government sabotage. He heads the outlawed African National
Congress.
   Mandela United is a soccer club whose young members have served
as Mrs. Mandela's bodyguards in Soweto, the black township outside
Johannesburg.
   Methodist Church officials and Soweto community leaders have
alleged that members of Mandela United abducted three young men and
Seipei from a church residence, then beat them.
   The three men, according to their attorney, have made statements
saying Mrs. Mandela was ``involved in the events'' on the night they
were allegedly abducted and taken to her home.
   Mrs. Mandela, an anti-apartheid activist in her own right, has
denied she was present. She said the soccer club took the four from
a Methodist Church residence to protect them from sexual abuse, a
charge church officials say is false.
   The African National Congress has called publicly for the
disbanding of Mandela United.
   Maj. Gen. Jaap Joubert, who heads the police investigation of the
case, said today that fingerprint experts had been able to identify
a body at a Soweto mortuary as Seipei. Earlier, Joubert has said the
body appeared to have two stab wounds in the neck.
   He said the body was found in a field in Soweto after police
received an anonymous phone call Jan. 6.
   A Johannesburg newspaper on Tuesday quoted an unidentified
witness as saying one of the young men living at Mrs. Mandela's home
had been hacked to death in Soweto on Monday.
   Police said they were investigating the possibility that a young
man found dead of multiple stab wounds may have been a Mandela
United member.
   The Star newspaper said the dead man was Maxwell Madondo, 19, who
had been staying at Mrs. Mandela's house.
   The Star quoted an unidentified youth as saying he saw a crowd of
youths attack Madondo with pick handles, then drag his body into a
house, where he was stoned.
</TEXT>
