<FIRST>r a PM-ChurchProtest     02-15 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Church Protest,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priest at Center of Controversy In Seclusion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A priest whose transfer sparked a sit-in
at a largely Polish Roman Catholic Church has been ordered back to
Poland, but a small group of dissenting parishioners vowed to stage
a hunger strike tonight.
   The Rev. Roman Palaszewski has been ordered by the head of the
Franciscan order in Krakow to return to Poland in an attempt to
defuse tensions at St. Michael's, a friar at the order's provincial
headquarters in Baltimore said Tuesday.
   The friar, an assistant to the Very Rev. Daniel Pietrzak, head of
the Franciscan province that includes St. Michael's, said the
telegram sent within the past two days was a ``last resort.''
   ``We're all free to do wrong,'' the friar, who declined to give
his name, said of Palaszewski. ``He obviously has a decision to
make.''
   Palaszewski has been in seclusion since about 100 dissident
pashioners, angered by his removal in December, began occupying the
church in shifts on Saturday. Neither church officials nor the
dissidents have revealed Palaszewski's whereabouts.
   But Halina Chmiel, one of the leaders of the dissidents, said
Palaszewski told her that he had received no telegram ordering him
back to Poland.
   Two members of the dissidents plan to start a hunger strike
tonight, she said.
   ``They said they will sacrifice their lives for the rest of the
parish,'' Chmiel said.
   The dissidents vow to remain in the church until Bridgeport
Bishop Edward Egan agrees to meet with them. They want Palaszewski,
who spent three years at St. Michael's as an associate pastor,
reassigned to their church and want the present pastor, the Rev.
John Bambol, removed.
   The dissidents claim Bambol engineered Palaszewski's removal
because he was too active in the Polish community. Some say they are
upset by Bambol's efforts to open up the parish, located in a
largely Hispanic section of Bridgeport, to other ethnic groups.
   Palaszewski's five-year contract was terminated late last year by
joint agreement between Franciscan officials in Baltimore and
Krakow, the friar in Baltimore said. He was asked to return
voluntarily to Poland at the time, but failed to comply, the friar
said.
</TEXT>
