<DOCNO> AP890215-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 1200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   02-15 0852</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0894</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout
the nation.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 10
   St. Cloud (Minn.) Times on John Tower as defense secretary:
   The first vote on John Tower's nomination as secretary of defense
has been put on hold for two weeks while the FBI reviews new
allegations about his finances and excessive drinking.
   Tower has vowed to stick with the fight for Senate confirmation.
That's a mistake. He should withdraw and allow (President) Bush to
submit another nomination.
   Many of the allegations against Tower may well prove to be
unfounded. But there have been enough serious questions about his
character that it is doubtful that he could function effectively in
one of the nation's most vital Cabinet positions. ...
   Tower has not been convicted of any misdeeds. But questions about
his personal life and hints and allegations of conflicts of interest
have not subsided. If anything, they grow as time passes.
   The result is a dangerous void in one of the nation's most
important leadership roles. Even if he survives confirmation,
lingering doubts will impair his ability to lead for many months, at
best.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 11
   The Milwaukee Journal on congressional pay raises:
   Congressional leaders, having taken a beating in the recent
pay-raise controversy, seem to have concluded that their present
method is doomed.
   Adopted 22 years ago, the plan was supposed to spare lawmakers
direct responsibility for setting their own pay. A bipartisan
commission would recommend salary increases, if deemed appropriate,
once every four years _ subject to paring by the president and
passive acceptance by Congress.
   As it turned out, however, lawmakers did not get credit for
letting someone else decide what their pay should be.
   Far from it. They were accused in various quarters of cowardice
and subterfuge for ``not having the guts'' to vote on their own
salaries. ...
   The Senate and House, working with the president, need to search
for an alternative.
   We believe the method Wisconsin uses is part of the answer.
Technically, at least, the lawmakers in Wisconsin do not give
themselves a raise. Voters have the opportunity to throw them out of
office before the salary increase takes effect.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 9
   The Westerly (R.I.) Sun on mob justice:
   What happened to a mugger who got caught in Brooklyn's close-knit
Williamsburg section ... tells us again that when people take the
law into their own hands ... the consequences may also be criminal.
   A man who held up another at knifepoint ... and slashed his face
when he resisted was chased by a crowd of some 50 people and beaten
unconscious.
   Should a mob, even well-motivated against crime, ... have meted
out this rough justice?
   This society long ago established the principle ... that it is
the function of the police to apprehend suspects and of the courts
to determine their guilt or innocence.
   That angry crowd ... should have grabbed him and held him for the
police. That, in sum, is what the rule of law is all about.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 11
   The Arizona Republic, Phoenix, Ariz., on drug tests of nuclear
plant employees:
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission is headed in the right
direction with its move toward a rule requiring random drug and
alcohol testing of employees at all U.S. nuclear power plants.
   Given the risks and the magnitude of mishaps, it is frightening
to think that workers at such critical jobs would not be closely
monitored, and certainly the monitoring should include regular
checks for evidence of substance abuse.
   Implementation of the proposed regulation, which would apply to
all utilities operating or building atomic power stations, hinges on
final approval by the NRC, which is expected to rule in about a
month, and official publication of the rule, which could take an
additional month.
   The possibility _ more likely a probability _ also exists of a
time-consuming legal challenge.
   The federal government's plans for random drug testing seldom go
unchallenged by civil libertarians, and that is fine, provided the
courts do not lose sight of the public safety.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 9
   The Charleston (W.Va.) Gazette on affirmative action:
   Predictions that President Reagan's appointees to the U.S.
Supreme Court would undercut affirmative action proved partly
correct last month.
   In its ruling on a Richmond (Virginia) case, the court slightly
curtailed this discrimination remedy, and perhaps opened the door to
future assaults.
   The Richmond City Council had set aside 30 percent of all
municipal contracts for minority firms. ...
   The high court scuttled the Richmond law, decreeing that state
and local governments can't establish set-asides without first
proving past discrimination and their predecessors' responsibility
for it _ a tough task.
   Further, the city or state cannot establish quotas or goals.
   Writing for the majority, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor warned that
set-asides will be subject to ``strict scrutiny.''
   Justice Thurgood Marshall, in a biting dissent, ... said the
court is ``constitutionalizing its wishful thinking'' which assumes
that racial equality has been achieved in America.
   That's not so. Until it is, affirmative action will continue to
be unequal but necessary.
</TEXT>
