<HEAD>UNDATED: moving again.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 12
   The Miami Herald on Bush's address to Congress:
   The tone was kindler and gentler, but the underlying economic
message of President Bush's budget address to Congress (Feb. 9) was
the familiar supply-side voodoo.
   Those facts likely mean that the rhetoric between the White House
and the Capitol will be softer than in recent years, but the
prospect for stalemate is as strong as ever. ...
   The voodoo comes in the fact that ... Bush hopes to keep his
no-taxes pledge by simply projecting a whopping $80 billion growth
in Federal revenues from exisitng sources.
   Given the $150 billion deficit in foreign trade, the $100 billion
emergency in the savings and loan industry, the festering wound of
unpayable debts owed by Latin America to U.S. banks, and early signs
of creeping inflation, that projection looks wildly optimistic.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 13
   The Meridian (Miss.) Star on higher taxes:
   House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill.,
is a true Democrat. He wants higher taxes.
   Congressman Rostenkowski said Sunday that President Bush should
look to gasoline, tobacco and alcohol as possible vehicles for
higher taxation as Congress begins work on the government's 1989-90
budget. ...
   Never mind that the president, both in his 1988 campaign for
election and since taking office, has vowed that he will not go
along with new taxation.
   Never mind, either, that ... Bush already has presented the
Congress with a plan showing how the new budget can be funded
without new taxes. ...
   Despite the voter mandate, the Democratic Party's prescription
for government financing has not changed one iota. It is to
tax-and-tax, spend-and-spend. So far as it is concerned, there
apparently is no limit.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 8
   The Hudson Dispatch, Union City, N.J., on FBI bungling of a
kidnap case:
   Somebody needs to say it: Irving Flax probably would be alive
today if it weren't for the FBI's handling of the (New Jersey) case.
   The kidnapped warehouse supervisor was alive when his wife paid a
$25,000 ransom late last month. Within four hours, the 58-year-old
was killed execution-style.
   (The FBI's) first mistake was failure to notify Paramus police of
the imminent pickup of the ransom money at a borough diner _ clearly
a dangerous situation, and the FBI obviously could have benefitted
from the help and expertise.
   After the pickup, FBI agents could have arrested the kidnapper.
Incredibly, they passed up the chance, then lost the car.
   The suspect in the case, John M. Martini Sr., was apprehended not
by the FBI, but by Fort Lee Police.
   Arrogantly, the FBI _ which could be called the Federal Bureau of
Ineptitude for its actions _ works in a vacuum, assuming a false
superiority and slighting local law enforcement agencies. ...
   FBI agents have bungled dangerous situations and heightened
potential danger to the public.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 8
   The Joplin (Mo.) Globe on Bill White as National League president:
   It seems fitting the search committee that selected Bill White, a
black man, as the National League's next (president) was headed by
Peter O'Malley, owner of the Los Angeles Dodgers.
   For it was a former Dodgers official, Al Campanis, who stood the
game on its ear with his remark that blacks could never attain top
positions in baseball because they were unequipped for management.
   The decision to choose White ... should help silence the
criticism that baseball has refused to extend to minorities the
opportunities for top executive positions.
   Talent is the key to the selection. The owners didn't choose
someone as head of the National League just because he was black.
Rather, the choice was predicated on the ability of the man to
handle the high responsibility of the task. ...
   In short, Bill White fills the job description of National League
president nicely, thank you, and is what the game needs.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 11
   Portland (Maine) Press Herald on wrestling as entertainment, not
sport:
   Professional wrestling, it turns out, is just an
``entertainment'' and not a dangerous sport at all. The admission
comes from no less than the World Wrestling Federation.
   Talk about a drop kick in the abdominal area.
   It's near impossible to believe. ... You mean those terrifying
choke holds, those vicious body slams, those flying body presses
launched from the top of the ropes are all just fun and games?
   Apparently. The WWF concedes as much in legislation it is
supporting in New Jersey in order to win exemption from regulations
that apply to boxing and other sports that can cause serious
physical injuries.
   It wants professional wrestling defined as ``an activity in which
participants struggle hand-in-hand primarily for the purpose of
providing entertainment to spectators rather than conducting a bona
fide athletic contest.''
   Arrgh.
</TEXT>
