<FIRST>u a PM-Explosion     02-15 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Explosion,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosion At Explosives Plant; Seven Suffer Minor Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPANISH FORK, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion and fireball rocked an
exlosives plant early today, injuring seven people and damaging four
buildings in a blast felt 10 miles away, authorities said.
   ``I thought it was a little tremor,'' said Brendon Nichole, an
engineer at radio station KHON in Spanish Fork, about two miles from
the Trojan Corp. explosives plant at the mouth of Spanish Fork
Canyon.
   The explosion at 6:37 a.m. was felt as far away as Provo, about
10 miles to the north, and there were several reports of cracked
windows in Spanish Fork and Mapleton, said Utah County sheriff's
Sgt. Craig Turner.
   Witnesses described the blast as a ball of fire that melted the
snow on a mountainside.
   A bus carrying three workers was about 50 yards away when the
blast occurred, Turner said. Those three workers and four others
either outside or in nearby buildings were injured. All the injuries
were minor.
   Five people were treated at Mountain View Hospital in Payson,
said Pam White, hospital public relations coordinator.
   The sheriff's office reported the fire under control shortly
before 8 a.m., but people were not allowed in the 100-acre plant
because of the potential for other explosions.
   Workers later secured the plant and chemists and engineers
planned to enter it and stabilize chemicals, Turner said.
   ``It may take quite some time,'' he said.
   The cause of the explosion, which occurred in an unoccupied
building where primers were manufactured, was not immediately known,
Turner said.
   The primers are replacements for dynamite and made of TNT and a
chemical called PETN, he said.
   Calls to the company were referred to plant managers, who
declined to comment.
</TEXT>
