<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 1304EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sakharov     02-15 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharov Says He's Quitting Race for a Territorial Parliament Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Human rights campaigner Andrei D. Sakharov said in
a letter published Wednesday he is withdrawing from the race for a
territorial seat in a new national legislature.
   Sakharov's letter, published in the weekly Moscow News, said he
would not accept nominations from territorial districts because he
believes he should represent the Academy of Sciences.
   The prestigious academy, where Sakharov works as a nuclear
physicist, last month rejected proposals to throw his hat in the
ring as its representative in the new 2,250-seat Congress of
People's Deputies. The 67-year-old dean of the Soviet human rights
movement was nominated to represent a Moscow district, but many of
his scientific colleagues wanted him to represent them in the new
congress.
   Sakharov, who won the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize, said he agreed.
   ``I feel that I am inseparably linked with the academy, of which
I have been a member 35 years,'' Sakharov wrote. ``I have come to
the conclusion that I should be a candidate namely of the academy in
the new elections or not be one at all. Therefore, I am taking the
decision not to run anywhere except the Academy of Sciences of the
U.S.S.R., withdrawing my consent to run from all territorial and
national-territorial districts which fielded my candidacy.''
   In a letter accompanying Sakharov's in Moscow News, space
scientist Roald Sagdeyev said he supports his colleague's decision
and hopes the academy leadership will reverse its decision and
``find a way'' to nominate Sakharov. Sagdeyev was also passed over
as an academy nominee.
   Sakharov is visiting Canada, where he has given conflicting
signals about whether he will continue to seek a Congress of
People's Deputies seat. On Sunday, he told reporters in Ottawa, ``I
don't reject the idea that I will still be a candidate in the
election.''
   More than 1,000 Academy of Sciences workers rallied Feb. 2 to
protest the organization's rejection of the candidacies of Sagdeyev,
Sakharov and several other prominent intellectuals. The protesters
charged that the academy leadership failed to listen to the popular
will in rejecting the nominations.
</TEXT>
