<DOCNO> AP890215-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 1313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-PanchenLama     02-15 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panchen Lama,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memorial Caps Transformation of Panchen To National Hero</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top government and Communist Party leaders paid
lavish tribute Wednesday to the late Panchen Lama, who used his
influence as Tibetan Buddhism's No. 2 leader to support Chinese rule
in Tibet.
   Party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang, Premier Li Peng and other
top officials stood with bowed heads in front of a portrait of the
Panchen Lama, capping the official transformation of him in death
into a national hero and symbol of ethnic unity.
   The Panchen Lama ``took a clear-cut stand of patriotism for
decades, particularly in the fight against the separatists on the
Tibetan issue,'' Vice President Wan Li said in eulogy to about 1,000
government and religious leaders at the Great Hall of the People.
   It is rare for a dead official, even one of high rank, to be
honored with such a lavish memorial at the Great Hall.
   The Panchen Lama died Jan. 28 at age 50 of a heart attack. He was
a vice chairman of the National People's Congress, China's
legislature, as well as the highest-ranking Tibetan Buddhist monk in
China. The Dalai Lama, the faith's top leader, has lived in exile in
India since a failed 1959 Tibetan revolt against China.
   ``His death means the loss of a great patriot and statesman to
our country, a devoted friend to our party and an outstanding
patriotic religious leader to the Tibetan people,'' the official
Xinhua News Agency quoted Wan as saying.
   The memorial, parts of which were shown on TV, was closed to
foreign reporters. Reporters also have been barred from attending
ongoing mourning services for the Panchen Lama in Tibet.
   Tibetan officials tightly restrict foreigners' access to Tibet
for fear they will witness demonstrations of anti-Chinese sentiment,
periodically reported by travelers.
   After nearly 40 years of Communist rule in Tibet, China remains
in tenuous control of the Tibetan people. Despite a heavy military
presence, revolts have broken out sporadically. Three large-scale
protests and many smaller ones have been held in the capital, Lhasa,
in the past 1{ years.
   Many Tibetans argue that they have their own language, culture
and religion and wish to be left alone.
   The Panchen Lama, by virtue of his religious role, was the only
Tibetan who supported Chinese rule and still held the respect of the
people. He was regarded as the 10th incarnation of the Buddhist god
Amitabha.
   His death leaves the government without a credible foil to the
Dalai Lama, who has sharply criticized the Chinese for human rights
abuses in Tibet.
   The only other Tibetan with a high post in the Chinese government
is Ngapoi Ngawang Jigme, 78, also a congress vice chairman. He was
an aristocrat and official in the pre-Communist Tibetan government
who declared allegiance to the Chinese soon after their troops
entered Tibet in 1950. He has no strong following among Tibetans.
   Although he has opposed calls for Tibetan independence, the
Panchen Lama spoke out several times against what he considered
harsh treatment of his people. In one of his last speeches, he said
Tibetans had paid too high a price for their development under
Chinese rule, and that communist mistakes outnumbered their
successes in Tibet.
   The comments were reported in the official media at the time, but
have not been mentioned since his death. Instead, the Panchen Lama
has been turned into a symbol of loyalty to the Chinese motherland.
   The party newspaper, the People's Daily, carried a full-page
tribute to him Wednesday, referring to him as the ``great Panchen.''
   The government has indicated it will allow religious officials to
carry out the traditional method of selecting a new Panchen Lama by
identifying his reincarnation in a child. However, it has said the
choice must be approved by the government.
   Tibetan officials have refused to say if the process has begun.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890215-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 1426EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People-Reagan     02-15 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Reagan,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phone Harassment Complaint Dropped Against Reagan's Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Reagan, son of former President
Reagan, won't be prosecuted for making a threatening telephone call
to a photographer because he has apologized to the man, the city
attorney's office said Wednesday.
   A prosecutor dropped the misdemeanor telephone harassment case at
the recommendation of a hearing officer who listened to Reagan
apologize for leaving an obscenity-laced message on the answering
machine of Roger Sandler.
   ``In the hearing officer's opinion, the dispute was resolved at
the hearing,'' said Mike Qualls, spokesman for the city attorney's
office.
   Reagan was not available for comment, said his spokesman, Dale
Olson. He previously apologized for any embarrassment the incident
brought on his family.
   The complaint against Reagan, 43, the adopted son of Ronald
Reagan and his first wife, actress Jane Wyman, involved a dispute
over the use of two of Sandler's pictures in Reagan's 1988 book,
``On the Outside Looking In.''
   Sandler is seeking $1,500 for alleged copyright infringement
because he wasn't given credit and because he says he didn't give
permission for the photos to be published.
   In the Jan. 15 telephone message, Reagan threatened Sandler and
ended with the words: ``I hope your ... family dies in a plane crash
with you in it.''
   The prosecutor's office considered filing a misdemeanor charge of
making an annoying phone call, which carries up to a year in jail
and a $1,000 fine.
   The Feb. 7 session before hearing officer was conducted under
routine procedures intended to resolve minor cases without charges
or court hearings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
