<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 1427EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bush     02-15 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says He and Congress Will Make `Hard Choices' on Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Wednesday his new
budget plan will force Congress and the White House to make ``hard
choices'' on spending cuts so that more money can be targeted for
social programs, the environment, educaton and the space program.
   But Bush, speaking to the South Carolina legislature, did not
offer any suggestions about where to reduce spending. Democrats
complain that Bush is taking credit for raising spending for
domestic programs while making Congress share responsibility for
unpopular cuts.
   Bush flew here as part of a series of appearances around the
country to extol the $1.16 trillion budget he unveiled last week.
The president will travel to St. Louis on Friday for a speech and
lunch with students at Washington University.
   The expanded social programs proposed in Bush's budget would have
to be offset by up to $11 billion in spending reductions to keep the
deficit down.
   Bush got a friendly reception from the Democratic-controlled
legislature. Speaking in the cavernous, white-brick House chamber,
the president said:
   ``I speak to you in the spirit of bipartisanship. I've got to _
you've got us outnumbered.''
   Bush made a pitch for his proposed reduction in the capital gains
tax to a maximum of 15 percent. Now, capital gains are taxed as
ordinary income.
   The president said that change would spur investment and produce
more tax revenues while, at the same time, making America more
competitive in international markets.
   ``All of our biggest trading partners, including Japan and West
Germany, tax long-term capital gains modestly if at all,'' Bush said.
   Pledging anew not to raise taxes, Bush said that reducing the
deficit means the government will have to make tough choices.
   ``My budget is a realistic plan that does more for education,
more for the environment and more for the space program,'' he said.
Moreover, he said it would increase spending for Head Start, the war
against drugs, child care and other social programs.
   Bush said that projected economic growth would result in up to
$80 billion in additional tax revenue.
   But spending more on ``priority programs,'' he said, would
require that savings be found elsewhere in the budget.
   ``And I am prepared to work with the Congress to make those hard
choices,'' Bush said.
   ``We weren't sent to Washington _ any of us up there _ to sit on
our hands, either to pass the cost of indecision onto working
Americans by raising their taxes or to fail to reduce the deficit,
which will cause the cuts to be done automatically under the law,''
the president said.
   Faced with a Congress controlled by Democrats, Bush said, ``I
will seek to work'' with the House and the Senate ``not as members
of competing political parties but as cooperating public servants.''
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush's budget
chief, Richard Darman, would meet during the day with congressional
staff people to discuss Bush's budget proposal.
   ``Details are being exchanged all the time,'' Fitzwater said.
``Darman goes up there with an armload of books and numbers so
there'll be detail.''
   Fitzwater acknowledged Tuesday that the administration had not
offered a separate proposal for filling a $9.6 billion to $11
billion gap in the amount of money available to finance Bush's
domestic spending initiatives.
   Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., chairman of the Senate
Appropriations Committee, and Sen. Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., head of the
Senate Budget Committee, told Bush in a letter that if he failed to
provide more detail on areas that will need to be cut, Congress
would ``have no alternative'' but to assume that he endorses the
reductions that Reagan proposed last month.
</TEXT>
