<FIRST>r a AM-HatchetHunt     02-15 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hatchet Hunt,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kids Scramble For Hatchets On Washington's Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHOL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the 67th year, children in this little
town will celebrate George Washington's birthday with a hatchet hunt.
   The tradition is aimed at reminding youngsters of the ``little
lessons'' in the story of young Washington admitting to his father
that he chopped down the cherry tree, said Joseph Hawkins, director
of the local YMCA, said Wednesday.
   The hunt in this town of 10,000 sends about 300 youngsters
ranging from pre-schoolers to teen-agers scrambling through the
woods for two engraved hatchets and two dozen other prizes, such as
fishing tackle and portable radios.
   Finders get to keep the hatchets. The grand prizes are quite
capable of taking down a cherry tree, but no injuries have been
reported, and no one has suggested a break with the tradition,
Hawkins said.
   ``The parents have always gone along with it,'' he said. ``But of
course, after 67 years we now have a lot of the parents that took
part in the hunt when they were kids.''
   Hawkins said there have been instances when some participants
didn't take the lesson of honesty to heart.
   ``We've had some kids that tried to get into the woods early,''
said Hawkins. ``But the Fire Department monitors the situation and
when we find them we take the kids down to the police station where
they get a little talk warning them about doing those sort of
things.''
   The search is sponsored by the YMCA and the Fire Department.
Washington's birthday is celebrated on Monday.
</TEXT>
