<FIRST>r i AM-China-Defector     02-15 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Defector,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot From Taiwan Crashes in China, Requests Asylum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Taiwanese fighter pilot whose jet crashed in
China has requested asylum from Beijing, and he denied reports he
was carrying military secrets.
   Lt. Col. Lin Xianshun told a news conference in Canton that he
wanted to be a pilot in the air force of the People's Liberation
Army.
   ``I am proud to be a Chinese,'' Lin said, appearing on Hong Kong
TV Wednesday night. ``I have studied the history and geography of
the motherland since grade school ... I think coming back is better
for myself.''
   The defection is the first since China announced in September it
would abolish rewards for defecting military personnel.
   Lin, 35, met with reporters from China, Hong Kong and Taiwan at
the Pearl River Guest House in Canton, capital of the southeastern
province of Guangdong.
   China's Air Force had held Lin incommunicado since Saturday when
the crash occurred in Fengshun county, about 180 miles north of
Canton.
   Lin parachuted to safety after his F-5E fighter ran out of oil in
heavy fog Saturday. He had flown from Chihhang Air Base in Taiwan.
   Lin, who suffered minor injuries from his jump, said he decided
about a month ago to defect to China because he wanted to return to
the ancestral home of his father's family, Meixian county in
northern Guangdong.
   Lin said planned his escape for the Spring Festival holidays
because he thought his fellow Air Force officers would not be at
their most vigilant.
   He said he did not believe that his family in Taiwan would suffer
because of his action and said he would like to call them from China.
   Lin denied reports in the Taiwanese press he had brought
Taiwanese military secrets to China. He said he only had things
``absolutely necessary for flying.''
   Lin declined to comment on a Taiwanese government statement he
suffered from an ``emotional imbalance'' due to problems with his
marriage. He denied a government report that he had sinus problems
which prevented him from flying.
   In Taiwan, the Defense Ministry said Lin flew to China because of
fears that he soon would be grounded permanently and because of
serious family problems.
   The statement said Lin had been expelled from the military and a
warrant issued for his arrest. It also said the commander of the
Chihhang Air Base and other responsible officers had either been
transferred or received other penalties. It said that Lin did not
carry confidential reports to China.
   Chinese reporters said air force officials have yet to decide
whether to allow Lin to join China's military.
   Reports on the defection have been muted in the Chinese press,
which usually employs such incidents as a propaganda tool against
Taiwan. The state-run TV news did not report on Lin's news
conference.
   More than a dozen Nationalist Air Force officers have sought
asylum in China since 1949 when the Nationalists fled to Taiwan
after losing a civil war to communist forces on the mainland.
   Military officials in Taiwan said 19 military personnel have
defected from China to Taiwan since 1949. All of the 19 defected in
planes, 13 flying to South Korea.
   Taiwan still offers rewards for Chinese military defectors, but
they reduced them when China stopped its rewards.
</TEXT>
