<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan-Gromov 1stLd-Wriethru a0595 02-15 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Gromov, 1st Ld - Wriethru, a0595,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lt. Gen. Boris Gromov: Last Soviet Soldier in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to CORRECT typo in Gromov name.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gen. Boris Gromov promised his troops he would
be the last Soviet soldier to leave Afghanistan.
   He kept that promise Wednesday, crossing into the Soviet Union
over the Amu Darya bridge that links the Soviet Union to Afghanistan
at the city of Termez.
   His four years as commander of Soviet forces in the embattled
country earned him the title ``Hero of the Soviet Union'' and a
promotion to commander of the Kiev military district, the Tass news
agency said.
   The 45-year-old career soldier was met by his 14-year-old son,
Maxim, as he crossed over to Soviet soil, officially ending the
nine-year military engagement that turned into what President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev called a ``bleeding wound.''
   Gromov graduated with honors from the Kalinin Suvorov Military
School, the All-Arms Command in Leningrad and the Frunze Military
Academy before serving the first of three tours of duty in
Afghanistan, Tass said.
   ``In one of the battles, when rebels broke through to the command
post, he courageously drew regimental artillery fire on himself,
though he knew that the slightest inaccuracy could be fatal,'' Tass
said.
   Between his second and third Afghan tours, Gromov graduated in
1984 from the General Staff Academy. ``He submitted a report
requesting that he be sent back to Afghanistan,'' Tass said. ``He
was appointed commander there.''
   Gromov's wife died in a plane crash in 1985, and as he returned
to the Soviet Union, he said, ``My two sons are looking forward to
my return.''
   The general was given the title ``Hero of the Soviet Union'' for
leading an operation to unblock the Gardez-Khost highway in
Afghanistan.
   According to Tass, Gromov is well-liked by the men who served
under him and his troops were known to call him ``Dad'' on informal
occasions.
   On his arrival in Termez, he was greeted by army Gen. Valentin
Varennikov, who said, ``Boris served in Afghanistan three times. He
held different posts and distinguished himself as a man with a high
sense of duty, who works for the fulfillment of the tasks set with
minimum losses.''
</TEXT>
