<FIRST>r i AM-Lithuania     02-15 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lithuania,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lithuanians Celebrate Independence Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two days of celebrations marking the anniversary of
Lithuanian independence began Wednesday in the city of Kaunas,
despite demands by ethnic Russians the event be canceled, reform
movement sources said.
   According to the Lithuanian Information Center in New York,
15,000 ethnic Russians rallied in Lithuania's capital of Vilnius on
Sunday to protest the celebrations. They called for the removal of
the republic's government because of what they called ``nationalist
tendencies.''
   Speakers at the Sunday rally criticized the Lithuanian reform
movement Sajudis and denounced a government decree making Lithuanian
the republic's official language.
   ``Celebrations are starting now in Kaunas, where independence was
proclaimed on Feb. 16, 1918,'' Kazimeras Moteka, a member of the
Sajudis council, said in a telephone call from capital of Vilnius.
   Lithuania was a Russian province under the rule of the czars and
proclaimed its independence following the Bolshevik Revolution of
1917. But it was incorporated into the Soviet Union in 1940 under a
secret pact between the Kremlin and Germany.
   Alvydas Medalinskas, a spokesman for the movement, told the
Lithuanian Information Center the commemorative program would last
for two days and that the program was not changed because of
pressure from the Russian community.
   However, Medalinskas said, the Lithuanian government and
authorities in Moscow apparently had bowed to Russian pressure and
had scaled back planned TV coverage of the celebrations.
   Russians make up 10 percent of Lithuania's 3.7 million
population, the smallest Russian minority in the Baltic states of
Lithuania, Estonia and Latvia.
   On Monday, about 100,000 mostly ethnic Russians rallied in
Vilnius protesting the language decree adopted earlier this year,
the Communist Party newspaper Pravda said.
   ``The protesters claimed that such a decree is a violation of
human rights of non-Lithuanian people living in the republic,''
Pravda said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
