<FIRST>u a PM-SeaLions 1stLd-Writethru a0485 02-15 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sea Lions, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0485,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Latest Plan Laid For Fish-Eating Sea Lions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with morning attempts to catch
sea lions; Picks up 7th graf, `There the ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wildlife agents and dozens of news organizations
waited in boats this morning for sea lions to return to a floating
trap that officials hope will keep migrating salmon and steelhead
from becoming sea lions' lunch.
   At least a dozen sea lions were basking in the floating cage when
wildlife agents, with reporters and photographers there to capture
the battle, launched their latest plan to stop the steelhead and
salmon suppers.
   But there were too many sea lions in the cage for National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administation agents to handle so the agents
yelled and slapped the water with paddles to scare them away.
   The sea lions stop at the Ballard Locks near the canal as they
migrate from Southern California and feast on steelhead, which are
rainbow trout headed back to their native streams and rivers in
western Washington to spawn after a few years at sea. The locks, a
gateway for fishing vessels as well as migrating salmon that are
also preyed on, connect saltwater Puget Sound with freshwater Lake
Washington and Lake Union.
   Officials launched ``Operation Goodbye,'' the sixth plan in five
years, in an effort to save the valuable fish runs. Agents hope to
move the sea lions from the sound to the Long Beach Peninsula some
250 miles away.
   ``This is our best opportunity so far,'' Hal Alabaster of the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration said Tuesday.
   Wildlife officials hope to pull the door to the floating cage
shut today, then take the sea lions two at a time to a barge for
removal to a hangar at the Sandpoint Naval Base on the Lake
Washington shore, state Wildlife Department spokesman Bob Byrne said.
   There the sea lions will be tagged and equipped with radio
collars to monitor their travels after being dropped off 250 miles
to the southwest near Long Beach Peninsula, where the Columbia River
meets the Pacific, Alabaster said.
   ``We're confident this plan is going to work,'' he said. ``At the
very least it'll be a good test of how long it takes them to get
back. Some are guessing they'll beat the trucks back'' to Seattle.
   The sea lions are being tagged with colored streamers to tell if
any of the culprits returns to the locks.
   At stake is the run of 1,600 steelhead expected to approach the
locks by April, with the peak late this month or in early March. An
average of five sea lions a day has been camping in the ship canal
and near the locks, each eating a couple of steelhead daily to the
distress of fishermen who depend on the run, Byrne said.
   The ``war'' with the sea lions began about five years ago when
officials detonated noisemaking bombs to try to scare them away,
Alabaster said. But the bewhiskered diners quickly got used to the
underwater booms.
   Wildlife officials then tried playing tapes of the sounds made by
killer whales; the sea lions weren't fooled, the NOAA official said.
   Lithium fluoride, a chemical used to stop wolves from eating
sheep, was injected into some steelhead fed to sea lions. But the
seagoing predators didn't become nauseous as expected, Alabaster
said.
   Officials turned to nets to capture the sea lions, but the
mammals simply eluded them. ``They were too smart,'' Alabaster said.
   A steel mesh barrier that would let fish through but block sea
lions also proved ineffective.
   After officials tried the nets, ``Some lumber company had a
reader board and they put up `Sea Lions 4, Government 0' or
something like that,'' Alabaster said. ``It was pretty embarassing.''
</TEXT>
