<FIRST>r i AM-Sakharov-Prize     02-15 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov-Prize,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mandela, Marchenko Receive Sakharov Prizes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mandela, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Parliament on Wednesday
awarded its first Sakharov Prizes to jailed anti-apartheid activist
Nelson Mandela and Anatoly Marchenko, a Soviet dissident who died in
prison.
   Relatives represented the prize winners at the awards ceremony.
Both prizes carry $5,600 cash awards.
   Larissa Bogoraz, Marchenko's widow and a human rights activist
who spent three years in Siberian exile, accepted the prize for her
husband. She said she was proud the prize had been named after
another Soviet dissident, Nobel Peace Prize winner Andrei Sakharov.
   Mrs. Bogoraz said she hoped other Sakharov Prize winners would
have a fate ``less tragic than those of Nelson Mandela and even more
the tragic fate of my dead husband.''
   Marchenko died in a Soviet prison in 1986 after spending more
than 20 years in jail. He was a member of a group that tried to
ensure that Moscow respected the Helsinki human rights accords. His
book, ``My Testimony,'' described life in Soviet labor camps and
prisons.
   Mandela Sizwe Dalibhunya Mandela, 14, who lives in Swaziland,
accepted the prize on behalf of his grandfather.
   ``I hope that I will be allowed to visit him on my return to
South Africa to describe this ceremony and hand over this silver
medal, this scroll and check to him personally,'' the teen-ager
said. He said he hopes to visit his grandfather this week.
   Nelson Mandela, a founder of the African National Congress, the
chief guerrilla group fighting to overthrow the South African
government and end apartheid, has been jailed since 1962.
</TEXT>
