<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     02-15 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Art didn't just imitate life at the North
Carolina Museum of Art, it hatched it _ in the form of 100 praying
mantises.
   An egg sac containing the insects hitched a ride into the museum
on one of the maple saplings that artist Patrick T. Dougherty used
in his sculpture ``Shelters of Transition.''
   The museum's warm, spring-like air prompted the pecan-size bundle
of eggs to begin hatching last weekend. The first of the half-inch
critters were noticed Friday by security guards.
   Anna Upchurch, a museum spokeswoman, said the saplings had been
fumigated in the parking lot for several days prior to the
sculpture's installation, which began in mid-January. The exhibit
runs through March 26.
   But apparently the eggs survived the chemical warfare.
   The bugs posed no danger to other artwork because they eat other
insects, not canvas or plaster, she said.
   ``There is nothing for them to eat in the museum except each
other,'' Ms. Upchurch said. Praying mantises are sometimes
cannibalistic.
   As more hatched over the weekend, they were sucked into a vacuum
cleaner and released outside.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fashion statement of shorts over
longjohns has been silenced, at least for the moment, at Syracuse
Junior High School.
   The shorts just got too short, Principal James Schmidt said
Wednesday. They are allowed under school policy, if of a proper
length and type.
   ``They were wearing thermal underwear in a way you can call
extreme,'' Schmidt said.
   The principal said he believes the students tested the school
policy on shorts by pushing them to extremes of brevity. The
principal said officials will meet with students soon and work
something out that is reasonable.
   ``We're not going to stop thermals. It's just the extremes I'm
talking about,'' he said.
</TEXT>
