<FIRST>r p AM-DioGuardi     02-15 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DioGuardi,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spokesman Says Disputed Contributions Returned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Joseph DioGuardi, R-N.Y., has
returned more than $50,000 in disputed campaign contributions to
employees of a New Rochelle, N.Y., auto dealership, a spokesman for
the ex-congressman said Wednesday.
   ``The contributions in question all came in December 1987, and
all those were returned,'' said Kieran Mahoney, DioGuardi's former
administrative assistant who now is a consultant and lobbyist.
DioGuardi was defeated last year by Democrat Nita Lowey.
   According to DioGuardi's year-end campaign finance report, filed
with the Federal Election Commission, People for DioGuardi returned
$39,000 in mid-December to present and former employees of Crabtree
Automotive.
   Mahoney said these were the last of the disputed contributions.
   ``In our previous report, we also listed contribution refunds to
a number of people. I don't have my files in front of me but it
totals in excess of $50,000,'' he said Wednesday.
   DioGuardi, reached at his Westchester County home, referred all
questions to Mahoney.
   DioGuardi lost the election after Gannett Westchester Newspapers
reported that employees of Crabtree Automotive had been reimbursed
for giving money to DioGuardi's campaign. Such reimbursement is a
violation of federal election law.
   Dealership owner Joseph Crabtree had been on DioGuardi's
executive campaign finance committee and quit the post after the
published report. He maintained the supposed reimbursement checks
were Christmas bonuses.
</TEXT>
