<HEAD>Bloody Night in Capital Leaves 3 Dead, 11 Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 1st and 3rd grafs to CORRECT number wounded and time frame</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men were killed and 11 other people were
wounded by gunfire in a 5{-hour period in the nation's capital,
police reported today.
   The deaths bring the District of Columbia's homicide toll so far
this year to 74, compared with 46 at the same point in 1988. The
city registered a record 372 homicides last year, most of them
drug-related.
   The shootings occurred between 6:30 p.m. and midnight _ almost
all of them in the southeast area of the city, said Officer Walter
Ferguson, a police spokesman. Nineteen people initially were
reported as wounded, but authorities later revised the figure down
to 11.
   Two men were shot to death while sitting in a car in an alley
near Capitol Hill, Ferguson said. They were identified as Anthony
Bailey and Derrick Bell, both 25 and of suburban Capital Heights, Md.
   Darnell Wells, 26, of Capital Heights, was shot to death near one
of the city's most notorious open-air drug markets and three other
men were wounded, Ferguson said. He said police confiscated a
shotgun, a machine gun, nine handguns and a quantity of cocaine at
the scene.
</TEXT>
