<FIRST>r w AM-BudgetRent-A-Car     02-15 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget Rent-A-Car,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>ADA Blasts Budget-FTC Agreement on Rental of Cars with Unrepaired
Defects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A public interest group on Wednesday sharply
criticized a proposed consent agreement between Budget Rent-A-Car
and the Federal Trade Commission that would allow Budget to rent
cars with unrepaired safety defects.
   ``The FTC-Budget solution is dumb, dangerous and potentially
disastrous,'' said Ann Brown, chairwoman of the consumer affairs
committee of Americans for Democratic Action.
   Under the proposed agreement announced Dec. 28, Budget could
choose to ignore manufacturer safety defect recall campaigns by
posting a disclaimer indicating that the affected vehicle is
``subject to a recall notice and has not been inspected or
repaired.''
   William MacLeod, director of the FTC's Bureau of Consumer
Protection, said the circumstances which gave rise to the consent
agreement dated back several years and have since been rectified.
   ``There is a procedure in place at Budget whereby these things
(safety defects) are repaired. The cars are in fact repaired
according to the recall notices,'' he said.
   Commenting on the ADA committee's statement, MacLeod said, ``it
sounds to me like they are making a controversy out of whole cloth.''
   At Budget Rent-A-Car headquarters in Chicago, spokeswoman Jody
Wilson said the company had no immediate comment on the ADA panel's
criticism of the consent agreement. She cited a press release issued
Dec. 30 by Budget, saying ``we have always provided our customers
with safe, reliable cars.''
   Ms. Brown told a news conference that ``sometimes consumer
information and even clear disclaimers provide no useful consumer
protection. This is one of the clearest examples.''
   ``When a car is known to be unsafe _ it simply shouldn't be on
the road _ no amount of nebulous warnings will protect a car renter
from a dangerous, life-threatening defect,'' she said.
   In comments submitted to the FTC, the ADA panel said it
``strongly opposes giving Budget Rent-A-Car or any other auto rental
firm an option to ignore safety recalls. It offers great risk to
customers that is not outweighed by the relatively minimal cost
savings.''
   Fred B. Goldberg, an attorney who prepared the ADA statement,
said the organization hopes that the FTC will vote to reject the
proposed consent agreement after a public comment period ends March
6.
   He noted that Budget's rental fleet includes, for example, the
1988 Buick Regal, for which five recalls were issued last year.
   ``The defects include potential disengagement of the steering
column, undesired resumption of cruise control, loss of braking
capacity, unexpected opening of the car's hood _ each of which poses
a clear safety threat,'' Goldberg said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
