<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 1946EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Mayhaw     02-15 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mayhaw,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientist Says Mayhaw Being Rediscovered As Possible Cash Crop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Can some of those fancy, expensive imported
fruits hold a candle to the down-home mayhaw?
   ``The mayhaw is a good ol' Southern crop that's been around for a
long time,'' says Jerry A. Payne, an Agriculture Department
scientist. ``Because of its tart flavor, it makes one of the best
jellies in the world. It's just now being rediscovered as a possible
cash crop from North Carolina to Texas.''
   Mayhaws grow wild in the acid soils of swamps and shallow ponds
and are about the size and color of ripe cherry tomatoes. They grow
on thorny trees that can get as high as 25 feet.
   Payne, who is with the department's Agricultural Research Service
in Byron, Ga., said in a report issued here Wednesday that mayhaws
may be catching on for a good reason: fruit sells for $5 to $8 a
gallon and the jelly for $8.50 per pint.
   Farmers and homeowners interested in planting mayhaw trees should
find them widely available in the next few years, he said. Related
to hawthorns, they can live 50 years or longer and remain
productive. Some varieties, once established, can withstand subzero
temperatures without damage.
</TEXT>
