<FIRST>u i AM-Mandela Bjt   02-15 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mandela, Bjt,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigate Killing of Teen Allegedly Held at Mandela Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police began an investigation
Wednesday into the death of a 14-year-old whose body was found early
last month after he allegedly was beaten at the home of
anti-apartheid activist Winnie Mandela.
   Police and community leaders say the youth, Stompie Seipei, led a
``children's army'' of 1,500 black children in the Tumahole township
of the Orange Free State and became a legend in the racial unrest of
1984-87. He was jailed under emergency rules at age 10, the youngest
of the thousands detained, and held for 11 months.
   Mrs. Mandela had an 80-minute meeting Wednesday at a prison farm
near Cape Town with her husband, African National Congress leader
Nelson Mandela.
   When she returned, police stopped her van on the highway and
impounded it. Mrs. Mandela, her daughter and granddaughter hitched a
ride with a journalist to her home in Soweto, the huge black
township outside Johannesburg.
   Police took a young man accompanying them into custody but
released him later.
   Capt. R.H.V. Bloomberg said the van was ``impounded for
examination, for investigation in connection the murder'' of Seipei,
whose decomposed body was identified in a police morgue Wednesday
through fingerprints.
   Mrs. Mandela made no comment about the meeting with her husband
or the controversy that has surrounded her since three men told a
community meeting in Soweto last month about the alleged abduction.
   She said she did not know why police took the van and the man,
who met her at the airport and was not identified. Mrs. Mandela told
a police officer: ``We don't want any trouble.''
   The men said they and Seipei were abducted Dec. 29 and taken to
Mrs. Mandela's home. They said the boy was beaten more severely and
was taken away after a few days.
   Their attorney said Mrs. Mandela was involved in the events.
   She has denied being home at the time and said the three men and
Stompie Seipei were taken from a Methodist Church residence in
January to protect them from sexual abuse. The church denied the
charge.
   According to the three men, the abductions and beatings were
carried out by members of the group known as the Mandela United
soccer team. Mrs. Mandela formed the group in 1986 and its members
act as her bodyguards.
   Police said the boy's body was found Jan. 6 in an open field in
Soweto after they received an anonymous telephone call. The body
remained in the morgue unidentified until police began investigating
the disappearance this week.
   Soweto community leaders said Seipei, like other young activists
from the years of revolt, decided to resume his education and went
to live in the house operated by the Methodist Church, from which he
and the others were abducted.
   A murder investigation will be conducted because there appear to
be stab wounds in the neck, police said. An official statement said,
without elaboration, that all people who might be able to assist the
investigation would be questioned.
   Mandela, who was convicted of plotting sabotage a quarter-century
ago and is serving a life sentence, was transferred to a staff house
at the Victor Verster prison farm in December after recuperating
from tuberculosis.
   The government has said Mrs. Mandela is free to live with him
there permanantly or have unlimited visits, but she has said she
would make her normal 40-minute monthly visits. The meeting
Wednesday was twice that long.
   Mandela has made no statements about the controversy. The African
National Congress, the main guerrilla group fighting white
domination in South Africa, has urged that Mandela United be
dismantled.
   Mrs. Mandela often is surrounded by Mandela United members, who
wear gold, green and black track suits, but they were not in
evidence at the airport Wednesday.
   On Sunday, Johannesburg's Star newspaper said Dr. Abu Baker
Asvat, a prominent anti-apartheid physician, saw Stompie Seipei at
the Mandela home after the boy had been beaten.
   Gunmen subsequently killed Asvat at his clinic in Soweto and
police are trying to determine whether the killing was linked to the
Mandela United controversy.
   Police said Wednesday a man found dead of stab wounds Tuesday
morning in Soweto was Maxwell Madondo, 19, who lived at Mrs.
Mandela's home. The Star quoted a witness as saying a crowd of young
men hacked Madondo to death.
</TEXT>
