<FIRST>r w AM-BusinessInventories     02-15 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Inventories,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inventories, Sales Both Up in December</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories rose 0.9 percent in
December and sales increased at almost the same pace despite a
buildup in stockpiles of unsold autos as car purchases lagged, the
Commerce Department said Wednesday.
   The Commerce Department said inventories held on shelves and
backlots rose to a seasonally adjusted $760.6 billion in December,
while sales reached $508.2 billion.
   December's 0.9 percent increase in inventories followed a 0.4
percent increase in November. Sales, meanwhile, rose 0.8 percent in
December following a 0.4 percent increase in November.
   Because the rates of increase for inventories and sales closely
tracked one another, there was no change in the ratio of inventories
to sales, which stood at 1.50, meaning it would take 1.5 months to
exhaust inventories at the December sales pace.
   If not accompanied by rising sales, rising inventories can signal
economic weakness because they may lead manufacturers to order
production cuts and layoffs while they sell off reserve goods.
   Robert DeFina, senior economist for Security Pacific National
Bank in Los Angeles, said the balance between sales and stockpiles
suggests most ``businesses are in a pretty comfortable position.''
   The auto industry was an exception, with stoent
says the war left 1 million Afghans dead and sent 5 million fleeing
into Iran and Pakistan.
   Moslem guerrillas are massed around Kabul, the capital, and
Western officials believe Afghan troops left behind will be defeated
soon. The divided guerrilla leadership has been meeting to try to
coordinate a strategy.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said in Washington the
Soviet pullout marks ``a long awaited day for the Afghan people and
they can now go on to determine their own future.''
   He said the United States would not be proposing any blueprints
for the future course of Afghanistan's government.
   ``This whole struggle has been about self determination,'' he
said. ``We'll continue to be supportive of the Afghan people as they
pursue this.''
   The United States ``has supported efforts to form a broadly based
government'' in Afghanistan, he said, but it would not tell the
Afghan people how to go about it. Redman said U.S. support for the
rebels continues.
