<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan-Kabul     02-15 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Kabul,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Thanks Soviets but Calls for Future of Non-Interference</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Wednesday thanked the
Soviet Union for its help in Afghanistan but said future relations
should develop on the basis of non-interference in each other's
internal affairs.
   The last Soviet soldiers who had been fighting Moslem guerrillas
left Afghan soil earlier in the day, meeting the U.N.-mediated
deadline set by an accord signed in April.
   ``The government of the republic of Afghanistan, on behalf of the
entire people of the country, expresses its appreciation to the
people and the government of the Soviet Union for their all-sided
assistance and continued solidarity in the cause of defending
Afghanistan's national sovereignty, political independence and
territorial integrity,'' the government said.
   It accused the United States and Pakistan of ``virtually
trampling'' on the Geneva agreements that paved the way for the
withdrawal of the Soviet soldiers, who entered the country in
December 1979.
   The statement said the United States and Pakistan shraply
increased their support for the guerrillas since the accord was
signed in April.
   It said the government of President Najib was confident relations
with the Soviet Union would develop on the basis of ``friendship,
mutually beneficial good neighborliness, equal sovereignty and
non-interference in each other's internal affairs.''
   The statement also denounced the shura, or council, being held in
Pakistan by the guerrillas, who have predicted Najib's government
will fall within weeks of the Soviet withdrawal. The shura is to
coordinate their plans for a postwar government.
   ``Pakistan has been making futile efforts of late to forge
various Afghan opposition groups into a so-called shura and a
transitional government on the territory of Pakistan by exerting
enormous pressure on them ... Such hostile and expansionist schemes
which are aimed at infringing upon the independence of Afghanistan
are resolutely rejected and condemned by the people and the
government,'' it said.
   Residents of the besieged capital said they hoped the completion
of the withdrawal would lead to peace after 10 years of civil war.
   ``The Russians are gone,'' said a merchant in the city's old
bazaar who identified himself as Hasan. ``Now there will be peace,''
he said as he tried to sell one of the few Soviet fur hats left in
the shopping district.
   ``We are brothers,'' another merchant said, referring to the
Moslem guerrillas outside the capital. ``We can solve our problems
without foreigners. The problems are just between Afghans. We don't
need help from foreigners,'' said the jewelry seller, who gave only
his first name, Ghulam.
   The pullout from Kabul was completed Tuesday night when about 80
Red Army troops at the city's airport filed two-by-two onto four
military transport planes that took them home.
</TEXT>
