<SECOND>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0657,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayles Settled in at New Digs, Kids Throw Weekend Slumber Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts 2 grafs after 7th graf bgng: With the ... to move up
reference to remodeling. Deletes now redundant grafs 11-12 pvs bgng: The
remodeling ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new family on the block _ mom, dad, three
kids and a dog _ have settled into their Victorian mansion on
Massachusetts Avenue and already thrown a video slumber party to
break in the place.
   But even when you're master of the vice presidential digs, like
Dan Quayle, you find there are some things that don't change.
   Quayle, who moved his family into the vice president's official
residence a week ago, agreed to let his three children each have a
friend over for a slumber party Saturday night.
   Dad accompanied son Tucker, 14, to a local video store to pick
out the evening's entertainment. Quayle was instructed by his wife
Marilyn to ``supervise'' the selection process and to put a
two-video limit on Tucker, according to Quayle's press secretary,
David Beckwith.
   ``I guess I didn't do a very good job of supervising because he
got away with four,'' Quayle told Beckwith, adding that he stood in
line for 10 minutes to return them Sunday night.
   The comedy lineup included ``Moonstruck,'' ``Vice Versa,''
``Throw Momma From the Train,'' and ``Planes Trains and
Automobiles.''
   With the first slumber party behind them and the Quayle family
ensconced in their new home, there is remodeling yet to be done and
things to get used to _ like a staff of stewards.
   The remodeling plans are on hold pending a private fund-raising
effort being handled by a group of Quayle's friends. The work is to
include installing a bathroom for daughter Corinne since all three
children are sharing one bathroom now, redoing one upstairs bedroom
as a family room and reconfiguring the children's bedrooms on the
third floor.
   In addition, Mrs. Quayle wants a laundry room on the third floor
since she intends to do the children's laundry, according to a
spokeswoman.
   The stately three-story residence is situated on the sprawling
Naval Observatory grounds in Northwest Washington, near the British
Embassy and a tree-lined upscale residential neighborhood.
   President Bush lived there for eight years as vice president. But
while Bush and his wife Barbara often had a bevy of grandchildren
underfoot, with frequent visits by the five Bush offspring and their
families, none of the children lived with them.
   The 42-year-old Quayle brings a crew that includes Tucker and
Benjamin, 12, and Corinne, 10, and an arthritic Labrador, Madame
Justice, 14.
   The current laundry facilities are in the basement, below the
large first-floor rooms that are decorated with elegant period
furnishings and are more suited to entertaining than to family life.
   Beckwith said that for the Quayles' purposes the house is ``very
spacious. It's just not configured for a family with children at the
moment.''
   Aides to Mrs. Quayle brushed aside most questions about the
Quayles' personal lives. One aide, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Mrs. Quayle ``is very protective of their family
privacy,'' and that even though the former Indiana senator now is
vice president, ``The Quayles would like to keep their kids' lives
as normal as they can.''
   Tucker will finish out this year at Langley High School, where he
is in the ninth grade and a member of the basketball team. The
school is near the McLean, Va. house where the family lived when
Quayle was a senator.
   The other two children have switched to private schools in
Washington.
   The one family member who's having a tough time at the new house
is Madame Justice, so named because Mrs. Quayle, an attorney, got
the dog right after passing her bar.
   The dog has difficulty negotiating stairs due to arthritis and
old age. That makes it hard not only to get to the third floor where
the Quayle kids live and but also to enter and leave the house using
the porch steps.
</TEXT>
