<FIRST>u i AM-Belgium-Kidnap     02-15 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belgium-Kidnap,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kidnap Victim Recalls Four Weeks in Handcuffs, Hood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Paul Vanden
Boeynants said Wednesday he spent his month as a kidnap victim
hooded and handcuffed and never saw his captors' faces or heard
their voices.
   Vanden Boeynants described the kidnappers who abducted him Jan.
14 as ``professional criminals'' interested only in money. He said
they were well organized and operated with military discipline.
   ``My impression is that I was in France,'' Vanden Boeynants said
two days after he was freed by his kidnappers, who were paid a
ransom of hundreds of thousands of dollars.
   The wealthy businessman said his captors, possibly as many as
five, first sought a $10 million ransom but reduced the demand after
reading a newspaper article indicating he was not as rich as they
thought.
   At a news conference, Vanden Boeynants said he spent almost all
his time in captivity handcuffed and hooded. The first two weeks
were spent under threat of a gun, he said.
   The kidnappers, calling themselves the Socialist Revolutionary
Brigade, used the guise of a left-wing terrorist group to mislead
investigators and had no political motives, said Vanden Boeynants.
   ``We don't give a damn about politics. We want money,'' he quoted
them as telling him in a typewritten note.
   All communication with his kidnappers was done through such
notes, said Vanden Boeynants, 69. He said he remained calm
throughout the ordeal by repeatedly telling himself, ``You're not
going to die here.''
   He said two men attacked him the evening of Jan. 14 after he had
parked his car in the garage of his apartment building in Brussels.
   During a struggle, a third man came to help the assailants. They
pulled a hood over Vanden Boeynants' head, dragged him into a car
and drove for about 2{ to three hours.
   For the next four weeks, Vanden Boeynants said he was kept in a
darkened room in a house and always wore the hood. His handcuffs
were only taken off to allow him to eat or go to the bathroom.
   He was released late Monday in Tournai, 50 miles southwest of
Brussels, after his family paid the abductors a ransom that police
say totaled ``several tens of million of francs.'' Ten million
francs is about $250,000.
   Vanden Boeynants did not reveal the sum paid but did not dispute
the estimate given by police.
   Some newspapers reported Tuesday the ransom totaled $1.61 million.
   Vanden Boeynants was prime minister from 1966 to 1968 and again
from 1978 to 1979. He was also defense minister for seven years
during the 1970s and served as a Brussels city councilman for more
than 30 years starting in 1953.
   He received a three-year suspended sentence and was fined nearly
$17,000 in 1986 for tax fraud and forgery as head of a Brussels
meat-packing company.
</TEXT>
