<UNK>Closing Notice Posted for `Legs Diamond'</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Legs Diamond,'' the lavish Peter Allen musical
about the 1920s gangster, will close Sunday after a troubled
four-month run and a drubbing from the critics.
   The musical, which cost more than $5 million, will have played 64
regular performances and 72 previews, the show's spokeswoman, Glenna
Freedman, said Wednesday.
   ``Legs Diamond'' has been plagued by problems since October, when
its preview at the Mark Hellinger Theater was delayed a week because
of difficulty with the complicated scenery.
   The opening was postponed twice as the book by Harvey Fierstein
and Charles Suppon was extensively revised, and two performers were
written out of the show.
   The musical finally opened Dec. 26 to overwhelmingly bad reviews.
Allen, who also wrote the music and lyrics, vowed to keep the show
running.
   He reportedly took a salary cut from $20,000 to $5,000 a week.
But weekly grosses slid from $455,250 during the Christmas holiday
week to $196,283 last week.
