<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Afghanistan     02-15 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Says Soviet Pullout Official Over, But Advisers Remain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt ^By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. official who negotiated the Red
Army's withdrawal from Afghanistan said Wednesday that the pullout
was officially concluded even though some Soviet soldiers will
remain behind as advisers.
   Diego Cordovez, special U.N. representative for Afghanistan,
confirmed that more than 100,000 Soviet troops had been withdrawn by
the Feb. 15 deadline set under the U.N. agreement.
   ``Officially, I can tell you that they (the Soviet troops) have
left,'' said Cordovez, a former undersecretary-general who now is
the foreign minister of Ecuador.
   Cordovez personally negotiated the Soviet withdrawal accord among
the governments of Afghanistan, Pakistan, the Soviet Union and the
United States. The anti-Soviet guerrillas were not part of the
negotiations.
   Cordovez said the U.N. observer team in the region ``is satisfied
of the exemplary manner in which the time frame (for withdrawal) ...
has been fulfilled very, very strictly, both in the first phase and
the completion of the second phase.''
   Cordovez said the Soviet Union ``is leaving behind only a few
military advisers ... less than 10, a residual presence.''
   He did not elaborate and said he had no information about Soviet
civilian advisers who might remain.
   He indicated that the presence of Soviet military advisers did
not violate the Afghan agreements because the United States and
other nations which have closed their embassies have left behind
guards.
   Despite the withdrawal, Cordovez failed to persuade Afghans to
form a broad-based transition government as Soviet troops withdrew.
The future government, he said, must be decided by the Afghan people
themselves, without outside interference.
   He cited the history of friendship between Afghanistan and the
Soviet Union and predicted the Kabul regime would always be friendly
toward the Soviet Union, or at least ``not hostile.''
   He declined specific comment on whether aid provided by the
United States and Pakistan to the rebels violates the U.N.
agreement's provisions against intereference by other nations.
   ``Anything that fuels hostilities would be a violation of the
letter of spirit of the agreement,'' he said.
   The Soviet withdrawal began May 15 under U.N.-mediated accords
signed in Geneva on April 14 by Afghanistan and Pakistan, with the
United States and Soviet Union signing as guarantors.
   Fifty U.N. military observers in Afghanistan have a 20-month
mandate to fulfill. They are to concentrate on assisting the
repatriation of Afghan refugees and the rehabilitation of the
country.
</TEXT>
