<DOCNO> AP890215-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 1656EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Libya     02-15 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Libya,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Kohl Aide Acknowledges First Reports on Libyan Affair Date Back
to 1980</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government
learned in 1987 that Libya planned to produce poison gas at a plant
West German companies are suspected of helping to build, Kohl's
chief of staff said Wednesday.
   Wolfgang Schaeuble also said intelligence reports to the Bonn
leadership dating back to 1980 suggested West German involvement
with the plant in Rabta, but that authorities then determined there
was no ``conscious participation.''
   Schaeuble's disclosures have plunged the Bonn government deeper
into the scandal that has plagued U.S.-West German relations for
three months.
   But he declined to comment when asked whether the mounting
indications that Bonn authorities have known about the Rabta plant
all along have damaged West Germany's international prestige.
   Schaeuble said companies from at least six other countries have
been mentioned since the controversy over the chemical plant in
Rabta became public in late December. He said it was too early to
assess what responsibility West Germany might bear.
   Schaeuble reported the findings of a government investigation
into the Libyan affair to Parliament on Jan. 18, but the information
was made public Wednesday.
   He answered reporters' questions about the report after Economics
Minister Helmut Haussmann outlined proposals endorsed by Kohl's
Cabinet on Wednesday that would impose stricter export controls.
   The measures Parliament could consider this spring include a
proposed 15-year prison term and fines up to $540,000 for West
German businessmen who knowingly provide materials or technical
know-how for the production of chemical weapons.
   They also broaden the list of chemical, biological and nuclear
materials for which shippers must obtain federal approval to deliver
abroad, as well as reducing the number of countries to which
sensitive materials can be exported without government authorization.
   West Germany is the world's largest exporter, and 30 percent of
the nation's companies are involved in international trade,
Haussmann said.
   U.S. officials informed Kohl and Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher during their visit to the United States in November that
intelligence reports linked the Black Forest chemical company of
Imhausen-Chemie to the Libyan project.
   The allegations were made public in late December, and Kohl and
others initially denied they had any indications West German
companies broke the law.
   Although authorities now say the U.S. charges probably are
grounded in fact, they say they have no clear evidence against any
of the companies implicated on which to press charges.
   According to Schaeuble's report, the Bundesnachrichtendienst
(BND), the country's central intelligence service, sent its first
report on the Libyan plant to the chancellor's office and the
Foreign Ministry on April 22, 1980.
   ``The BND reported that Libya proposed to build a plant to
produce chemical weapons with the help of East and West German firms
that were not named,'' Schaeuble said.
   ``The BND considered it possible that what was involved was a
normal chemical plant. A conscious participation by German firms in
construction of a chemical weapons plant was excluded.''
   Schaeuble repeated claims made by other senior officials over the
past couple of months that their first substantial information on
which they could base investigations came only in October 1988.
</TEXT>
