<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan-Pakistan     02-15 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Pakistan,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pakistani Analysts Foresee Continued Struggle in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistani analysts on Wednesday
praised the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan but said they foresee
further struggles in the country before its 10-year-old civil war
ends.
   ``This must be the miracle of century. It's finally come about,''
said retired Lt. Gen. Kamal Matinuddin after the last Red Army
troops left Afghanistan.
   As the head of Pakistan's Institute of Strategic Studies,
Matinuddin has followed the decade-long war between communist forces
and Moslem guerrillas.
   ``Today is a very historic day. It must be marked,'' said Ijaz
Gilani, research director of the institute's crisis and conflict
analysis team, which has published monthly statistics on the war.
   They spoke during a status report on Afghanistan at the
institute's Islamabad headquarters.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman, speaking on the usual condition of
anonymity, said the withdrawal ``paves the way for a comprehensive
settlement based on the right of the Afghan people for
self-determination.''
   Matinuddin said he was skeptical of widespread predictions that
Afghanistan's government will fall quickly to the guerrillas in the
absence of Soviet soldiers, who entered the country in December 1979.
   ``I don't think it's that simple. (President) Najib's forces are
strong. I think the most likely scenario is that fighting will
continue ... by harassment by mujahedeen _ attacks on airports and
such,'' he said.
   Guerrilla leaders, most of whom are based in Pakistan, said they
do not plan to launch frontal assaults on communist-held Afghan
cities.
   They said their main tactic will be to besiege cities in hopes
that demoralized government troops will defect to the guerrillas,
causing the communist government to collapse.
   Matinuddin said the pullout leaves the guerrillas in disarray as
they argue over formation of a postwar government.
   He indicated the guerrillas' failure to form a cohesive
alternative to the Kabul regime may cost it its credibility in the
crucial months ahead.
   ``I don't believe the international community will respond to the
new government very quickly,'' Matinuddin said.
   Gilani gave an account of the military situation in Afghanistan
on the last day of the Soviet withdrawal. Among other points, he
said:
   _ All cities with strategic or ``psychological'' importance were
under guerrilla siege.
   _ The important airports were within attacking range of the
guerrillas.
   _ All major highways were at least partially interrupted by the
guerrillas.
   _ Kabul was relatively calm.
   _ There was a rising trend in defections by communist troops to
the resistance.
</TEXT>
