<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Sudan     02-15 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Sudan,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Planning Starvation Prevention In Sudan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudan's government has invited U.N. relief
officials to Khartoum next month to begin planning ways to prevent
mass starvation during the rainy season, officials said Wednesday.
   ``It's a meeting that is looking at a potential tragedy, and we
want to find practical solutons to avoid it,'' said Charles-Henri La
Muniere, a senior U.N. official working on the Sudan relief project.
   The conference is planned for March 8-9 and will be led by UNICEF
Director James P. Grant and Undersecretary-General Abdulrahim A.
Farah, said U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani.
   Private relief agencies will be contacted shortly to join the
effort, said La Muniere.
   Unless food is delivered throughout the Sudan to about 4 million
people displaced by rebellion, drought and famine before the rainy
season begins in May, hundreds of thousands of people may starve.
   ``It's a race against time,'' said La Muniere. ``We've got to
beat the devil at his game on this one. The donor community is
solidly behind this.''
   The United States and other Western nations are pressuring the
Sudanese government of Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi to improve food
distribution and other aid to all sections of his country.
   Madhi's government has often cited the rebellion by the Sudan
People's Liberation Army as posing too great a danger for relief
flights and convoys in the south.
   The government has allowed little aid to reach the rebel-held
south, where about 500,000 people died of starvation last year. The
rebellion broke out in 1983 over demands for greater automony and
economic reforms.
   The southern provinces of Bahr Ghazal, Upper Nile and Equatoria
are mainly Christian and animist and resent being ruled by the
predominantly Islamic governing elite in the north.
   During the past year the rebels have become more cooperative due
to limited negotiations with some elements of Mahdi's government,
said U.N. officials, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Relief flights organized by the World Food Program, the Red
Cross, UNICEF and the U.N. Development Program have been allowed by
the rebels to land in cities in the south, where peasant farmers
have fled to escape the guerrilla war.
   Distributing food throughout the country before the rainy season
will require truck convoys and shipments by train, said U.N.
officials.
</TEXT>
