<FIRST>r w AM-US-MoscowEmbassy     02-15 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Moscow Embassy,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say Offer Being Reviewed But Could Pose Some Difficulties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department is still reviewing an
offer made last month by a group of American businessmen to purchase
the partially built U.S. Embassy in Moscow, but the proposal could
pose some difficulties, officials said Wednesday.
   The United States has halted construction on the eight-story
embassy because it was found to have been riddled with Soviet
listening devices while the Soviets were building it.
   Last year, then-President Reagan recommended that the building be
razed and rebuilt.
   But last month, a trade group headed by Dwayne O. Andreas, one of
the nation's richest men and chairman of Archer Daniels Midland Co.,
offered to buy the building for use as business offices.
   Andreas is also co-chairman of the U.S.-U.S.S.R. Trade and
Economic Council, which has tried to promote more trade between the
two superpowers. He made the offer on behalf of a consortium of U.S.
companies, which would use the building as a Moscow headquarters.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman, asked about a
report that U.S. officials had found the Andreas proposal to be the
most expensive of several options for dealing with the building,
said Wednesday that ``all of the options'' were still under study,
including the proposal from the businessmen.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III is expected to send a
recommendation to President Bush once the ``in-depth review'' of
those options is complete, Redman said. The spokesman said he was
not aware of any deadline for completion of the study.
   Joseph S. Hulings, the coordinator of embassy problem in the
department's management bureau, said his office was ``still
evaluating'' the businessmen's offer.
   Hulings said he could estimate ``off the top of my head'' that it
might cost 25 percent more to sell the building to the businessmen
and build a new embassy.
   That is because the foundation of the unfinished building
contains some of the electrical, water and other facilities for the
surrounding living quarters of the U.S. diplomats and their
families, and if a new building were built at a different site, new
utilities would be required.
   The Soviets would have to approve any sale because the building
was intended for use as a new embassy, built under a 1972 agreement
between the two countries.
   Another problem arises because, under the agreement, the Soviets
cannot occupy their new facility in Washington until the U.S.
Embassy in Moscow is ready. If U.S. businessmen occupied the Moscow
building, the Soviets might seek to take over their completed
chancery in Washington.
   Although the United States has informally discussed the proposal
with the Soviets, no reply has been received from them, and until
they reply, no formal cost estimate can be drawn up, Hulings added.
   The United States has filed claims against the Soviets for $29
million in connection with what the United States claims are defects
and delays in the construction. Those claims must be negotiated by
an arbitration panel in Stockholm, Sweden.
   The existence of bugs in the structure became widely known in
1986. Under the 1972 construction agreement, a Soviet
government-owned construction firm was permitted to build the
American embassy.
</TEXT>
