<FIRST>r w AM-DCShootings     02-15 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC Shootings,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Way Ahead of Last Year's Record Homicide Rate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flurry of shootings overnight, including
three killings, accelerated demands Wednesday for tougher action to
stem rising violence in the nation's capital.
   ``No mayor anywhere could be more unhappy about this situation
than me,'' Mayor Marion S. Barry Jr. said at his monthly news
conference. ``If I had the solutions for these killings at my
fingertips, I'd stop them. It's frightening, it's sad, that we've
come to this point.''
   Said Barry, ``Obviously, meeting in the community is not enough,
marches aren't enough, sending hundreds of police officers out isn't
enough. We're in an epidemic around America.''
   Paramedics responded to 14 reports of shootings in the city
Tuesday, 11 of them between 6:30 p.m. and midnight, according to
Twyla Geraci, a spokeswoman for the D.C. Ambulance Service. Five of
the 14 ended up being false calls or people refusing treatment. She
didn't know whether other shootings might have occurred without
ambulance calls.
   The three slayings, combined with the death Tuesday of a
teen-ager who was shot in the head the previous night, raised the
total of lives taken in the first 45 days of 1989 to 75, compared to
46 at the same time in 1988. The total for all of last year was 372,
a record for the city.
   The dead Tuesday night were identified as Anthony Bailey and
Derrick Bell, both 25, and Darnell Wells, 26, according to Officer
Walter Ferguson, a spokesman for the Metropolitan Police Department.
He identified the teen-ager as Habib Mathis, 15. All four were from
suburban Maryland.
   Nearby but not included in the D.C. toll, a gunman described as a
``disgruntled employee'' killed three women and then himself at the
office of a savings bank in suburban Bethesda, Md., on Wednesday.
   Police and Mayor Barry have blamed drugs for most of the recent
homicides in the District of Columbia.
   ``Obviously, these are targeted murders,'' Barry said. ``They are
not random killings _ these are assassinations, drug dealers killing
one another.''
   The mayor said city residents needn't fear for their lives.
   ``Downtown Washington is safe, and a lot of our neighborhoods are
safe. Washington is not Dodge City,'' the mayor said, though last
year Police Chief Maurice Turner said the number and variety of
weapons seized on the city's streets reminded him ``of something out
of the wild, wild West.''
   Though blaming drugs for the violence, Barry two months ago
drastically curtailed Operation Clean Sweep, the police department's
program targeting street drug sales.
   At his news conference, he promised a major announcement on new
crime fighting strategies by next Monday.
   Since budget problems will prevent Barry from hiring many new
officers, some police officials predict the city will try to deal
with the crime wave by moving officers from safer neighborhoods into
drug-plagued sections.
   But council members called for more drastic action.
   Councilman H.R. Crawford renewed his call for the National Guard
to patrol notorious drug markets.
   Barry has opposed such a move, saying the city can handle its own
problems.
   ``It just says to me that we need to apply tougher standards
across the board when it comes to dealing with this,'' Councilman
James Nathanson said. ``We cannot let this continue.''
   The mayor said legislation instituting the death penalty in the
District of Columbia isn't the answer.
   ``We have a death penalty already _ 70 percent (of last year's
murders) were assassinations, and those count as executions,'' Barry
said. ``That's an unjust system, but if that's not keeping people
from killing one another, I'm not sure a just system would.''
</TEXT>
