<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 1746EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Baker     02-15 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Allies Urge Bush Administration To Respond To Gorbachev Agenda</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO allies are urging Washington to launch a
comprehensive arms control initiative or risk of allowing Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev to take charge of the East-West agenda,
a senior U.S. official said Wednesday.
   The official briefed reporters aboard the plane of Secretary of
State James A. Baker III as Baker moved into the final phase of his
tour of NATO capitals.
   The U.S. official said said Gorbachev was getting credit from the
West European public for arms reductions and human rights advances
that were pressed on him by the United States.
   ``There are potential opportunities for us to launch
initiatives'' to reduce long-range nuclear weapons arsenals, slow
the proliferation of ballistic missiles in troubled areas of the
world and curb chemical weapons, the official said on condition of
anonymity.
   ``There are real problems that threaten to make the whole
environment a lot more dangerous,'' he said. ``If the Soviets really
have new thinking _ and we think they may _ these are good areas for
us to be both probing and challenging.''
   He said that if the West, led by the United States, does not take
charge ``and deal with that reality ... Gorbachev's agenda will
become one that is much more prominent and we will have to respond
to Gorbachev's agenda rather than have him respond to ours.''
   Baker's eight-day trip is designed primarily to solicit the views
of the allies as the Bush administration tries to formulate new
foreign policy initiatives.
   In the meantime, resumption of U.S. negotiations with the Soviets
to reduce strategic nuclear weapons has been postponed indefinitely.
   Baker made stops Wednesday in Spain and Portugal, meeting in
Madrid with Spanish Prime Minister Felipe Gonzales and Foreign
Minister Francisco Fernandez-Ordonez and in Lisbon with Portuguese
Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva and Foreign Minister Joao de Dues
Pinheiro.
   Baker then flew to Brussels for meetings Thursday with Belgian
and NATO officials. Later Thursday he will stop in Luxembourg and
the Netherlands. He flies home Friday.
   In a brief exchange with reporters in Madrid, Baker marked the
final pullout of Soviet troops from Afghanistan with an appeal to
Moscow to contribute to rehabilitating that country.
   He called the Soviet military intervention, which began in
December 1979, ``a tragic chapter'' in Afghanistan's history.
</TEXT>
