<FIRST>r w AM-EscapedWolf     02-15 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Escaped Wolf,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaskan Wolf Loose in Capital Said `Friendly' but `Timid'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black Alaskan timber wolf, described as
``friendly'' but ``quite timid,'' was on the loose in the nation's
capital Wednesday but authorities said it probably was not dangerous.
   The wolf, on tour with its owner to promote its job as mascot of
a Fairbanks radio station, escaped Tuesday from its crate in a
garage near the National Zoo while the woman was visiting relatives.
   Kristina Harper, chief of animal disease control for the city's
Department of Human Services, said, ``We have no reason to think
that the animal's dangerous.''
   ``It sounds kind of alarming to think there's a wolf in the city,
but it's a domesticated hybrid. Apparently it's tame and used to
people,'' she said.
   The wolf is named ``Athena'' and is part dog. It chewed its way
through a wooden crate, said Glenner Anderson, program director of
KWLF in Fairbanks. He said Dawn Maddox, of Fairbanks, had raised the
2-year-old wolf as a pet since its birth, alongside her two children.
   ``It's extremely friendly, but is quite timid,'' said Anderson.
``It's probably got its tail between its legs and it's running
around somewhere or hiding somewhere. It's going to be hard to catch
because it's scared around people.''
   The wolf won a contest eight months ago seeking a mascot for the
radio station and has been on an East Coast tour promoting the
station.
   Ms. Harper said her agency had received no calls from people
sighting the animal.
   She described the animal as ``mostly black with a little bit of
brown in its mane and some white on its back and haunches.'' It has
amber eyes and was wearing a choke collar.
</TEXT>
