<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     02-15 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Wound 15 Palestinians, Round Up 40</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army gunfire wounded 15 people in the occupied
lands on Wednesday, and soldiers rounded up 40 Palestinians
suspected of anti-Israeli activities, Arab and Israeli reports said.
   Arab reporters and Israeli radio stations said the Palestinians
were detained in raids on refugee camps and villages in the West
Bank.
   An Israeli military spokeman said soldiers made arrests and
sealed a Palestinian home in the Ein Beit Elma refugee camp near
Nablus, but he would not say how many people were arrested. Army
radio said 14 Palestinians were taken into custody there.
   The spokesman, who cannot be identified under army regulations,
said the purpose was to capture Palestinians suspected of attacking
others who have collaborated with Israel.
   He said a resident of the sealed house is accused of attacking an
alleged collaborator last September. Arab reports identified him as
Talat Abu Saris, 19, who has been held four months without trial.
   More than 30 Palestinians were detained in other raids at
villages and refugee camps near Ramallah on suspicion of
anti-Israeli activities, the Arab reports said. The army said it was
checking the reports.
   Nine Palestinians were reported shot by soldiers Wednesday in the
Gaza Strip, six of them in the Shati refugee camp.
   Camp residents said troopers stopped an elderly man for
questioning and struck him, then a crowd gathered, urged on by
chants of the Moslem rallying cry ``Allahu akbar'' (God is great).
   The crowd began throwing stones and the soldiers fired, the
residents said.
   At the Rafah refugee camp, soldiers dispersed schoolchildren by
using rubber bullets and a machine that fires gravel, the reports
said.
   Hospital officials said two Palestinians, aged 16 and 25,
suffered leg wounds and a 17-year-old in Gaza City also was shot in
the leg.
   In the West Bank, six Palestinians were reported wounded at
Nablus, the nearby Faraa refugee and Janna Ein village.
   At least 380 Palestinians and 15 Israelis have been killed since
the uprising against nearly 22 years of occupation began 14 months
ago. More than 7,000 Palestiians have been wounded.
</TEXT>
