<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 1814EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghan-Chronology     02-15 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan-Chronology,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of some of the main events in the war in
Afghanistan:
   
   1978:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   APRIL _ The pro-Soviet Marxist party of Afghanistan overthrows
the Afghan republic and installs Nur Mohammad Taraki as president.
Armed non-communist resistance begins.
   
   1979:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MARCH 12 _ The National Liberation Front, a Moslem group, calls
for Jihad, or Holy War, against Kabul government.
   JULY _ Soviets deploy first combat unit in Afghanistan, a 400-man
airborne battalion.
   SEPTEMBER _ Taraki killed in intra-party showdown with deputy
Hafizullah Amin.
   DECEMBER _ Massive Soviet airlift of 5,000 troops to Afghanistan.
Soviet commandos attack presidential palace. Amin is killed and
Babrak Karmal becomes president.
   
   1980:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JANUARY _ United Nations demands ``immediate, unconditional and
total withdrawal of foreign troops'' from Afghanistan.
   FEBRUARY _ Soviet troop strength increases to 75,000, and
eventually to 115,000, by Western estimates.
   
   1982:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JUNE _ In Geneva, U.N. official Diego Cordovez conducts first
indirect peace talks between Afghanistan and Pakistan, which speaks
for Afghan resistance.
   
   1984:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   APRIL _ Soviets conduct saturation bombing of guerrilla
strongholds and villages.
   AUGUST _ Pakistan protests to Kabul government about repeated
aerial bombing and crossborder shelling.
   
   1985:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MAY _ In Pakistan, fundamentalist Moslem guerrillas join
moderates to form a seven-party coalition.
   DECEMBER _ Afghanistan offers timetable for Soviet withdrawal.
   
   1986:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MAY _ Karmal replaced by Najib, former head of secret police.
   JULY _ Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev announces plans to
withdraw six regiments from Afghanistan. Washington later says
forces mainly were unnecessary antiaircraft units, and were replaced
by armored regiments.
   SEPTEMBER _ Guerrillas, supported by significant U.S. arms
shipments, reportedly receive first U.S. Stinger antiaircraft
missiles. Within months, they reportedly shoot down average of one
enemy aircraft per day.
   
   1987:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JANUARY _ Najib declares unilateral ceasefire. It is ignored by
both sides, and guerrillas reject powersharing with communists.
   OCTOBER _ Surveys estimate that more than 1.2 million Afghans
have died in war and that 2.9 million Afghans have fled to Pakistan
and 2.3 million to Iran. DECEMBER _ One of Gorbachev's chief
advisers tells reporters he expects Soviet Union to pull out of
Afghanistan in 1988.
   
   1988:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   JANUARY _ Pakistan says it will accept some Communist involvement
in future Afghan government as price for Soviet withdrawal.
   FEBRUARY _ Gorbachev offers to withdraw Soviet troops beginning
May 15 and ending 10 months later, if an accord is signed by March
15. Cordovez announces near agreement on Soviet pullout and new
round of talks in Geneva.
   MARCH _ Agreement reached that Soviet troop withdrawal must be
completed within nine months of starting date. Negotations continue
past Gorbachev's March 15 target date.
   APRIL 14 _ The Soviet Union, Pakistan, the United States and the
Afghan government sign U.N.-brokered accord in Geneva arranging for
the withdrawal of 115,000 Red Army troops from Afghanistan.
   MAY 15 _ Soviets pull out from eastern Afghanistan as rebels
continue attacks on Soviet troops. Moscow accuses foreign sponsors
of stepping up weapons shipments to guerrillas.
   AUG. 15 _ The second phase of the troop withdrawal begins. More
than half of the Soviet troops in the country have been evacuated
since pullout began.
   NOV. 4 _ The Soviet Union, citing continued military aid to the
guerrillas from Pakistan and the United States, says it is
indefinitely suspending the pullout.
   
   1989:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JAN. 23 _ Soviet and Afghan troops shell both ends of a major
tunnel on the Salang highway, the main route for Soviet troops
leaving Kabul. Western diplomats say hundreds of civilians are
killed in several villages in the region.
   JAN. 24 _ Western diplomats say the Soviet withdrawal is in full
swing, even though Moscow has not said whether it has resumed
pullout.
   FEB. 7 _ A Soviet Foreign Ministry official says 15,000 Soviet
soldiers were killed during the war, including 2,000 who died during
the withdrawal.
   FEB. 10 _ Afghan rebel leaders based in Pakistan and Iran meet to
discuss forming a postwar government, but the talks break off over
disputes on power sharing and including disparate factions in new
government.
   FEB. 15 _ The Red Army commander for Afghanistan leads the last
contingent of his troops across a border bridge, ending the
nine-year intervention. The United Nations confirms the Soviet
occupation is over.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890215-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 2115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-AirSecurity     02-15 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Air Security,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>US, Britain Appeal for Action Against Air Terrorism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. and British transportation secretaries
appealed Wednesday for better security practices to make
international air travel safe from terrorists.
   They addressed the 33-member council of the International Civil
Aviation Organization at the opening of a two-day meeting the United
States and Britain requested after a bomb blew up a Pan Am jetliner
Dec. 21 over Scotland.
   Samuel K. Skinner of the United States said: ``No one country or
carrier should have to stand alone in matters of security. It is
only by joining together, in the finest traditions of ICAO, that we
can secure international civil aviation from acts of terrorism.''
   Paul Channon, the British secretary, told the council members:
``We meet today because the list of such disasters has grown too
long.''
   He noted the attack on Pan Am flight 103, which killed 259 people
on the plane and 11 on the ground, and the bombings in flight of an
Air India flight in 1985 and a Korean Airways jet in 1987.
   Those attending the meeting said bomb attacks on planes must be
considered a phenomenon to be fought much as international
cooperation helped reduce the number of aircraft hijackings after
they became epidemic.
   Among suggested neasures are increased screening of passengers
and carry-on baggage, more thorough screening of checked baggage,
pairing passengers with checked baggage and better screening of
cargo and mail.
   Others include faster development and installation of screening
technology, tighter control of access to strategic areas and the
possibility of limiting carry-on radios, computers and other
electronic devices in which explosives are difficult to detect.
   Channon asked the council for a unanimous decision ``that the
time has come to take vigorous action to review existing provisions
and examine the need for new ones to improve our common defenses
against the scourge of sabotage which has taken such a hideous toll
of innocent life in the past four years.''
   U.S. airlines have taken more stringent security measures since
the Pan Am bombing, but officials said air terrorism can be
controlled only through international measures.
   ``We are dealing with terrorists who can and will strike
anywhere,'' Channon said. ``Only concerted action by all ICAO's
member states can give air travelers and air crews confidence in
their security.''
   The organization is a U.N. agency and 160 countries are members.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
