<DOCNO> AP890215-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 1850EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-NorthTrial 3rdld-writethru a0743 02-15 0818</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial, 3rd ld-writethru, a0743,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial May Be Back On Track</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf to show Supreme Court asked to lift stay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North's Iran-Contra trial appeared to
get back on track Wednesday as prosecutors, after meeting with
Justice Department lawyers, issued guidelines designed to guard
against disclosures of classified material by North.
   In a four-paragraph statement, independent counsel Lawrence Walsh
said he will, if necessary, seek an affidavit from Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh to prevent the disclosure of classified information
which could harm national security.
   The statement was worked out with Thornburgh, who said it will
permit national security secrets to be protected.
   Hours after the announcement, Thornburgh asked the Supreme Court
to lift the stay that has delayed the start of the trial and said he
will also drop his appeal of rulings by U.S. District Court Judge
Gerhard A. Gesell on secrecy issues. Chief Justice William Rehnquist
had issued the administrative stay at the Justice Department's
request.
   Walsh's statement was in response to an order issued Tuesday by
Gesell, who told Thornburgh to stay out of the North case, barring
the attorney general from filing affidavits in ``bits and pieces''
in response to individual documents or testimony planned by North.
Gesell said Walsh ``will be recognized as responsible for the
day-to-day conduct of this case.''
   North's attorney, Brendan Sullivan, was not immediately available
for comment.
   Thornburgh, in a statement, endorsed the plan. ``The independent
counsel's planned implementation of yesterday's district court order
provides the government with the substance of what we have been
seeking for the past week.''
   ``I am pleased that a mechanism has been developed that will
permit the trial to go forward while ensuring that I can fulfill the
responsibility imposed upon me by the Congress to protect the
national security interests of the United States,'' Thornburgh said.
   Walsh's statement also says Walsh will notify Thornburgh if
evidence in any of eight specific categories is to be introduced.
   Those categories include information identifying undercover CIA
officers, and information revealing locations of CIA stations and
U.S. covert activities other than paramilitary support for the
Contras. Also included are details about specific CIA operations
with foreign intelligence services and government officials as well
as information identifying by name or description foreigners who are
CIA assets or liaison officials.
   ``If the Attorney General, by affidavit, states that the evidence
(in the eight categories) is such a threat to national security that
it can not be introduced, Independent Counsel will accept this
statement as a statement by the Administration and ask the Court to
take appropriate action,'' said Walsh.
   ``If the attorney general, by affidavit, states that the evidence
(in the eight categories) is such a threat to national security that
it can not be introduced, independent counsel will accept this
statement as a statement by the administration and ask the court to
take appropriate action,'' said Walsh.
   Walsh also said he ``will, of course, object to any classified
information not previously'' designated by North as being part of
the evidence he plans to introduce at trial.
   Walsh's statement differs from Gesell's order of Tuesday in one
respect. Gesell's order says Walsh may prevent the introduction of
classified information through the section of the Classified
Information Procedures Act dealing with affidavits.
   Walsh, however, said he doesn't have the power to file an
affidavit under the section of CIPA permitting the barring of
classified information damaging to the national security.
   But Walsh said he can ask Thornburgh to file an affidavit if it
becomes necessary and after the court has rejected other
alternatives such as summarizing, or censoring, the classified
material.
   Gesell said Tuesday he won't let Thornburgh ``chop up the case''
with a series of affidavits barring disclosure of information each
time North tried to introduce evidence the government found
objectionable.
   Decisions on possible challenges to classified information will
be left to Walsh, Gesell said.
   Concerns over classified material that North wanted to use in his
defense erupted Feb. 8. The Justice Department sought a court order
that would have barred the fired White House aide from disclosing
any classified material without a court ruling that it is admissible
and as long as there is an objection to its release pending from the
government.
   North faces 12 criminal charges. He is accused of allegedly
concealing from Congress in 1985 and 1986 his efforts on behalf of
the Nicaraguan Contras and of covering up from the attorney general
the National Security Council's role in diverting money from the
Iran arms sales to the Contras.
   North also is accused of illegally accepting a $13,800 security
system at his home from co-defendant Richard Secord, converting to
his own use at least $4,300 in traveler's checks from Contra leader
Adolfo Calero and conspiring to defraud the Treasury of tax revenue
in connection with charitable contributions supporting the Contras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890215-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 1854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     02-15 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition, Government Discuss Farmers Union Freedoms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition and the government agreed on
union freedom for farmers at talks Wednesday, an opposition
participant reported.
   He said the two sides still are divided on agricultural price
reforms.
   The government meanwhile announced an average 8 percent increase
in processed meat prices, a touchy issue among consumers. Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa was hailed when he visited a pro-Solidarity
factory in southeastern Poland, and small strikes broke out across
the country.
   ``We were able to agree on pluralism,'' Law Professor Andrzej
Stelmachowski told a news conference after the first session of an
agriculture working group.
   The agricultural reforms talks are part of the unprecedented
round-table negotiations on a wide range of political and economic
reforms.
   ``I had an overwhelming impression that many concrete things were
discussed,'' said Stelmachowski, who wore the badge of the banned
Solidarity independent union movement.
   Wielsaw Mlynarczyk, deputy minister of agriculture and forestry,
said the group agreed on ``creating organizational and legal
conditions of activities of farmers' trade unions, covering
Solidarity, farmers' circles or any other organizations that farmers
will form according to their will.''
   Solidarity national spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz said agreement
on the need to allow more than one legal trade union for farmers
will influence discussions at talks on union freedoms set to resume
Thursday.
   ``It's important in the context of pluralism because it implies a
change in the union law,'' he said.
   The 1982 law on trade unions does not allow farmers to organize
independent unions.
   Talks began on Feb. 6 and are intended to negotiate the terms for
restoring Solidarity's legal status and to develop a ``social
contract'' between the opposition and the government to chart
Poland's future.
   On Wednesday, the government proposed a system to lessen state
control of market prices for agricultural products. Solidarity said
a minimum level of prices must be guaranteed to protect farmers'
incomes.
   Stelmachowski said the government-sanctioned trade union alliance
OPZZ vetoed the proposal on minimum prices, but that it will be
discussed again when agriculture reform talks resume Friday.
   The state news agency PAP announced the average 8 percent meat
price increases, effective Thursday.
   Better quality meat products are affected, including ham, which
will increase by 12 cents per pound, PAP said.
   The increases are aimed at reducing state price subsidies for
meat, Mlynarczyk said.
   In state-operated butcher shops, meats are rationed and supplies
of better quality cuts are erratic. The government has talked of
eliminating meat-rationing. Some products have been seen recently in
state-run specialty stores available at much higher prices but
without ration coupons.
   Meat also is sold at high prices in private markets.
   Walesa's rally Wednesday in Stalowa Wola was one in a series he
has held to build support for talks with the government and to
inform followers on the progress of the talks.
   Machinery factory workers in the industrial town struck during
the labor unrest in May and August. On Tuesday, Walesa was in the
coal region of Silesia to address miners whose work stoppage began
last August's wave of strikes.
   Local authorities granted permission for the Stalowa Wola rally
and march, and Walesa was greeted by posters bearing his portrait
and followers chanting ``Solidarity must be!''
   A flare-up of strikes began after round-table talks started. Only
one, by textile workers in Ozorkow, appeared to be led by Solidarity
supporters. The others were led by OPZZ or could not be linked with
any specific union.
   Various strikes were reported in Zdunska Wola, Starachowice,
Bilgoraj, Szczecin, Piotrkow Trybunalski, Lask, Sieradz, Lodz,
Ostrow Swietokrzyski, Ciechanow and Lublin.
   PAP said health service workers in Poznan decided to suspend a
strike for the duration of the round-table talks.
   Walesa asked workers not to strike during the talks to give the
discussions a chance to produce results.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
