<FIRST>u i AM-CentralAmerica 1stLd-Writethru a0723 02-15 0875</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central America, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0723,0901</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summit's Agreements Face Follow-Through, Key Players Left Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to ADD Contra leader quotes, edits to trim.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan rebel leaders
Wednesday criticized the Central American summit agreement that
would dismantle their movement, and they insisted they must be
included in negotiating their own future.
   Leaders of the guerrillas known as Contras also said they felt
abandoned by the United States, which one called ``a bad ally, not a
trustworthy ally.''
   The agreement announced Tuesday by five Central American
presidents calls for disbanding the Contra guerrillas and for early
elections in Nicaragua. But the presidents still face two major
tasks: getting the rebels and their U.S. sponsors to go along with
the accords, and verifying Nicaraguan compliance.
   ``A lot of people put themselves out on a limb by signing this,''
Contra leader Adolfo Calero said Wednesday.
   Presidents Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua, Jose Azcona Hoyo of
Honduras, Oscar Arias of Costa Rica, Vinicio Cerezo of Guatemala and
Jose Napoleon Duarte of El Salvador said they agreed to develop a
plan within 90 days to demobilize and dismantle the 11,000-strong
Contra army.
   Ortega also promised to advance national and local elections from
November 1990 to February of that year and open the electoral
process to the opposition. He said he would permit United Nations
observers, but the presidents were unable to agree on a verification
procedure.
   The two major components of the accord were presented as
unilateral agreements. Nicaragua's promise to hold elections does
not formally depend on what happens to the Contras, although
Sandinista spokesmen made it clear they expect the Contras to be
gone by the time electoral reform begins.
   Neither the United States nor the rebels are parties to the
accord, although neither rejected it outright.
   ``We are neither rejecting nor enthusiastically promoting this
action,'' Calero said.
   The accord left the Contras isolated diplomatically and
psychologically in Central America, but it was not known what would
happen if the rebels refuse to go along with the plan to dismantle
their camps.
   An estimated 11,000 fighters and several thousand family members
are in Honduras along the border with Nicaragua, many of them vowing
to fight on. They ran out of ammunition and moved into the camps
after the United States suspended military aid last February.
   The Honduran army would have a difficult time ejecting the
battle-hardened guerrillas by force, and Honduras fears ending U.S.
humanitarian aid would leave a hungry horde on the loose.
   ``We are well and alive,'' Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros
insisted during the summit. ``We are a very real ghost.''
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman had no
comment on the summit meeting except to say U.S. officials will be
interested in consulting with the four Central American countries
friendly to the United States.
   He said no consultations with Nicaragua are planned, consistent
with the Reagan administration's policy of avoiding diplomatic
contact with the Sandinista government.
   Arias noted the importance of the U.S. reaction after the summit
ended.
   ``It is the responsibility of the international community _ but
above all of those who for many years sponsored the Contras _ to
find a solution to this problem,'' Arias told a news conference.
   Contra spokesmen were bitter toward the United States, saying
Washington had abandoned them despite their sacrifices and the 8,000
dead they have suffered.
   ``The U.S. has not lived up to its responsibility to us, to our
dedication,'' Calero said.
   ``The United States is a bad ally, not a trustworthy ally,'' said
Calero, a soft-drink distributor in pre-revolutionary Nicaragua.
``But of bad allies, it was the least bad.''
   Matamoros said in a separate interview that ``if we had to do it
over again, we would look for support from China (Nationalist China,
or Taiwan), or some other reliable country.''
   Calero said that ``whether it likes it or not, the United States
is deeply involved in what's happening'' and should monitor the
accord, using ``coercive force'' if need be to make sure the
Sandinistas live up to their promises.
   ``The United States must either assume its responsibility or give
us more military aid to keep going,'' he said.
   Both the Contras and President Bush have said peace would come
when Nicaragua became a democracy. Contra military leader Enrique
Bermudez said dismantling the Contras would remove any incentive for
democratization.
   ``If we take these promises as the foundation, if they serve to
dismantle us, then the Sandinistas will be there forever,'' he said.
   The Sandinistas clearly expect the Contras to be gone before
Ortega's summit promise of open, early elections is fully tested in
February 1990.
   The Sandinistas said they were ready for democratic reform
because the Contras had been defeated both politically and
militarily.
   Bermudez and Calero said the rebels could resume their fight from
Nicaraguan soil if they are no longer welcome in Honduras.
   ``Leaving Honduras is one thing,'' Calero said. ``Dismantling is
another.''
   Calero estimated the cost of disbanding the Contras at between
$150 million and $250 million and said the United States should take
in former Contras who want to live there.
   ``Like the Vietnamese,'' he said. ``The U.S. has done that before
with abandoned allies.''
</TEXT>
