<FIRST>u a AM-ChildAbuse 1stLd-Writethru a0666 02-15 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Abuse, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0666,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Child Sex Scandal Spurs Examination of Psych Centers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Chairman Clarence ..., and 13th graf, ``Thank
God ..., to CORRECT chairman's name to Sundram, sted Sundrum.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST SENECA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ability of mental health workers to
cope with sexual abuse is being questioned following the discovery
that youngsters at a children's psychiatric center had turned the
place into a sexual playground.
   A state investigation uncovered 64 instances of sexual activity
involving 47 children from November 1987 to July 1988 at the Western
New York Children's Psychiatric Center. The children, most of them
ages 5 to 12, had sex with each other while administrators looked
the other way, according to the report by the watchdog commission
that investigated the facility in this Buffalo suburb.
   Chairman Clarence Sundram said the panel determined that
administrators considered the sexual activity normal and did nothing
to stop it.
   State Mental Health Commissioner Richard Surles called the
findings ``morally offensive'' and ``inexplicable.'' He promised
reforms at the facility and a review of the state's four other child
psychiatric hospitals.
   Experts in child abuse said the case has revealed an
extraordinary inability of mental health workers to deal with sexual
abuse.
   Jen Henry, an expert on treating sexually abused children who was
brought in to assist the West Seneca staff, said sexual abuse has
become a major topic of general concern only in the past 10 years.
   ``The training of mental health professionals has not caught
up,'' said Henry, who noted that victims of sexual abuse can become
child abusers as adults if they do not receive treatment.
   For example, she said, most of the center's personnel who worked
closely with the children had only associate's degrees in social
work and were not required to take courses on how to recognize
sexual abuse.
   The scandal was revealed only after the parents of an 8-year-old
who had been sodomized several times by his 12-year-old roommate
refused to accept administrators' explanations that the behavior was
normal.
   The couple told police the boy had been disciplined for
complaining about the situation. Police later confronted
administrators.
   ``We had to inform them that sex between children is a crime,''
said Lt. Allen Scioli of the police juvenile division. ``They were
of the opinion there was nothing for the police to investigate.''
   After an initial police probe, the state commission investigated.
   ``Thank God they (the parents) persisted and were able to bring
their complaints to a place where could be dealt with,'' Sundram
said.
   The couple, who had sent their son to the facility because he was
hyperactive, are suing the state.
   Several top administrators who have resigned or been reassigned
have since acknowledged errors in judgment in not reporting the
incidents.
   C. Richard Orndoff, regional director of the state Mental Health
Department, defended the staff.
   ``It wasn't that they were callous or didn't care,'' Orndoff
said. ``They tried to address the problem clinically'' in group
therapy and in counseling.
   Dr. Kathleen Fowler, a child abuse researcher at the University
of Michigan, said most institutional health workers have little or
no training in handling sexual incidents. Staff members often
discount children's accounts of sexual situations because youngsters
sometimes tell stories to get attention.
   But the stories are sometimes true, said Fowler, who is
investigating a case in a similar facility in Michigan where a boy
was sodomized by 14 others.
   While sexual activity between children is definitely not
``normal,'' it is not unusual for children who are the victims of
sexual abuse to act out the abuse on each other, she said. She said
it is up to administrators to check a child's background and be
aware of possibly dangerous behavior patterns.
   State officials estimate that up to 75 percent of the children
that were at the West Seneca facility may have been sexually abused.
   Among the revelations was that children at the facility formed a
sex club variously called the ``GI Joes'' or the ``Transformers''
that required members to engage in oral and anal sex as an
initiation rite.
</TEXT>
