<FIRST>r i AM-Vatican-Czechoslovak     02-15 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican-Czechoslovak,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Warns Its Radio on Broadcasts to Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican rebuked its radio station
Wednesday for some of its broadcasts to Czechoslovakia, apparently
in hopes of resolving a dispute over the choice of Roman Catholic
bishops in that communist country.
   The nature of the broadcasts was not disclosed, but Vatican
sources said they involved a report on a demonstration for religious
freedom in Bratislava last year and one about events in
Czechoslovakia at the end of World War II.
   Spokesman Joaquin Navarro expressed the Vatican position in a
statement about a visit last month by Vladimir Janku, the
Czechoslovak official in charge of church affairs.
   In talks with Archbishop Francesco Colasuonno, special envoy to
Eastern Europe for Pope John Paul II, Janku complained of ``attacks
on Czechoslovakia'' in Vatican Radio programs, Navarro said.
   He said the ``Holy See confirmed its desire of arriving with
Czechoslovak authorities at a correct dialogue made with good will
toward resolving the problems regarding the Catholic church and in
particular the nominations of bishops.''
   Navarro said the two sides agreed the radio should keep its
broadcasts about Czechoslovakia ``in harmony'' with the Holy See's
attitudes toward that country.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Navarro's
statement would be broadcast back to Czechoslovakia.
   Relations between the Vatican and Prague have been cool because
of Czechoslovakia's intolerance toward believers and refusal to
accept bishops who do not belong to the pro-government Pacem in
Terris organization.
   Some improvement occurred last year, with the approval of two
auxiliary bishops for Prague and an apostolic administrator in
Trnava, but nine of the 13 sees still do not have Catholic bishops.
</TEXT>
