<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-15 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Rains, Flooding Continues In Several States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains caused flooding Wednesday in Tennessee, Kentucky,
Illinois and Indiana and flood watches were posted in a number of
other states.
   Nearly 9 inches of rain has soaked parts of western Kentucky
since Sunday, forcing hundreds of evacuations.
   In Frankfort, the Kentucky River had reached 4.6 feet above flood
stage by Wednesday afternoon, state officials said. The Barren River
was expected to crest about 5 feet over flood stage at Bowling
Green, Ky., on Thursday.
   Many small streams in southern Illinois and southern Indiana
flooded Wednesday morning. In Ohio, the Scioto River was flooding
and a flood warning was posted Wednesday for the West Virginia
counties of Cabell, Wayne and Mason.
   Flood watches remained in parts of Ohio, Kentucky, Indiana,
Illinois, Tennessee, Missouri, Arkansas, Oklahoma and Texas.
   In the southern Atlantic, a tropical disturbance sent heavy rains
and gusty winds toward Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands. The
hurricane season runs from June 1 to Nov. 30, putting the tropical
disturbance well beyond the normal bounds of tropical weather.
   ``Of course, we've had hurricanes in March, but this is not at
that stage yet. It's still just an area of disturbed weather
associated with a low-pressure system,'' said Bob Sheets, director
of the National Hurricane Center in suburban Coral Gables.
   Winter weather advisories were posted in parts of Illinois, New
York, Idaho, and Vermont. A snow advisory was posted in northeast
Washington state.
   Snow fell Wednesday in northern New England, northeast New York
state, Michigan, northern Indiana, central Illinois, the Dakotas,
eastern Montana, eastern Nebraska, Colorado and northern New Mexico.
There was freezing rain in parts of Oklahoma, Missouri, Pennsylvania
and New York state.
   Snowfall during the 6 hours ending at 1 p.m. EST included 2
inches at Burlington, Vt., and an inch at Bismarck, N.D., Buffalo,
N.Y., Chicago, Grand Rapids, Mich., Peoria, Ill., and Syracuse, N.Y.
   Rainfall during the same period included 1} inches at Fort Knox,
Ky., and almost an inch at Fort Campbell, Ky.
   Several cities in the South broke high temperature records for
the date including Augusta, Ga., 82; Cape Hatteras, N.C., 72;
Charleston, S.C., 81; Chattanooga, Tenn., 77; Greer, S.C., 74;
Huntsville, Ala., 74; Lynchburg, Va., 76; Mobile, Ala., 80; Norfolk,
Va., 79; Pensacola, Fla., 76; Roanoke, Va., 78; Richmond, Va., 82;
and Savannah, Ga., 82.
   The nation's low Wednesday in the Lower 48 was 29 degrees below
zero at Warroad, Minn.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 13
degrees below zero at International Falls, Minn., to 86 degrees at
McAllen, Texas.
   Thursday's forecast called for snow showers from north-central
Kentucky across central Ohio to west-central Pennsylvania. Snow was
expected to become rain from southern New England across Maryland
and west across the Appalachians, from northern Georgia across
Arkansas, Oklahoma and northern Texas. Showers and occasional
thunderstorms were to reach from southeast Texas across Louisiana,
southern Mississippi and central Alabama. Snow was to extend from
the northern Rockies across the Pacific Northwest and change to rain
along the northern Pacific Coast.
   Predicted high temperatures were: single digits from the northern
Rockies across North Dakota; single digits and teens over northern
Maine, Upper Michigan, Wisconsin across the upper Mississippi
Valley, South Dakota, northern Wyoming and western Montana; 20s and
30s from the central half of New England across the Ohio Valley, the
remainder of the Great Lakes, the middle Mississippi Valley, the
central Plains, Oklahoma, Texas, the remainder of the Rockies, the
Pacific Northwest and the northern coast of Washington; 40s and 50s
from southeast New York state across Delaware and Maryland, much of
Virginia, western Tennessee, Arkansas, northern Texas, southern
Rockies and the Pacific Coast from central Washington through
central California; 80s from southeast Louisiana across Florida.
High temperatures will generally be in the 50s and 60s in the
remainder of the nation.
