<FIRST>u a AM-TampaDisturbance 1stLd-Writethru a0774 02-15 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tampa Disturbance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0774,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Find No Police Wrongdoing in Drug Suspect's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 3rd graf, `Two officers ..., to UPDATE
with comment from police chief; ADDS 4 grafs comment from mother of Price's
girlfriend.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigation found no criminal wrongdoing
or negligence by police officers in the death of a suspected drug
dealer that touched off two nights of disturbances, prosecutors said
Wednesday.
   The Hillsborough State Attorney's Office concluded that the Feb.
1 asphyxiation of Edgar Allen Price, who was black, was accidental,
Assistant State Attorney John Skye said.
   Two officers were put on administrative leave while prosecutors
reviewed the case, amid racial sensitivities heightened by three
nights of rioting last month in Miami sparked by the fatal police
shooting of a black motorcyclist.
   Police Chief Austin C. McLane said he was not surprised that no
charges were filed. He said his officers properly restrained the
battling Price with handcuffs and leg ropes.
   A police department internal review of the officers' actions has
not yet been completed and was not expected for a couple of weeks.
   Eight police officers subdued the 6-foot-3, 300-pound Price in a
violent struggle after an informant made a crack cocaine buy in
College Hill, a predominantly black housing development.
   The officers hogtied the 40-year-old Price and placed him face
down in the back seat of a police cruiser, authorities said.
   Before paramedics could arrive to tend to a cut on the suspect's
head, rock- and bottle-throwing erupted. An officer drove the patrol
car to a parking lot a couple blocks away, where police noticed
Price was having trouble breathing. He died at a hospital two hours
later.
   The medical examiner's office said the restraint following the
exertion of the struggle figured into Price's death.
   ``By being placed in a limited space with the head face down into
the back seat associated with limited activity from being handcuffed
and restrained, the necessary conditions for producing an asphyxial
death existed,'' Dr. Charles Diggs, associate Hillsborough medical
examiner, said in a report released Friday.
   Diggs said the way Price was manacled is normally ``relatively
innocuous.'' Police said the medical examiner's report showed that
Price was not beaten or choked to death by officers.
   At least 10 people were arrested in the two nights of
disturbances, and five officers received minor injuries. A grocery
store was looted and torched.
   Price served 11 years of a 50-year prison sentence in Texas for
attempted murder of a Houston police officer and a string of
robberies. He was paroled in 1984 and came to Tampa in 1986, police
said. His girlfriend said Price worked as a long-distance trucker
and laborer.
   Arvida Marion, grandmother of Price's girlfriend, who was in her
house when Price and a band of officers came crashing in, said she
believed prosecutors never had any intention of filing charges.
   ``I'd knew they wouldn't do nothing to those cops,'' Ms. Marion
told The Tampa Tribune. ``But you'll be hearing from me again. This
ain't over yet.''
   ``They didn't need to tie him like a wild horse,'' she said.
   Police reported streets in the College Hill area were quiet early
Wednesday night and no extra patrols were called out, said Officer
John Newman.
</TEXT>
