<FIRST>r a AM-UnleashedClout     02-15 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unleashed Clout,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Unleashes Clout Against Veterinian Over Dog's Death</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   CHICAGO _ A former Watergate prosecutor unleashed her clout over
the death of a beloved dog, with her former personal lawyer named
special prosecutor to go after the veterinarian who tended her pet,
the vet's lawyers say.
   Hearings by the Professional Regulation Department have been
scheduled against Mell Wostoupal after former prosecutor Jill
Wine-Banks filed a complaint against the veterinarian over treatment
of her dog, Finnegan.
   Ms. Wine-Banks is executive vice president of the American Bar
Association and a former deputy Illinois attorney general.
   Lawyer Ken Ross, who had been gathering information for a
possible lawsuit against the veterinarian, last month was named by
the attorney general's office to handle the licensing case. Ms.
Wine-Banks acknowledged the appointment was at her suggestion, but
says she sees no conflict.
   The general counsel for the regulation department said Wednesday
the appointment by a special prosecutor was rare and was made by the
attorney general's office.
   At issue is the death in December 1987 of Finnegan, a 7-year-old
Dalmatian owned by Ms. Wine-Banks and her husband, Michael Banks.
   An autopsy found a ``fibrous substance'' blocking Finnegan's
intestines was the cause of death.
   Ms. Wine-Banks says when she and her husband took the dog to
Wostoupal, he said Finnegan had just eaten some leaves.
   The animal died several days after he was stricken with symptoms
that included vomiting and a loss of appetite.
   Angry about Wostoupal's diagnosis, Ms. Wine-Banks sought
revocation of his license. The regulation agency issued a formal
complaint and scheduled hearings.
   The veterinarian's lawyers, John Huston and Glen Crick, say the
appointment of a special prosecutor is outrageous, and that Ross's
appointment places him in violation of legal ethics.
   The case arises ``from the same facts and circumstances in which
he privately represents the complaining witnesses,'' they said.
   ``Ken represents the state now. He is going to pursue this to
protect the pet owners of Illinois,'' said Ms. Wine-Banks, a
prosecutor in the Watergate burglary coverup revealed after
President Nixon's 1972 re-election campaign.
   She said she suggested Ross for the job after they became
frustrated that Finnegan's case wasn't moving fast enough.
   ``I did what any citizen should do: I went to the state. I have
faith that the system will work,'' Ms. Wine-Banks said.
   ``I don't know that Jill used clout. My guess is she used a
little yelling and screaming,'' said spokeswoman Jeanne Marie
Schultz in the office of Illinois Attorney General Neil Hartigan.
   Ms. Wine-Banks said regulation department officials concurred in
Ross's appointment, but Michael Accettura, general counsel for the
agency, said they had no say.
   ``The attorney general's office has the power to tell us Ross was
our man,'' Accettura said in a telephone interview Wednesday.
   Michael J. Hayes, deputy attorney general, said he approved Ross'
hiring for the case Jan. 25 after the regulations agency agreed to
pay his fee.
   Ross said the department will pay him $160 an hour.
   Accettura agreed the appointment of special prosecutors in such
cases is rare, but refused to comment on the alleged conflict of
interest.
   ``That's for the attorney general to decide. They appointed this
individual,'' he said.
   Accettura said hearings before the department's veterinarian
board are scheduled for next month. The agency director will decide
the matter.
   Board members ``will decide whether a violation occurred or not,
and what penalty should apply _ a two-month suspension or
whatever,'' Accettura said. ``They make a recommendation and the
director acts on it.''
</TEXT>
