<FIRST>r i AM-CentralAmerica-Glance     02-15 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central America-Glance,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Central America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COSTA DEL SOL, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the main points of the
agreement signed Tuesday by the presidents of Nicaragua, El
Salvador, Honduras, Costa Rica and Guatemala.
   Nicaragua said it would:
   _ Hold national and local elections 10 months early, by Feb. 25,
1990.
   _ Give opposition parties equal access to the Sandinista-run
radio and television.
   _ Invite international observers to be present during the
campaign and the election.
   _ Free people classified as political prisoners by the
International Commission on Human Rights.
   The five presidents jointly:
   _ Agreed to devise a plan within 90 days to demobilize the
Nicaraguan rebels and relocate the estimated 11,000 Contra fighters
in Honduran base camps.
   _ Decided to continue talks on having the United Nations send
unarmed military observers to Central America to monitor security
issues.
   The accord does not:
   _ Say what will happen if the Contras refuse repatriation or
relocation.
   _ Say when Nicaragua will free political prisoners.
   _ Say whether early elections in Nicaragua mean the presidential
inauguration now scheduled for January 1991 will also be advanced.
   _ Satisfy a demand for international monitoring of all political
reforms called for by an August 1987 regional peace plan.
   _ Directly address major aspects of the regional plan that call
for an end to continuing civil wars in El Salvador and Guatemala.
   The reaction:
   _ Opposition political leaders in Nicaragua said the Sandinistas
would try to cheat on their election promises and would have to be
watched closely.
   _ Contra leaders expressed skepticism about Nicaraguan promises
and said they and the United States would have to be involved in
negotiating their future.
   _ The United States said it would not lift a four-year ban on
diplomatic contact with the Sandinistas, and Vice President Dan
Quayle said he did not think the accord was a ``death warrant'' for
the Contras.
</TEXT>
