<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     02-15 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Holds Firm To May 1 Election Schedule; Opposition Angry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders on Wednesday said
they will discuss this week whether to boycott the May 1 elections
set by the new military regime.
   The government of Gen. Andres Rodriguez reiterated on Wednesday
that it would not postpone the balloting despite opposition
contentions that there is not enough time to mount an effective
challenge to the ruling Colorado Party.
   ``Gen. Rodriguez expressed in a clear and final manner his vow to
respect the constitution and its laws,'' Gen. Orlando Machuca
Vargas, the interior minister, told reporters.
   ``If we violate those articles of the constitution at the request
of the opposition, we would also be empowered to violate other
articles.''
   The constitution states that in the event of the death,
disability or resignation of a president, elections must be held
within three months.
   Opposition leaders say Rodriguez deposed President Gen. Alfredo
Stroessner by coup on Feb. 3 so the constitutional clause does not
apply.
   ``This clearly shows the ill will of the provisional
government,'' said Domingo Laino, president of the Authentic Liberal
Radical Party. ``They've already violated the constitution with
cannons.''
   Laino said the National Accord opposition coalition planned to
consider Thursday whether to participate in the elections ``under
the existing conditions, which we believe are not the most
propitious for a clean election.
   ``We're not going to do what we refused to do during the
Stroessner years, which is to participate in electoral farces,''
Laino said.
   Machuca Vargas spoke with reporters following a meeting with
Rodriguez, a 65-year-old cavalry general and the presidential
candidate of the ruling Colorado Party.
   Opposition parties filed a formal request for the postponement of
elections with Machuca Vargas on Monday, saying they needed more
time to organize if they were to have any chance of defeating
Colorado candidates. The minister's official reply still was pending.
   In past elections, opposition parties called for the abstention
or casting of blank votes, and thus few of their leaders and members
are included on voter registration lists.
</TEXT>
