<FIRST>u i AM-Balloonist 1stLd-Writethru a0603 02-15 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Balloonist, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0603,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Balloonist Hampered By Technical Problems, Shifting Winds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with more technical problems,
CORRECTS that jet stream heading east sted west, other details; picks up
9th pvs, ``He said...' Edits thereafter to trim</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY49</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese adventurer attempting the first solo
balloon flight across the Pacific Ocean battled shifting winds and
mechanical problems Thursday as he floated three miles above the
Earth, bound for California.
   By 6 a.m. (4 p.m. Wednesday), balloonist Fumio Niwa was 660 miles
southeast of Yokohama and flying at 35 mph at an altitude of 20,000
feet, said his spokesman, Naoko Higashi.
   Niwa set out before dawn Wednesday from Yokohama, near Tokyo, in
a mammoth blue-and-orange helium balloon. Depending solely on the
power and direction of the wind, he hoped to land in San Diego,
Yokohama's sister city.
   During radio contact early Thursday, Niwa described the 56-foot
helium balloon as ``slightly swollen'' and complained of rising
temperatures in some of his instruments. However, neither problem
was considered serious, Higashi said.
   In radio contact made 2{ hours later, Niwa reportedly said he was
descending to 15,000 feet because the balloon was swelling in higher
outside temperatures.
   Otherwise, there was ``nothing unusual,'' Niwa told Higashi.
   On Wednesday, Niwa said the main compressor that maintains air
pressure inside the tiny gondola broke down, but that his backup
compressor was working well.
   Niwa had planned to move directly into the jet stream at an
altitude of 26,000 feet to cover the 5,000 miles to his target in
four days.
   But he changed his mind after discovering the jet stream was
veering north rather than east, as it normally does, and could push
him toward Alaska.
   His trip may now last six days and he has enough food to last 10,
Higashi said.
   ``He said he's going to hang under the jet stream as he
approaches Hawaii before moving up into the winds,'' Higashi said.
   Niwa said earlier he was staying low by holding on to his ballast
so the balloon would drift farther south before entering the jet
stream.
   After his first half day of flight, he commented: ``All I see is
clouds and the ocean. I have nothing to take a picture of.''
   The temperature inside the unheated gondola, an elongated capsule
measuring 6 feet in diameter, was 56 degrees Wednesday evening and
below freezing on the outside, Higashi said. Temperatures could
plunge to minus 75 at such altitudes.
   For heat, Niwa depends on his flying suit, which has built-in
electric coils powered by batteries charged by solar panels outside
the gondola.
   The gondola also is too small to stand up in and lacks
navigational equipment. Niwa relies on amateur radio reports of his
location, drawn from radio beacon signals.
   In 1981, four men traveled by balloon from Japan to the United
States, but no one has crossed the Pacific alone in a balloon.
   Niwa, 38, has about 1,000 hours of ballooning experience, and he
estimated the flight will cost about $540,000.
   He said money constraints kept him from installing alarms to warn
him of a loss of gas in the balloon or a sudden change in altitude.
   Niwa quit his job at a computer company in November to prepare
for the flight. He hopes to recoup his investment from a book and
public appearances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
