<FIRST>u a AM-SeaLions 1stLd-Writethru a0698 02-15 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sea Lions, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0698,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wildlife Agents Engage Sea Lions In New Battle For Migrating Fish</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE2</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with capture of two sea lions;
DELETES references to `Sea Lions 5, Government 0,' since this is 5th year
and DELETES rubber bullets which have NOT been used. Picks up 8th graf,
`We're confident...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wildlife agents tried using a floating cage
Wednesday to capture and deport sea lions that have been devouring
salmon, trout and other migratory fish on Puget Sound.
   So far, the sea lions are winning.
   Fisheries experts over the last five years have tried everything
from foul-tasting chemicals to taped sounds of predatory whales to
stop the huge mammals from depleting the fish runs.
   The latest and sixth plan of attack is a floating cage, which was
set just outside a ship canal to help wildlife agents remove the sea
lions for tagging and then take them 250 miles to the Pacific Ocean
off the southwest Washington coast.
   But the sea lions proved to be worthy opponents for the state and
federal government.
   On Wednesday morning, at least a dozen sea lions were crowded
happily into the cage, which was set out several weeks ago to allow
them to become accustomed to it. Unsure if they could handle that
many sea lions, eight wildlife agents yelled and slapped the water
with paddles to scare them away.
   By Wednesday afternoon, two sea lions had been caught. One of the
sea lions, nicknamed Blue Eye because of a cataract on his eye, has
been a problem for three years, said Bob DeLong, marine mammal
biologist with the National Marine Fisheries Service.
   ``We're confident this plan is going to work,'' said Hal
Alabaster of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
   But not too confident.
   ``At the very least it'll be a good test of how long it takes
them to get back,'' he said of the plan known officially at NOAA as
Operation Goodbye. ``Some are guessing they'll beat the trucks
back.''
   In recent years, nets and steel barriers at the Ballard Locks,
site of the fish ladder for fish returning to spawn, have led to
failure.
   After sea lions simply swam under and over the net, a lumber
company put up a board that read ``Sea Lions 4, Government 0,''
Alabaster said. ``It was pretty embarrassing.''
   Over the years, the sea lions ignored tape recorded sounds of
killer whales, and fish injected with nauseating chemicals failed to
slacken the sea lions' voracious appetites.
   The feasting sea lions have been the bane of fishermen and others
concerned about the salmon run, but they have delighted residents
and tourists who flock to the Ballard Locks to watch the spectacle
and applaud the frolicking animals.
   This year's run of steelhead was about 1,650 at the fish ladder,
down from about 2,600 last year, officials said last month.
   Seven to nine California sea lions ``hanging around'' the locks
are gulping an average of 14 fish a day each, said Bob Byrne, state
Wildlife Department spokesman.
   In Operation Goodbye, the 300- to 800-pound sea lions will be
taken two at a time to a barge, then to a hangar at the Sand Point
Naval Base on Lake Washington, where they will be tagged and
equipped with radio collars so they can be tracked.
   DeLong said moving a sea lion is like moving a ``leather bag
filled with 600 pounds of rocks.''
   Alabaster said if the sea lions return from Long Beach Peninsula,
the next step might be to transport them all the way back to
California.
</TEXT>
