<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-JetFighter     02-15 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Jet Fighter,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Criticism of U.S. Pact Spurs Calls for Japan To Build Own Fighter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three senior parliamentarians urged Japan to develop
its own plane after U.S. congressmen criticized an agreement for
joint U.S.-Japanese development of Japan's next jet fighter, a
newspaper said Wednesday.
   The English-language Japan Times said the three told reporters
this week that Japan should consider abandoning an agreement to
develop its future mainstay fighter using technology from the U.S.
F-16.
   It said former Transport Minister Shintaro Ishihara and two other
legislators suggested Japan should go ahead with development of its
own jet fighter, called the FSX.
   ``Since there clearly are disagreements over the accord, they
suggested that the agreement be reviewed and possibly abandoned,''
an aide to one of the legislators said on condition of anonymity.
   Japan orginally intended to build the jet on its own, but U.S.
government officials and aircraft makers urged Tokyo to buy
U.S.-made F-16 jets to help cut Japan's $47.6 billion trade surplus
with the United States.
   After years of talks, the two sides signed a memorandum of
understanding last November under which Mitsubishi Heavy Industries,
Japan's leading defense contractor, would head development of the
FSX using technology from Japan and from General Dynamics, which
produces the F-16.
   Congress will have 30 days to vote against the project after it
is formally approved by the Bush administration.
   The FSX issue surfaced on Feb. 3 during Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita's visit to Washington, where he urged Bush to line up
congressional support for the agreement.
   Last week, 21 senators introduced a resolution declaring ``strong
reservations'' about the deal and urging a 60-day delay to allow
time for a review.
   In Japan, the criticism of an agreement seen as a concession to
the United States led to renewed calls to develop the plane alone.
   Supporters say it's the best compromise possible given Japan's
refusal to buy F-16s from the United States. They say the
arrangement involves beneficial technology exchanges and will
generate employment in both countries.
   American critics say the agreement virtually gives away $7
billion in advanced aircraft technology that eventually could help
Japan compete effectively against the United States in the global
aviation market, a field in which Japan lags.
   Japanese officials said that despite the uproar they hope to go
ahead with the plan. Japan has appropriated $84.2 million in its
preliminary budget for the fiscal year beginning April 1 for FSX
development.
   Initially, 130 of the jets are to be built, with a possible
follow-up order of about 100 more at a cost of $40.5 million each.
Japan reportedly will maintain control over the FSX design and over
any new technology developed.
   General Dynamics would act as a subcontractor to Mitsubishi and
receive about 35 to 45 percent of the work, funded entirely by the
Japanese government.
   Japan's aviation industry has remained small. It relies mainly on
defense contracts, including development of Japan's current jet
fighter, the F-1, and production of F-15 fighters under license from
McDonnell Douglas of the United States.
</TEXT>
