<SECOND>AM-Honduras-US,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honduran Military Chief Criticizes CIA Chief's Remarks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army chief Humberto Regalado
Hernandez on Wednesday criticized remarks attributed to CIA director
William Webster about alleged military conspiracies to topple Latin
American governments.
   ``The armed forces were not created to govern the country, but to
work within the constitution,'' the military chief said. ``For this
reason, we are bothered by a foreigner questioning what we have
denied and repeated.''
   On Feb. 10, Webster was quoted by the Los Angeles Times as saying
Democrats and Republicans in the United States should agree on
undercover work in Latin America because of growing restlessness and
``coup conspiracies'' in the region.
   In the interview, the CIA chief said some fragile Latin American
democracies depend on the military to maintain law and order.
   The Times quoted Webster as saying U.S. Secretary of State James
Baker must confront difficult situations in other parts of Latin
America and mentioned Nicaragua, Honduras, Panama and Haiti as
possible trouble spots. He said military conspiracies exist to
overthrow various governments.
   Regalado said he wants Webster ``to present his proof of who is
conspiring, because if there is someone under my command, then I
would have to take decisions that the situation merited.''
   Honduras' Congress appointed a special commission Tuesday night
of six deputies, belonging to the nation's four active political
parties, to investigate the matter and issue a report in 30 days.
   The group plans to interview U.S. Ambassador Everett E. Briggs
and then key military leaders.
   The Congress mandated the group ``try to discover the truth about
the alleged conspiracy that exists in the country that intends to
change the government.''
   Charles Barclay, spokesman at the U.S. Embassy, said, ``The
United States will continue its constant support to democratic
institutions in Latin America.''
   ``What Webster said is that the administration of President
George Bush will have as its principal policy the strengthening of
democratic Latin America, and he warned that the future of the
region is highly unpredictable because the hemisphere is confronting
serious threats to democracy.''
