<FIRST>r a AM-HarvardEthics     02-15 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Harvard Ethics,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rumors Of Impropriety Spur Harvard Business Students To Discuss Honor
Code</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethics already is required study for Harvard
University business students, but campus activists said Wednesday
they want an honor code to prevent even the rumor of a breach in
their computerized classrooms.
   ``We're not terrible, amoral people here,'' said Anthony
Antonick, ``If we can come up with some sort of list to go by, I
think people would conform to the rules.''
   Antonick is one of a group of business students that organized in
reaction to recent rumors of borderline behavior during classroom
testing. The students are hoping in the coming months to pool their
opinions and come up with a formal code that the school might
eventually adopt.
   ``There are clearly things that are right and clearly things that
are wrong,'' said Earl Sasser, chairman of the master's degree
program in business administration. ``But where things are less
clear, there is for me the need for some kind of honor code.''
   The 80-year-old business school has left students on their honor,
free to take breaks during exams and remain after the testing period
was up to print out their answers.
   Since the school began requiring students to use personal
computers in the classrooms, questions of impropriety have cropped
up. Is it acceptable for people to exchange diskettes during exams?
Should students be allowed to print out their answers after the
allotted test time is up? If so, would it be cheating to correct a
typographical error?
   When rumors began circulating on campus that there had been some
cheating during final exams, concerned first-year students began
discussions on ethics.
   Antonick said he and others who organized an informal survey
recently were surprised at the disparity among students' opinions of
what might constitute an ethical compromise.
   ``We're looking at not only dos and don'ts of test-taking but
also at issues of what's acceptable in terms of classroom
preparation and participation,'' said Jennifer Raiser, a survey
organizer.
   Last fall, the school's 800 first-year students were required for
the first time to take a three-week course in ethics, spurred in
large part by a $20 million gift from former Securities and Exchange
Commission Chairman John Shad.
   But the school's own policy toward cheating and other ethical
questions was not sufficiently clear, Raiser said.
   ``We're trying to draw the line between competitiveness and
fairness,'' Raiser said. ``You can be competitive, but there are
still some guidelines of decency that people can and should abide
by.''
</TEXT>
