<FIRST>r i AM-Vatican     02-15 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Attacks Theologians Who Question Birth Control Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican on Wednesday took to task
theologians who question the church ban on contraception and accused
them of sowing confusion among the faithful.
   A front-page editorial in the daily newspaper L`Osservatore
Romano repeated a statement by Pope John Paul II that the ban is not
open to discussion.
   It did not cite anyone by name but mentioned recent remarks by
``one noted moral theologian'' and challenges to the church teaching
by other theologians.
   Last month, a group of 170 German-speaking theologians released a
statement called the Cologne Declaration that strongly criticized
the pope and the ban on artificial birth control.
   The Italian press earlier quoted another German theologian,
Bernard Haring, as attacking one of the pope's advisers on family
issues.
   The editorial responding to criticism carried three asterisks at
the end, the newspaper's way of showing it was authoritative.
   The editorial said married couples having difficulties living up
to the church's teaching for personal, economic or social reasons
deserve ``great respect and love.''
   But it said there was also need to affirm that the moral norms in
Pope Paul VI's 1968 encyclical ``Humane Vitae,'' which barred
aritificial birth control, ``do not allow exceptions.''
   It said this was no ``rigid and intransigent'' interpretation but
has been the ``clear and explicit teaching'' of both Paul VI and
John Paul II.
   L`Osservatore Romano said doubts raised over the Roman Catholic
Church's teaching on the family amounted to a ``concerted and
systematic'' attack by some theologians and lamented what it called
the ``serious confusion and misunderstandings'' caused among the
faithful.
   It repeated remarks by John Paul in June 1987 that ``what is
taught by the church on contraception is not a matter that can be
discussed freely by theologians. To teach otherwise is tantamount to
inducing into error the moral conscience of the married.''
</TEXT>
