<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-CrashEngines     02-15 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Crash Engines,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fan Blade Broke In Engine of Crashed Jet, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fan blade broke in the left engine of a Boeing
737 before the aircraft crashed on Jan. 8, killing 47 people, a
French engine manufacturer was quoted as saying Wednesday.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. said it obtained a document being
circulated by the French company SNECMA. It said the document urges
airline companies to check engines similiar to those on the British
Midland Airways jet that crashed in central England.
   SNECMA, which builds the CFM-56 engine with General Electric of
the United States, stripped down both engines from the jet at its
headquarters at Villaroche near Paris.
   The BBC quoted the document as saying a fan blade had broken in
the Boeing's left engine but the cause of the crash still had not
been established.
   Engineers found no evidence of a malfunction in the right engine,
which was shut down by the pilot before the crash, the BBC quoted
the document as saying.
   The accident investigation team's metallurgists were quoted as
saying there was metal fatigue on one fan blade in the left engine.
That fan blade fractured and apparently then pierced the engine's
cowling or outer skin, the BBC said.
   SNECMA was quoted as saying it was not known why the fan blade
fractured in what was a virtually new engine. Nothing similar has
occurred in any other CFM-56 engines during their 5.5 million flying
hours, the BBC said.
   Nonetheless, the BBC said the company recommended that all
airlines using SNECMA engines review their policies and instructions
on the maintenance and repair of the fan blades.
</TEXT>
