<HEAD>Foreign Ownership Disclosure Fight Flares Anew in House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House minority leader, Rep. Robert H.
Michel, R-Ill., said Wednesday he would try to block floor action on
legislation requiring disclosure of foreign owners of U.S. property.
   ``It has very serious implications for the faltering financial
industry and the potential international repercussions are
considerable,'' Michel said in a letter to the House Rules Committee
chairman, Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla.
   The bill, scheduled for floor action Thursday, would require
foreign owners to report sizable holdings in this country to the
federal government.
   Sponsored by Rep. John Bryant, D-Texas, the plan started life as
part of the 1,000-page trade bill that was signed into law last year
but was dropped long before the trade measure reached the
president's desk.
   The administration said it would stifle vitally needed foreign
investment and hurt business in a variety of other ways. Bryant said
Americans deserve to know who owns property in this country.
   Michel said the bill, heavily debated last year, should have been
sent to committee again for a fresh hearing before being brought to
the floor.
   ``Having just read the preliminary floor schedule for next week,
I find myself imploring you to `tell me it ain't so,''' said
Michel's letter to Pepper, who as Rules Committee chairman cleared
the way for the vote.
   ``This is a new Congress, a new century of government, with a new
president, new direction and constantly changing public opinions and
circumstances,'' Michel said.
   Wright was en route to Texas and thus had not seen Michel's
letter, according to an aide, Mark Johnson.
   The letter was distributed to reporters by the Republican
leader's office.
   An increase in foreign investment in U.S. property in recent
years has prompted concern on Capitol Hill, although a two-year-old
study by the General Accounting Office, an investigative arm of
Congress, found that overseas owners still held only a tiny
percentage of American farm land.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
