<FIRST>u a AM-KidnappingArrest     02-15 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kidnapping Arrest,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Arrested In Texas In Connection With Abduction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>APPLING, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-age girl abducted from her home by a
man answering an ad for a water bed was held handcuffed in a closet
before she escaped and, in a fortunate coincidence, got to meet
President Bush Wednesday on Air Force One.
   Just as strange as the ordeal authorities say the 17-year-old
endured is the story of the kidnapping suspect.
   Richard D. Starrett, 29, was arrested late Tuesday while napping
in his red sports car at a rest stop on Interstate 10 near Houston,
authorities said.
   Starrett has no known criminal record, Lexington County Sheriff
James Metts said, and is an engineer at a federal nuclear weapons
facility, the Savannah River Plant near Aiken, S.C., across the
river from Georgia, his employer said.
   Starrett was barefoot when he awoke to find a 12-gauge shotgun
pointed at him, Trooper Kevin Kennedy said by telephone from Texas.
   ``He didn't really say a whole heck of a lot of anything,''
Kennedy said. ``I asked him if he was Richard Daniel Starrett. He
said, `Yes, I am.'''
   Starrett of Martinez, Ga., was jailed in Houston and was to be
returned to Georgia and South Carolina, said Columbia County, Ga.,
Sheriff Otis Hensley. Starrett was charged in federal and state
warrants with kidnapping, and Georgia authorities added aggravated
sodomy and false imprisonment warrants Tuesday.
   The 17-year-old was abducted from her home in Lexington, S.C., on
Feb. 6. She remained in protective custody Tuesday, when a law
enforcement officer took her to see the presidential limousine that
was flown from Washington to Columbia, S.C., where Bush delivered a
speech Wednesday.
   South Carolina Gov. Carroll Campbell said he happened to meet the
teen-ager at the airport, and she expressed an interest in seeing
the president. Campbell, a Republican, told her she could do so at
the airport the next day.
   Bush gave her a presidential pin as a memento of their meeting,
the governor said.
   Bush ``expressed his sympathy for what she went through,''
Campbell said. ``That little girl has been through hell.''
   Authorities said the high school senior was abducted at gunpoint
and held for four days in a house in Martinez, near Augusta, part of
the time handcuffed and in a small closet.
   She escaped last Saturday from the house, which authorities say
Starrett owns. She told authorities she fled when her abductor fell
asleep, running to a neighboring home to call her family.
   Investigators said they seized videotapes from Starrett's house
showing the two together, but they would not elaborate on the
contents. They kept the girl's location secret Wednesday.
   Kennedy said the arrest followed a routine computer check on
Starrett's out-of-state license tag. He said he called for backup
before making the arrest, and added that Starrett had a .38-caliber
revolver between his legs on the car seat when arrested.
   ``He said he had been in Texas, in the Houston area, for three
days,'' Kennedy said, adding that Starrett had no money or credit
cards.
   Metts said an investigation indicated Starrett was having
drinking problems and problems at home and on the job. He said
authorities want to question Starrett in connection with at least
four other South Carolina disappearances, abductions or sexual
assaults that took place after a man answered a want ad.
   Starrett is employed by Bechtel National Inc. of San Francisco, a
contractor at the Savannah River Plant. Company spokesman Rick
Laubscher said Starrett began working for Bechtel in October and was
assigned to SRP for work on the federal government's Defense Waste
Processing Facility.
</TEXT>
