<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru   02-15 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0816,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Skeptical Of Ortega's Promises Of Electoral Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0816 to correct writethru sequence. LEADS with
7 grafs to UPDATE with Ortega's nationwide speech. Pick up 6th pvs, `Nevertheless,
Arguello...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Central America, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders said Wednesday they
are pleased President Daniel Ortega has promised electoral reform
but added that the Sandinistas must be watched carefully or they'll
try to cheat.
   ``President Ortega only talked with the Central American
presidents, but he still needs to talk with the Nicaraguan people,''
said Gilberto Cuadra, president of the opposition Superior Council
of Private Enterprise.
   Ortega announced Tuesday at the end of a two-day regional summit
in El Salvador that Nicaragua will hold early elections, permit the
opposition freedom to campaign and allow United Nations observers
into the country.
   Ortega and the presidents of Honduras, El Salvador, Guatemala and
Costa Rica also announced they will devise a plan within 90 days to
dismantle the U.S.-backed Nicaraguan rebel force, known as the
Contras.
   In a nationally televised speech Wednesday night, Ortega went
over the summit points and said his government's willingness to
institute election reform ``shows our political strength which is
rooted in the Nicaraguan people.''
   Miriam Arguello, secretary general of the Nicaraguan Conservative
Party, said in an interview in El Salvador that the opposition will
play watchdog.
   ``We can be sure that the Sandinistas, in spite of their
signature, will do whatever they can get away with to win,''
Arguello said. ``But we will fight to make them comply with their
agreements.''
   Nevertheless, Arguello said, ``The four democratic presidents of
Central America have given the Nicaraguan opposition a weapon that
we can use to say for ourselves who will govern us.''
   Also on Wednesday, the government announced the cordoba's fourth
devaluation this year. Fuel prices automatically increased, and a
rise in the price of basic foods was expected shortly as a result of
the 18.5 percent devaluation of the Nicaraguan currency.
   The leftist Sandinistas have been hurt by the crash of the
Nicaraguan economy, which has resulted in 20,000 percent annual
inflation. They blame most of their problems on a U.S. economic
boycott and the war against the Contras.
   They face an opposition split into at least 14 parties, and
Arguello and others said that advancing the elections by 10 months,
to February 1990, would actually give the Sandinistas an advantage.
   ``We see advancing the elections as a typical Sandinista game.
They look like they are willing to sacrifice time in office, but
they also leave less time for the organization and mobilization of
the parties,'' she said.
   She said the period for organization of parties was short,
``given that the opposition has been repressed, restricted and
terrorized.''
   ``There remains much to discuss in this country,'' Cuadra, whose
council is Nicaragua's largest grouping of businessmen, said in an
interview broadcast by Radio Noticias, an independent private radio
station.
   Jose Antonio Bonilla of a faction of the Social-Christian Party
told The Associated Press that advancing the elections left too
little time for ``the development and adequate organization of the
political bodies.''
   Luis Vega Miranda, an official of another faction of the
Social-Christian Party, called Ortega's promises ``superficial.''
   Upon his return to Nicaragua on Tuesday night, Ortega called the
presidential agreement to dismantle the Contras ``the final blow to
the war.''
   An estimated 11,000 rebels and about 10,000 family members are
living in camps on Honduran territory along the Nicaraguan border.
It remained unclear how the agreement at the summit would directly
affect the Contras.
   Wednesday's devaluation, announced by the Central Bank, raised
the cordoba's official rate of exchange to 3,200 cordobas to the
U.S. dollar, up from 2,700 cordobas to the dollar. Fuel prices also
rose as of Wednesday: the price of a gallon of gasoline went from
5,600 cordobas to 6,700 cordobas.
   In January the cordoba was devalued three times.
   Ortega announced on Jan. 30 an austerity plan for 1989 to combat
inflation. He has said at least 30,000 public employees will be laid
off and many government subsidies will be eliminated.
</TEXT>
