<FIRST>u a AM-CruiseShipAccident     02-15 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cruise Ship Accident,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Luxury Liner Strikes Anchored Navy Vessel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 400-foot luxury liner attempting
to dock in the Port of Palm Beach Wednesday night hit an anchored
Navy ship and tore several holes in the 110-foot vessel, the U.S.
Coast Guard said.
   The accident involving the Viking Princess and the unnamed naval
cargo loading craft at about 7:30 p.m. caused no serious injuries to
passengers or crew, said Coast Guard Petty Officer Jerry Snyder.
   ``It's a very small harbor,'' with only two shipping channels and
a small area where the cruise liners have to turn around, said
Snyder.
   Two Coast Guard utility boats plugged three holes below the Navy
vessel's water line, and minor flooding was quickly brought under
control, Snyder said. No fuel was known to have leaked into the
harbor.
   Some passengers of the Viking Princess were shaken up, but the
crew was able to care for them without assistance, Snyder said.
   The West Palm Beach-based ship, owned by Crown Cruise Lines, was
returning from an all-day Florida coastline cruise, which it runs
three days a week. The other four days a week it sails on a day
cruise to Freeport, Bahamas.
   Five days earlier, the Miami-based Celebration, owned by Carnival
Cruise Lines, sliced a Cuban cargo vessel in two, leaving three
Cuban crew members missing off the Cuban coast. No cruise passengers
were injured.
</TEXT>
