<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 2011EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:SegregatedMusic Adv19   02-15 1232</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Segregated Music, Adv 19,1265</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 19, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Arts: Grammys</HEAD>
<HEAD>Grammys Camouflage Music Industry's Racial Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   On the eve of the Grammy awards ceremony, a black
singer-songwriter is the record industry's uncrowned queen. Tracy
Chapman swept most major categories for her groundbreaking debut
album, receiving six nominations.
   Michael Jackson is looking to add to his trophy collection with
the gospel-tinged ``Man in the Mirror,'' while Bobby McFerrin, with
five nominations, Anita Baker and Whitney Houston are also
contending for big awards. All are black and all have been nominated
for the National Academy of Recording Arts &amp; Sciences' most
prestigious award, Record of the Year.
   It would appear that the music industry is free from racial
strife. A look beneath the surface, however, says otherwise.
   According to minorities and others in the business, and the
nation's oldest civil rights group, not only do blacks have
difficulty getting their music heard _ except for the superstars _
they also are kept from the corporate jobs that drive the industry.
   Music history has its share of bigotry: white artists remaking
black hits for white audiences and reaping the financial rewards;
pioneer rockers such as Bo Diddley who were underpaid or not paid
and had to fight for every dime; Motown artists who kept their black
faces off album covers. And few can ever forget that rhythm and
blues was once referred to as ``race music'' and its artists were
treated like third-class citizens.
   But it's more than history. A scathing report by the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People in 1987 concluded
the record industry is ``overwhelmingly segregated and
discrimination is rampant.'' Blacks are blocked from advancing at
every level, said the NAACP.
   Two years later, little has changed, said Fred Rasheed, author of
the report.
   ``We have to constantly remind ourselves that this is just music,
that we have to break down these barriers,'' said Ramon Hervey, a
manager who's steered the careers of such artists as Luther Vandross
and Andrae Crouch. ``It's just ingrained into the record companies.''
   The music business is like sports, where there are plenty of
blacks on the playing field but few in the manager's chair or
owner's office, the NAACP said. It is also mirrors the Hollywood
movie industry in which one or two black superstars generate
tremendous box office for studios that have no black executives at
the helm or in decision-making positions.
   This doesn't mean much for chart-topping artists such as Jackson
and Houston; their music gets heard regardless of who's working
behind the scenes.
   But it means a lot for artists such as Vandross, Aretha Franklin,
Rick James and even Stevie Wonder. They're on the second echelon.
Record company promotion people plug records by these musicians
first at black radio stations. If the records aren't big hits on the
black charts, chances are they won't be heard on the radio stations
that cater to a larger consumer group.
   And having a hit on ``urban'' radio stations _ a euphemism for
black audiences _ is no guarantee the record will ``cross over'' to
pop charts. That's a lesson newcomer Vanessa Williams learned very
quickly when ``The Right Stuff'' hit No. 1 on the black charts but
couldn't dent the pop Top 40.
   ``I believe it could have been a much bigger hit on pop (radio)
if I had more support promotion-wise,'' said Williams, a former Miss
America.
   The question of whether black artists get pop hits is
inextricably tied to the hiring patterns within the industry. The
high-powered music business jobs that decide where a company puts
its promotional muscle are almost all filled by whites, said
Billboard's Nelson George. Blacks are steered to the black music
division of a record company, he said.
   ``Most blacks are in the promotion area _ these are the ones that
are calling on radio stations _ and are not necessarily in the
mainstream of the business area of the company,'' said LeBaron
Taylor, vice president and general manager for corporate affairs at
CBS Records.
   ``Very few black acts have longevity as pop artists,'' said
Hervey, who manages and is married to Williams. ``I can't think
historically of any black artist who can consistently release albums
and be successful on the pop charts without being successful on the
black charts.''
   Stevie Wonder was at that point in the 1970s, when he raked in
awards and smash hits with ease. But today, the Rock and Roll Hall
of Fame member has trouble getting on the pop charts.
   Stunted racial attitudes have even led to a few tragic-comic
situations.
   The Detroit band Was (Not Was), which has two whites and two
blacks and play an eclectic mix of soul and rock, was not allowed by
its former record company to include pictures with promotional
materials sent to radio stations.
   ``They didn't want black radio to know there were white people
involved with the band, nor white people to see there were black
people involved,'' said band member David Weiss, currently riding
high with the band's hit ``Walk the Dinosaur.''
   Rick James (``Super Freak (Part 1)'') can't get his videos on
MTV, while black video stations have complained he has too many
whites in his clips, said his manager and brother, Leroi Johnson.
   For a good part of the '80s MTV refused to play videos of black
artists, saying they didn't fit with their rock format. The practice
ended when CBS Records threatened to pull all its videos from the
station if MTV didn't show Michael Jackson.
   ``Most record companies in America are looking to do what Geffen
Records did with Guns 'n Roses,'' Weiss said. ``They're looking to
find that band that's going to tear the heads off white America. ...
It's a game of numbers.''
   Many blacks are just as rigid in their views of what music should
or shouldn't be as whites. There was a lot of grumbling among
blacks, George said, when George Michael, who is white, had big hits
on the ``black'' charts.
   ``You may say there's a lot of segregation and stereotyping, but
a lot of the stereotyping is self-inflicted,'' he said. ``Blacks
can't keep blaming the white establishment. A lot of it comes from
the inside.''
   Another problem is that successful black artists rarely bring
other blacks into the business with them, the NAACP's Rasheed said.
Also, only a handful of major black artists have black managers.
   No one in the industry disputed the NAACP report, but responses
were left to the individual companies, said Trish Heimers of the
Recording Industry Association of America.
   However, said Rasheed, ``The attitude of most record company
executives was to ignore it and hope it goes away.''
   Both Warner Bros. Records and CBS Records have programs to
advance minorities, although both stressed it wasn't in response to
the NAACP report. They also couldn't say how many blacks are
employed.
   ``I believe that it is healthier than the report indicates,''
said Tom Draper, vice president for community relations at Warner
Bros.
   But it's important, Draper said, not to let the success shown by
Grammy nominees deceive people into thinking total racial harmony
has been achieved.
   ``We need more Tracy Chapmans to break through, more artists who
don't conform to stereotypes,'' George said. ``That's really
crucial. The industry follows the artist.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
