<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     02-15 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0830</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer spending began the year on a sunny
note as retail sales rose 0.6 percent in January, the government
said in a report that added to concerns the economy is speeding
forward so quickly it may fuel inflation.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that retail sales rose last
month to a seasonally adjusted $138.9 billion. That followed a
revised 0.1 percent decrease in December and a 1.3 percent increase
in November.
   Also Tuesday, automakers reported that sales of North
American-made cars and light trucks fell 15.2 percent in early
February from the same time last year, when automakers were offering
a larger and more varied group of incentives.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home prices skyrocketed in California last year
and continued to command top dollar in the Northeast, while sales
picked up in the lower-cost South and Midwest, a real estate trade
group reported.
   The National Association of Realtors said Tuesday that prices of
existing homes rose 3.4 percent to a national median of $87,900 in
the last three months of 1988 compared with the same period a year
earlier.
   The modest increase in median prices occurred as sales shifted
toward lower-cost areas of the country and shoppers purchased less
costly dwellings rather than leave the housing market.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration vowed to fight any
effort by savings and loan lobbyists to preserve their close
relationship with federal regulators and said it's ready to work
with Congress to gain speedy passage of the president's plan to deal
with the industry's crisis.
   Richard C. Breeden, Bush's top adviser on S&amp;Ls, also said Tuesday
the president's proposal to restructure the thrift regulatory system
is inseparable from any infusion of taxpayer money.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp. agreed to pay $470
million to the government of India in a surprise court-ordered
settlement resulting from the 1984 gas leak at Bhopal that killed
more than 3,300 people in the world's worst industrial disaster.
   Activists in Bhopal denounced Tuesday's settlement as a betrayal
of the 20,000 victims who still suffer from exposure to the deadly
gas that escaped from a pesticides plant on Dec. 3, 1984.
   The government had sought $3 billion in damages.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. said its fourth-quarter
profit soared 67.5 percent from a year earlier and that it posted
record earnings for all of 1988.
   GM's earnings, reported Tuesday, mean the nation's biggest
automaker will issue $114 million in profit-sharing checks to some
470,000 hourly employees, the first such payments since fiscal 1985.
   In the three months ended Dec. 31, GM had net income of $1.4
billion, or $4.25 a share, up from $835.8 million, or $2.36 a share,
in the same period of 1987. Revenue during the quarter rose to $32.4
billion from $29.7 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago Board of Trade Chairman Karsten Mahlmann
said he was not personally involved in his trading firm's hiring
last year of two men who have since been indicted on federal fraud
charges.
   The two salesmen, Michael N. Kolb and Jan Y. Biesiadecki, were
indicted by a federal grand jury Jan. 17 on charges they defrauded
investors while working for First Commodity Corp. of Boston, a
futures brokerage that collapsed in 1986 after its expulsion from
the MidAmerica Commodity Exchange, a Board of Trade affiliate.
   Mahlmann said Tuesday that he had not been involved with
individual hirings over the past two years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Threatened with a possible strike March 3 by
militant machinists, Eastern Airlines has introduced ``Super
Coupons'' offering passengers sizable discounts if they fly after
that date.
   Some analysts and travel agents said Tuesday that the coupons,
offered during the peak winter travel period, marked a desperate
move by the strapped airline.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. and Kobe Steel Ltd. of Japan
announced a joint venture to operate USX's plant in Lorain, Ohio.
   Kobe, the last of Japan's big integrated steelmakers to join with
a comparable U.S. producer, said Tuesday it will pay an undisclosed
sum to buy half the plant.
   The deal leaves only Bethlehem Steel Corp., the third-largest
U.S. producer, without a partner from the Far East.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market turned in an indecisive showing Tuesday after
rising interest rates helped blunt an early advance. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials closed with a 1.25 point loss at 2,281.25.
   The dollar dropped against most major currencies. Gold prices
were mixed.
   Bond prices finished lower, pulled down by a sagging dollar in
world currency trading.
   Soybean and corn futures rose sharply; cattle futures were mostly
lower; pork mostly was higher; precious metals were mixed and energy
futures mostly declined.
</TEXT>
