<DOCNO> AP890215-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Smith&amp;WessonAds     02-15 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smith &amp; Wesson Ads,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women's Magazines Refusing To Carry Handgun Ads Aimed At Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE FAHLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smith &amp; Wesson is trying to sell a new line of
handguns to women, but several leading women's magazines are
refusing to carry the gunmaker's advertisements for the petite
``LadySmith'' .38 revolvers.
   ``We would not accept that category of advertising,'' said John
de Holl, director of advertising services for Woman's Day magazine
in New York. ``It would be against the policy of the magazine to run
any advertisements for firearms.''
   Woman's Day is not alone. Smith &amp; Wesson officials say New
York-based Conde Nast Publications, including Mademoiselle, Glamour
and Self, and Des Moines-based Meredith Group's Better Homes &amp;
Gardens all have rejected ads for the LadySmiths.
   ``We do not accept handgun ads for any of our magazines _ even
Playboy,'' said a representative of Conde Nast's West Coast
advertising firm, who asked not to be identified. Playboy is not
published by Conde Nast.
   ``Some publications I have approached have turned down the ads,''
said Michael Shypula, director of advertising and promotions for the
Springfield, Mass.-based gunmaker. ``I think the bias is against the
Smith &amp; Wesson name...since there are no guns in our ads.''
   Smith &amp; Wesson last month unveiled the new line of four handguns,
the LadySmiths, at a trade show in Dallas. The guns _ all
.38-caliber revolvers _ have been scaled down to better fit a
woman's hand.
   Shypula said advertisements for the guns will focus on public
safety. The ads will not feature pictures of the guns, but rather
illustrations of women in typical pre-crime situations _ stuck on
the side of the road with car trouble or hearing a noise the middle
of the night.
   Rather than carrying the name of the guns, the ad will have a
toll-free 800-number Smith &amp; Wesson is setting up for women to talk
to a female gun specialist about purchasing a handgun.
   ``We're using illustrations,'' Shypula said. ``None of them show
anyone in a dangerous situation. A lot of our ads tell women to call
the police.''
   The ad with the woman with car trouble carries the headline:
``This is no place to take a walk.'' The one featuring a
startled-looking woman in bed reads: ``Things that go `bump' in the
night aren't always your imagination.''
   ``I want to inform women, I don't want to offend women,'' Shypula
said, adding the ads do not specifically advocate buying a gun.
``People who want to learn more about it, can pick up the phone and
dial the toll-free number to talk to someone about it.''
   Shypula said the ads will run for about four months, beginning in
April issues of these magazines: Country Home, Executive Female,
First, Harpers Bazaar, Lady's Home Journal, McCalls, Metropolitan
Home, Redbook, Shape, Town &amp; Country, Vanity Fair, Women's Sports
and Fitness, Working Mother, Working Woman.
   But Andrea Kaplan, spokeswoman for the Working Woman-McCall's
Group magazines, said none of the company's three publications,
including Working Mother, will be running the ads.
   ``I think there had been some discussion about them, but our
publisher decided not to run the ads,'' she said.
   Barbara Lautmann, spokeswoman for the Washington-based Handgun
Control Inc., criticized Smith &amp; Wesson when the LadySmiths were
introduced. She said the company and the National Rifle Association
have tried to boost sagging handgun sales by presenting women with a
fear campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890215-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Carbide-Analysis Bjt   02-15 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carbide-Analysis, Bjt,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Carbide's Payment Is Smaller Than Drexel Settlement</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp. is paying millions less to
settle claims from a chemical leak that killed thousands of people
in India than Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. is paying for white-collar
crime on Wall Street.
   To some legal experts, the comparison between Union Carbide's
$470 million payment and Drexel's $650 million settlement suggests
that Union Carbide got off lightly, while to others, it indicates
Drexel was overpunished.
   In either case, differences in the treatment of Carbide and
Drexel point up oddities in the way legal systems deal with
allegations of corporate crime and negligence.
   ``There's no doubt in anyone's mind that the Bhopal incident is
more serious than the Drexel Burnham Lambert case. But whoever said
that rationality prevails in the administration of justice?'' said
Robert Figlio, adjunct professor of legal studies at the University
of Pennsylvania's Wharton School.
   Carbide agreed Tuesday to pay $470 million to the government of
India in a surprise court-ordered settlement resulting from the Dec.
3, 1984, gas leak at Bhopal that killed more than 3,300 people in
the world's worst industrial disaster.
   Activists in Bhopal denounced the settlement as a betrayal of the
20,000 victims who still suffer from exposure to the deadly gas that
escaped from a pesticide plant. The government had sought $3 billion
in damages.
   In Drexel's case, the Wall Street firm that pioneered ``junk
bond'' financing agreed in December to pay $650 million in fines and
restitution and to plead guilty to six felony accounts.
   The plea bargain, which awaits the approval of a federal court
and the Securities and Exchange Commission, averted a lengthy trial
over charges of insider trading and stock manipulation.
   Which corporation committed a more serious offense?
   The National Survey of Crime Severity, which asked more than
50,000 Americans in the late 1970s to rank offenses ranging from
loitering to murderous bombing, gives some hint that Carbide would
be considered the more serious offender.
   Price-fixing between large corporations, a crime similar to
Drexel's, was given a relatively mild score of 9.2 in the survey.
   Willful pollution of a city water supply that resulted in 20
deaths, the closest approximation of Carbide's offense, was rated
extremely serious at 39.1.
   Several factors complicate the comparison, however. For one,
Carbide's chemical leak was not a willful act by senior management,
although prosecutors charged that the company was criminally
derelict in its duty to ensure the plant's safety.
   The U.S. government could get more out of Drexel than the Indian
government could get out of Carbide because it had more legal
leverage over the company.
   Also, $470 million goes a lot farther in India than it would in
the United States. Differences in the cost of living amplify the
actual value of Carbide's payment.
   Carbide's average payment per life lost is about $140,000. That
is nearly 100 times as much as an Indian court had ever ordered in
payment for deaths in cases that involved government, such as train
wrecks, according to Curtis Tarr, dean of Cornell University's
Johnson Graduate School of Management.
   Tarr said he had no figures on cases involving liability of
private entities.
   ``The difference between the cases is that Carbide has always
sensed a responsibility and wanted to do what they could,'' Tarr
said. ``In the Drexel thing, you have quite a different situation,
where some people were operating in a kind of a gray area of
legality.''
   Drexel might have gotten off more lightly five or 10 years ago,
before revelations about E.F. Hutton &amp; Co., Dennis Levine, Ivan
Boesky and others caused a wave of public outrage over insider
dealings on Wall Street.
   Today, Figlio said, ``You've got a whole buildup of sentiment
against that activity in all levels of society.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Editor's Note: Peter Coy has been a New York-based business
reporter for The Associated Press for four years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890215-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CommoditiesProbe Bjt   02-15 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe, Bjt,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Of Trade Executives Say Dual Trading Misunderstood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dual trading is a misunderstood and essential
element of the commodity futures markets, and its potential for
abuse can be offset by closer surveillance, say top officials of the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Dual trading, the practice among floor brokers of trading both
for their own accounts and those of brokerage-firm customers, has
long been cited by critics as a potential source of fraud.
   The debate has heated up since the revelation Jan. 19 of a broad
federal investigation of suspected trading fraud at the Chicago
Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   But Board of Trade Chairman Karsten Mahlmann and President Thomas
Donovan said Tuesday that dual trading helps ensure active, liquid
markets by providing an incentive for floor brokers to stay in the
pits and trade when the flow of orders from the public runs slow.
   Federal rules require brokers to execute all their pending
customer orders before trading for their own accounts, thus giving
customers the first crack at profiting from price fluctuations.
   Mahlmann said the exchange's board of directors voted to
tentatively retain dual trading, a decision announced last week,
because ``through the expansion of the surveillance system we could
eliminate any and all potential abuses of dual trading and keep the
benefit.''
   The rival Chicago Mercantile Exchange is still considering making
changes in its trading rules, including dual trading.
   ``There's nothing wrong with dual trading per se,'' Donovan said.
``The problem is when someone would trade ahead of a customer. And
we can detect that abuse.''
   The Board of Trade hopes to better detect such abuses through a
$1 million upgrade this year of its computerized trade
reconstruction system, an electronic system that officials estimate
can now catch about 90 percent of all improper trades. The goal is
100 percent.
   On another matter, Mahlmann said he was not involved in the
hiring by his own brokerage firm of two salesmen who have since been
indicted on fraud charges.
   The two salesmen, Michael N. Kolb and Jan Y. Biesiadecki, were
indicted by a federal grand jury Jan. 17 on charges they defrauded
investors while working for First Commodity Corp. of Boston, a
futures brokerage firm that collapsed in 1986 after its expulsion
from the MidAmerica Commodity Exchange, a Board of Trade affiliate.
   Sixteen other former First Commodity employees also were indicted.
   Mahlmann is the chairman of Stotler &amp; Co., a large Chicago-based
commodity futures brokerage that hired Kolb and Biesiadecki last
year, according to records of the National Futures Association, a
self-regulatory arm of the futures industry.
   Kolb, hired in March 1988, still works for Stotler. Biesiadecki,
hired in November 1988, left Stotler on Jan. 24 and is currently not
registered with the National Futures Association.
   The hirings of former First Commodity salesmen by Stotler and by
RB&amp;H Inc., a brokerage firm headed by a high-ranking executive of
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, have raised questions about the
industry's ability to police itself.
   Mahlmann said Board of Trade activities had consumed ``almost 100
percent'' of his time over the past two years and that he had not
been involved with individual hirings at Stotler during that time.
   He also said all salespeople hired by Stotler had been registered
with the National Futures Association, which is funded by the
nation's 11 futures exchanges through a per-trade fee on public
transactions and carries a federal mandate to screen and register
all commodities salespeople.
   ``As a brokerage firm, there is a reliance that goes with the
registration,'' he said.
   But Robert Wilmouth, president and chief executive officer of the
Chicago-based association, said hiring decisions ultimately are made
by brokerage firms.
   RB&amp;H is headed by John F. Sandner, the immediate past chairman of
the Chicago Merc, who now holds the title of senior policy adviser
at the exchange.
   RB&amp;H employed at least three former First Commodity salesmen last
year, all of whom left the firm before they were indicted.
   Sandner has said he was not directly involved in the hirings and
that his firm has not had any customer complaints relating to their
activities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890215-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-India-CarbideImpact Bjt   02-15 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Carbide Impact, Bjt,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carbide Settlement Buoys Walls Street, Dismays Liability Lawyers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp.'s $470 million
settlement with the Indian government over the 1984 Bhopal gas leak
pleased Wall Street but was criticized by a prominent attorney who
originally was involved in the case.
   ``They got off criminally cheap,'' said Melvin Belli, the
attorney who represented the interests of about 2,000 plaintiffs
before the cases were transferred from U.S. courts to India.
   ``We had that amount of money two years ago in New York and it
wasn't enough and it isn't enough,'' Belli said Tuesday in a
telephone interview from San Francisco. He added that he thought two
or three times the $470 million would have been fairer.
   The stock market, however, was delighted by the settlement, which
was ordered by the Supreme Court of India, sitting in New Delhi.
   Union Carbide's stock price soared $2.12{ to $31.25 a share in
New York Stock Exchange trading after news of the settlement and the
company's estimate that it expected a relatively mild impact on its
earnings from the agreement.
   The Indian court ordered the Danbury-based chemical company to
make payment by March 31, thereby settling all claims resulting from
the leak of deadly methyl isocyanate at the Bhopal pesticide plant,
which was operated by Union Carbide's Indian subsidiary.
   More than 3,300 people died as a result of the Dec. 2, 1984,
leak, the world's worst industrial disaster. The plant has been
closed since the accident.
   The Indian government sued Union Carbide for $3 billion in
damages, claiming company negligence caused the leak. Union Carbide
maintains that sabotage by a disgruntled employee was to blame.
   The company said it expected an earnings impact of no more than
50 cents a share from the settlement.
   In the year ended Dec. 31, Union Carbide earned $720 million, or
$5.31 a share, on revenue of $8.32 billion. That compared to 1987
earnings of $231 million, or $1.76 a share, on revenue of $6.91
billion.
   ``Psychologically, it's terrific. Financially, it's reasonable,''
said Leslie Ravitz, a research director for Salomon Brothers Inc. in
New York. ``This relieves the pressure on Union Carbide and the
stigma.''
   James Wilbur, a vice president with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp;
Co. Inc. in New York, said Union Carbide has set aside $200 million
toward the settlement and had $250 million in insurance coverage,
leaving it at risk for another $20 million under Tuesday's
settlement.
   ``I think it's a decision that was pretty much anticipated,'' he
said of the settlement.
   Union Carbide had offered to pay the Indian victims $350 million
as early as 1986. That settlement was accepted by U.S. courts but
rejected in India.
   U.S. District Judge John F. Keegan ruled in May 1986 that all
claims filed against Union Carbide by individuals and the Indian
government should be transferred to India.
   Under Tuesday's settlement, the Indian government also will
dismiss all criminal charges brought against the company and at
least nine present or former Union Carbide employees, including
former Chairman Warren M. Anderson, who was charged with culpable
homicide.
   Anderson, who maintains an office at Union Carbide headquarters,
did not return telephone calls Tuesday seeking comment.
   In a statement, Union Carbide Chairman Robert D. Kennedy said,
``We are pleased that this will now provide for the care and
rehabilitation of the victims and their families and a fair
resolution of all issues.''
   Had the settlement not been reached, ``The alternative is
litigation that probably would have extended into the next century
with the final outcome that would be completely irrelevant to the
interests of the affected people in Bhopal and a continuing drain on
Carbide,'' said company spokesman Earl J. Slack.
   Richard Grand, founder of the Inner Circle of Advocates, a group
of more than 100 liability attorneys who have won
multimillion-dollar damage awards for clients in personal injury or
death cases, said it would be irresponsible to speculate on how much
Bhopal victims could have won in U.S. courts.
   ``American lawyers should let India judge what's fair,'' he said
from Tuscon, Ariz.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890215-0223 </DOCNO>
