<FIRST>r f PM-Pennwalt-Centaur     02-15 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pennwalt-Centaur,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Centaur Increases Offer For Pennwalt To $110 Per Share</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennwalt Corp., which has agressively spurned
Centaur Partners' advances since the group announced eight months
ago it wanted to take over the chemical company, now says it will
consider a $110 per share offer.
   Centaur announced its increased offer Tuesday morning. After the
stock market closed, Pennwalt came back with its answer.
   Pennwalt Chairman Edwin E. Tuttle said in a letter to Centaur
that the company would call a special board of directors meeting to
consider the increased offer.
   Centaur had offered $100 a share for the company in mid-December
in a deal valued at $698 million. The offer was to expire Feb. 22.
Tuesday's offer is estimated at $869 million.
   Tuttle said the board also will consider a date for a special
stockholder meeting called by Centaur and other stockholders.
Centaur has said it intends to try to fire Pennwalt's board of
directors and install its own board to approve the tender offer.
   The increased offer, due to expire March 1, came four days after
a federal judge denied a Pennwalt request to block the stockholders'
meeting.
   Pennwalt's stock closed at $113.12{ Tuesday, up $7.37{ from
Monday.
   Pennwalt's stock was trading at about $70 per share when Centaur,
an investor group with offices in New York and Bethesda, Md.,
launched its takeover bid.
   To fend off the takeover attempt, Pennwalt sold its
pharmaceutical division and most of its equipment business and
bought back about 40 percent of its outstanding shares for $85 each.
   Most recently, Pennwalt lobbied the Pennsylvania Legislature for
protection, hoping lawmakers would view the company as a victim of
the recent takeover frenzy.
   In an effort to thwart Pennwalt's defense efforts, Centaur, whose
stake in the Philadelphia-based company has increased to 17 percent
since mid-December, called for the meeting.
   Centaur said it has solicited support from shareholders
representing 34.6 percent of the common shares believed to be
outstanding, more than the 20 percent required under Pennsylvania
state law to call such a meeting.
   Michael Brinn, a senior vice president of the Carter
Organization, which tracks shareholder investments, testified in
federal court that arbitrageurs, who hope to make short-term profits
in takeover attempts, owned about 40 percent of the outstanding
shares as of November.
   Centaur said its increased offer would be funded from an
additional $10 million equity investment to be made by Centaur's
partners and from previously disclosed financing to be provided by a
syndicate of banks and the investment firm of PaineWebber Inc.
</TEXT>
