<FIRST>r f PM-PrimeComputer     02-15 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prime Computer,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Grants Appeal In Prime Computer Takeover Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals will conduct
an expedited review of a lower court order that has blocked MAI
Basic Four Inc.'s hostile takeover of Prime Computer Inc., which is
based in suburban Natick.
   MAI Basic said Tuesday that the federal appeals court in Boston
granted its motion for an quick appeal and scheduled a hearing for
March 2.
   On Dec. 29, Massachusetts District Court Judge A. David Mazzone
issued a temporary restraining order prohibiting MAI Basic from
pursuing its $20-per-share tender offer for Prime, saying the
company needed to make further financial disclosures.
   The Tustin, Calif.-based firm submitted a financial disclosure on
Jan. 24, but Prime insisted the information was still incomplete and
that MAI Basic's financing plan was in violation of several federal
securities rules.
   Mazzone refused to lift his injunction, and MAI Basic filed an
appeal last week.
   The two companies also are fighting a separate legal battle in
Delaware, where Prime is incorporated. Peter Rosenthal, a spokesman
for MAI Basic, said a Delaware court will schedule a hearing in that
case once the federal court in Boston makes its decision.
</TEXT>
