<FIRST>r f BC-Mexico-Finance     02-15 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mexico-Finance,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Bank Affiliate To Invest $200 Million In Mexican Companies
This Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Finance Corp. will invest at
least $200 million in private Mexican companies by the end of this
fiscal year, primarily to refinance individual foriegn debts, an
official of the World Bank affiliate said Tuesday.
   ``Not only does the Mexican government have a major foreign debt
problem, but so do many Mexican companies,'' corporation vice
president William Ryrie said at a news conference. ``One of the
things we do is to help various private companies restructure their
finances and liberate them from the financial burdens that have kept
them from expanding.''
   Ryrie said the corporation's investment in Mexico this fiscal
year includes $14.5 million already appropriated to Polimar, a
plastics export firm, and a $60 million line of credit granted for
restructuring of the government controlled Banca Serfin.
   He said most other investments planned for Mexico during the
remainder of fiscal 1988-89 are still in negotiations and he would
not say what other companies would be involved.
   The corporation was formed to boost economic development through
private-sector investment.
   Helmut Paul, the corporation's director of Latin American
investments, said future investments in Mexico will benefit
companies producing petrochemicals, household appliances, automobile
parts and hotels.
   Paul said those petrochemical companies are small private firms
making such things as plastics from petroleum derivatives and do not
include Pemex, the government oil monopoly.
   Ryrie was in Mexico to review corporation programs and meet with
federal officials, including Treasury Secretary Pedro Aspe.
   ``Mr. Aspe and his collegues have encouraged us to expand our
activities here and we expect to have a close relationship with the
new (presidential) administration,'' Ryrie said. President Carlos
Salinas de Gortari took office in December.
   ``Our activities in Mexico are growing very fast,'' Ryrie added.
He said the corporation already has invested $375 million in 27
companies nationwide.
   The corporation will continue investing at least $200 million in
Mexico each year in the future, he said.
   Much of that money will be used to restructure private companies'
foreign debts, Ryrie said.
   In 1988, the corporation used an $80 million loan to help the
Visa Group of Monterrey slash its foreign debt from $1.7 billion to
$400 million. The group's principal holdings are breweries,
including Dos Equis beer.
   Visa's restructuring included a variety of alternative
refinancing methods, including debt-for-equity exchanges, in which a
debtor uses equity to pay off outstanding debts.
   Mexico should examine similar alternative refinancing methods to
reduce its $106 billion foreign debt, Ryrie said.
   Ryrie said that despite its economic troubles ``the adjustment
Mexico has made in the last year of crisis has been an impressive
one, and one that should be respected.''
   ``The recent expansion of non-oil exports is important, as is the
new liberalization of previous trade policies,'' he added.
   Ryrie also praised the government's recent push to reprivatize
some government-held companies and said the corporation is willing
to help in the sale of additional state-owned companies to the
private sector.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890215-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0828EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-AutoSales     02-15 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Early February Car and Truck Sales Slide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automakers suffered a 15 percent drop in sales of
domestic-made cars and light trucks in early February over a year
ago, reflecting rising interest rates and declining incentives.
   The companies reported Tuesday that during the Feb. 1-10 period,
they sold vehicles at an average daily rate of 27,770, compared with
a rate of 32,749 during the same time in 1988.
   Car sales were off 18 percent, led by Chrysler Corp.'s drop of
nearly 31 percent, and light truck sales fell by 10 percent.
   The decline occurred partly because there were more enticing
incentives being offered in the market during early February last
year. Incentives are available now but only on a smaller number of
cars than in early February a year ago.
   Interest rates also have crept up since early February last year.
   ``I think the recent rise in (interest) rates have hurt sales a
little bit,'' said analyst Scott Merlis of Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. of
New York. ``Also they finished '88 on a very strong note.''
   So far this year, car and light truck sales are off 4.4 percent,
going to a daily rate of 31,257 from a rate of 32,686. Car sales are
down 7.7 percent while light truck sales have risen 1.9 percent so
far this year.
   Chrysler said its car sales fell 30.9 percent during early
February to a daily rate of 2,200 from a rate of 3,185 in the same
period last year. Chrysler's truck sales fell 5.1 percent to a daily
rate of 2,398 in early February from a rate of 2,528 at the same
time last year.
   So far this year, Chrysler's car sales are 13.6 percent lower
than they were last year, but truck sales are 7.7 percent ahead of
last year's pace.
   GM car sales fell 23 percent during early February to a daily
rate of 8,355, compared with a rate of 10,856 in early February
1988. Trucks made by GM in the United States sold at a daily rate of
4,040 during the first 10 days of the month, down 13 percent from
the 4,643 daily rate during early February last year.
   For the year, GM has sold 14.3 percent fewer cars this year than
last year, and 2.3 percent fewer trucks.
   Ford said its early February car sales slipped 9.5 percent to a
daily rate of 5,557 from last year's rate of 6,143. Ford truck sales
fell by 11.3 percent during the period to a rate of 3,596 compared
with a rate of 4,053 in the same period last year.
   Ford has sold 0.2 percent more cars and 0.7 percent more trucks
so far this year than during the same time last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890215-0228 </DOCNO>
