<FIRST>r f PM-Antitrust-Westinghouse     02-15 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Antitrust-Westinghouse,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accord Reached In Westinghouse-Asea Brown Boveri Venture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. and ABB Asea Brown
Boveri Ltd. of Switzerland are going ahead with planned joint
ventures following a proposed settlement of a federal antitrust
action.
   The Justice Department filed both the antitrust lawsuit and
proposed settlement Tuesday at federal court in Manhattan.
   Westinghouse and ABB later announced they have established joint
ventures in the electrical transmission and distribution equipment
markets of the United States, Brazil and Argentina.
   The Justice Department had sued to block the ventures, proposed
last April, claiming they posed significant threats to competition
in U.S. markets for power transformers, converter transformers,
steam turbine generator equipment and services.
   In January, Charles F. Rule, assistant attorney general in charge
of the Antitrust Division, said reduced competition ``would likely
mean higher electric rates for all users of electricity and higher
prices for many products manufactured using electricity.''
   Under the proposed settlement, the Justice Department withdrew
its objections to the joint ventures in return for ABB's agreement
to divest its Waukesha, Wis., transformer plant and related assets.
   One of the joint ventures establishes the Westinghouse ABB Power
T&amp;D Co., with Westinghouse owning 55 percent and ABB 45 percent. The
newly formed company will consist of Westinghouse and ABB's
manufacturing plants and engineering and marketing organizations of
their U.S. transmission and distribution businesses.
   Under separate agreement, ABB, based in Zurich, Switzerland, also
has acquired 45 percent of the stock of certain Westinghouse
subsidiaries in Brazil and Argentina.
   But as part of the settlement with the Justice Department,
Westinghouse must sell its technology for designing and making
converter transformers, used by electric utilities to convert
electricity to different voltages for efficient long distance
transmission.
   In its previous objection to the venture, the Justice Department
claimed the combined power transformer sales of Westinghouse and ABB
would exceed 50 percent of total U.S. sales, which were more than
$400 million in 1988.
   The settlement also bars both concerns from completing their
previously announced joint venture in the steam turbine generator
business for 10 years.
   Westinghouse and ABB are two of only four significant sellers of
major turbine generator repair and related services to U.S.
utilities, along with General Electric and Utility Power Corp., a
subsidiary of Siemens A.G. of West Germany, Rule said. U.S. sales of
steam turbine generators and the related services are estimated at
over $600 million per year.
   Pittsburgh-based Westinghouse had $12.5 billion in sales in 1988
and employs about 120,000 people.
   ABB Asea Brown Boveri Ltd. was created Jan. 1, 1988, with the
merger of Asea AB of Sweden and BBC Brown Boveri Ltd. of
Switzerland. ABB had 1988 sales of about $18 billion and 180,000
employees worldwide.
   Combined annual sales of the joint ventures are expected to be
about $1 billion. The operations employ about 10,000 and will
involve 20 Westinghouse and three ABB facilities in the U.S. and
Latin America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890215-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0852EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BoeingFines     02-15 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing Fines,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Fined 14 Times for $245,000 Total by FAA in Four Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. has been fined 14 times for a total of
$245,000 in the past four years by the Federal Aviation
Administration because of quality control problems, records show.
   Responding to a Freedom of Information request filed by the
Morning News Tribune of Tacoma, the FAA released a list of civil
penalties paid by Boeing and one paid by McDonnell Douglas from 1985
through 1988.
   Reports on the list were published Tuesday by The Seattle Times
and today by the Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
   The sole penalty McDonnell Douglas paid in that period was $1,700
for leaving a pin off an aircraft tail assembly.
   In addition, the FAA is pursuing a $200,000 fine against
McDonnell Douglas for failure to reinforce an area on the top side
of the fuselage of 174 aircraft where a blinking light is installed,
FAA attorney Douglas Anderson said.
   Fines paid by Boeing ranged from $1,000 for piercing wire
insulation with a marker, which caused an in-flight fire in a
lavatory on a Monarch Airlines 757, to a company-record $125,000
early last year for installing thousands of defective self-locking
nuts on flight-control systems of 22 767s.
   The list showed Boeing's second-largest fine was $30,000 last
October for installing faulty parts that help open the exit doors of
747 and 757 jetliners.
   Boeing discovered problems with ``emergency pressure reservoirs''
supplied by Textron Inc. but, ``in going through the process to
figure out what happened, they (Boeing) dropped the ball'' and the
parts were installed in 44 planes, Anderson said.
   Other Boeing fines on the list included:
   _$20,000 last September for failing to detect that another
supplier, Northrop Corp., improperly made a secondary
fuselage-support bracket used on 747s. The parts were installed on
an unknown number of 747s, resulting in an FAA order for the bracket
to be inspected periodically or replaced.
   _$16,000 last July for failing to install brake system guard
assemblies on 14 737s delivered in 1986 and 1987. Anderson said the
part was accidentally left off manufacturing blueprints.
   _$21,000 in January 1987 for using obsolete drawings at the
Everett plant and improperly trimming certain parts on half a dozen
747s without approval.
   _ $12,000 in February 1986 for ``reversing the installation of
right-hand and left-hand landing-gear up-lock and down-lock
actuators'' on five 737s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
