<DOCNO> AP890215-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 0938EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Semiconductors     02-15 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Semiconductors,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Computer Chip Makers Say Barriers Remain in Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American semiconductor makers are selling more in
Japan, but still face a ``psychological barrier'' in efforts to
expand their market share, a representative of the U.S.-based
Semiconductor Industry Association said Wednesday.
   Since the United States slapped $300 million in sanctions on
Japan in April 1987, saying it had violated a semiconductor trade
pact, the government and the country's largest chip makers have
tried to increase the foreign market share, said David Metz, Tokyo
representative of the American trade group.
   But Metz told the Foreign Correspondents Club of Japan that
changes in ``attitudes and practice'' have not been far-reaching
enough. He said the biggest barrier is that many Japanese
semiconductor users are not accustomed to doing business with
non-Japanese suppliers and are especially reluctant to deal with any
but the largest and most well-known foreign companies.
   ``The record during the last 1{ years under the semiconductor
trade agreement clearly reflects efforts of the Electronics Industry
Association of Japan and others to increase foreign access to the
Japanese market,'' Metz said.
   ``But the changes in practice have not filtered throughout the
industry,'' he said. ``We have to see a broader basis for increased
market share in Japan. The top five companies are not extensive
enough.''
   Foreign market share in Japan reached its lowest point in 1986 at
8.4 percent and rose to 12 percent in the fourth quarter of last
year.
   The United States says that Japan and the United States agreed in
1986 that the U.S. share of Japan's market should be about 20
percent in the absence of barriers. The Japanese say they promised
market access, but not guaranteed market share.
   ``We are no longer arguing that there are any formal or
legislative barriers, but there is a psychological barrier,'' Metz
said.
   U.S. officials imposed the unprecedented sanctions after accusing
Japan of dumping _ selling computer chips at unfairly low prices _
and not meeting pledges that the foreign share of Japan's market
would grow.
   The sanctions were in the form of special duties on imports from
Japan, and half were lifted in June 1987, when the United States
said it no longer could find evidence of dumping.
   But $165 million in sanctions remain, and Metz said the SIA does
not want them lifted yet.
   ``We won't advocate the sanctions be dropped because we want to
make sure that South Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong and Singapore know
there shouldn't be any dumping at all,'' Metz said.
   The world market for semiconductors is expected to soften in 1989
and Metz said the real test of progress for foreign producers in
Japan will be whether foreign firms are the first dropped by
Japanese users.
   Japanese producers captured half of the world's semiconductor
market last year, and enjoy an 89 percent share of their domestic
market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890215-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 1023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-OilReport     02-15 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Report,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Imports Continue To Soar, While Domestic Production Falls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. oil imports soared to more than 8 million
barrels per day in January for the first time since 1980 as demand
rose sharply and domestic production continued to dwindle, an
industry trade group said today.
   The American Petroleum Institute, which represents major oil
producers anday outside
government buildings to denounce the $470 million compensation
payment ordered by the Supreme Court.
   ``We want justice!'' and ``Hang Anderson!'' they shouted,
referring to former Union Carbide Corp. chairman Warren Anderson.
   ``The government has shaken hands with Union Carbide, whose hands
are dipped in the blood of our brothers and sisters,'' one woman in
the crowd of about 200 cried.
   The demonstration was organized by the Bhopal Gas-hit Women's
Front, one of several groups that accused the government of making a
deal with Union Carbide. The government had sought $3 billion
compensation for the gas leak, which according to the government
killed at least 3,329 people.
   Some survivors said they were glad a financial settlement was
finally reached, but they thought Union should be punished.
   ``We have often been promised money, but for us it was more
important that those who killed our brothers and sisters should be
hanged,'' said Sunil Kumar, 15, whose parents and five siblings died
when methyl isocyanate escaped from a pesticide plant owned by Union
Carbide's Indian subsidiary.
   On Tuesday the Supreme Court of India ended four years of legal
wrangling and ordered Union Carbide of Danbury, Conn., to pay $470
million to the government.
   The news was slow to sink in at the Jai Prakash Nagar shantytown
across the road from the deserted Union Carbide plant, which closed
after the Dec. 3, 1984 leak.
   Kumar still lives with a younger brother in the shack where his
family slept as the white killing vapor wafted across the teeming
settlement.
   This morning, he was studying for high school examinations _ one
of the few teen-agers in the shantytown who can afford not to work.
   He achieved this relative affluence soon after the disaster when
the Indian government gave next-of-kin 10,000 rupees (then worth
$833) for each gas death in the family. Kumar received 70,000 rupees.
   Many people seemed unable to comprehend what the settlement would
mean for them.
   One man, Shanker Lal, said there had been promises of money in
the past but he had yet to receive anything.
   At a hospital near the camp, Shaukat Bai, a veiled woman in her
mid-20s, waited for treatment for respiratory problems blamed on the
gas. Pregnant at the time of the disaster, she lost her unborn child
in a miscarriage health workers blamed on the gas. Her husband was
killed by the gas.
   ``Union Carbide should have been stripped of its assets,'' she
said. She said she thought pregnant women who suffered miscarriages
or gave birth to stillborn babies should be given compensation.
   Local politicians who crusaded on the victims' behalf were more
vehement.
   ``The Rajiv Gandhi government has committed an inhuman crime by
undermining the extent of the disaster,'' Giriraj Kishore, president
of the Slum Dwellers Federation said, referring to the prime
minister and his Congress Party.
   Satinath Sarangi, a scientist and member of the Bhopal Group for
Information and Action, said: ``This settlement is the final
testimony to the anti-people collusion between the government of
India and the Union Carbide Corp.''
   Alok Pratap Singh, a leader of the Poisonous Gas Episode Struggle
Front that often organized anti-Carbide demonstrations, called the
$470 million agreement ``a shameless settlement.''
   Vibhuti Jha, a young lawyer for the front, said the government
had committed a ``criminal offense'' by agreeing to drop criminal
charges against Union Carbide, its Indian subsidiary and corporate
officials.
   Anderson, chairman at the time of the gas leak, and eight
officials of Union Carbide of India Ltd. were charged in 1987 with
culpable homicide in the disaster.
   They never appeared for trial, and the Supreme Court quashed the
charges when it ordered Union Carbide to pay the ``full and final
settlement.''
   Dainik Bhaskar, a Bhopal daily newspaper, called the settlement
``niggardly and inadequate'' and said it set a dangerous precedent
for the Third World where ``people are considered guinea pigs by the
multinationals.''
</TEXT>
