<FIRST>u f PM-FactoryUse 1stLd-Writethru f0058 02-15 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Factory Use, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0058,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factory Use Holds Steady in January at Highest Level Since 1979</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 8th graf, The Fed's, to CORRECT to 5 percent sted percentage
points; Also moved on general news wires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's factories, mines and utilities in
January operated at 84.4 percent of capacity, a level that has not
been surpassed for nearly a decade, the government reported today.
   The Federal Reserve Board said January's operating rate was
unchanged from December, for which the figure was revised upward
from an earlier estimate of 84.2 percent.
   The operating rate for January and December has not been
surpassed since October 1979, when factories were functioning at
84.6 percent of capacity.
   As capacity use rises, so do fears that factories will have
trouble keeping up with orders, leading to shortages and price
increases and adding to inflationary pressures.
   The Fed since last March has been nudging interest rates upward
in an effort to slow the economy and keep inflation in check.
   In a second report today, the Federal Reserve said industrial
production climbed 0.3 percent in January following a revised
increase of 0.5 percent in December.
   A pickup in the production of both manufacturing and commercial
equipment during the month more than offset a decline in output of
transit equipment.
   The Fed's industrial production index stands at 141.1 percent of
its 1977 base, 5 percent higher than a year earlier.
   At manufacturing plants, the operating rate rose to 84.8 percent
last month, up from 84.6 percent in December. Capacity for durable
goods _ ``big ticket'' items expected to last more than three years
_ rose 0.1 percentage points to 83.3 percent, while capacity for
non-durable goods increased by 0.3 percentage points to 86.9 percent.
   Use of motor vehicles and parts manufacturing capacity was down a
hefty 4.1 percentage points to 75.7 percent.
   The January operating rate at utilities was 80.4 percent, down
from 81 percent a month earlier.
   In the mining sector, which includes oil and gas drilling, the
operating rate was down 0.8 percentage points to 82.5 percent. The
decrease reflected a substantial drop in coal output and oil and gas
extraction.
   Production in the manufacturing sector rose 0.5 percent in
January, matching a December increase, while output from mines and
utilities declined.
   Within manufacturing, production increased for all major
industries except transportation equipment and paper.
   Automobiles were assembled at an annual rate of 7.5 million
units, down from 7.9 million in December.
   Output at mines was down 1.2 percent in January after a 0.1
percent increase a month earlier. Production at utilities was down
0.8 percent from December, when output had increased 0.9 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
