<FIRST>r f BC-Sunshine-Rexene     02-15 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sunshine-Rexene,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mining Co. Drops Plan To Acquire Plastics Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunshine Mining Co. said it has abandoned
plans to acquire Rexene Corp., a Dallas-based plastics and
petrochemical maker, in a reported $896 million deal.
   ``We cannot reach agreement with the sellers on price and
terms,'' Sunshine Chief Financial Officer Joseph Denahan said.
   Sunshine said in December that the company known primarily for
silver mining and natural gas production with major operations in
the Idaho panhandle would pay $28 a share for Rexene common stock in
cash and securities.
   The proposal raised concern among some investors over how
Sunshine would finance the deal amid continuous losses the last four
years.
   Sunshine Chairman Michael Boswell had said the company wanted to
obtain a third line of business related to natural resources but
counter-cyclical to oil, gas and precious metals.
   ``I think our strategy continues as it has been and that is to
try to expand our precious metals and oil and gas business both
internally and through acquisition,'' Denahan said.
   Rexene, through its subsidiary Rexene Products Co., makes
thermoplastic resins and petrochemical products.
   Its products are used in many household goods, including food
packaging, toys, linings for disposable diapers and styrene for
production of disposable cups and other containers.
</TEXT>
