<HEAD>Grain and Soybeans Open Mixed to Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mixed to
mostly lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Weather again was the market's dominant feature, and it was
bearish on two counts. Traders said the rain and snow in the Midwest
would replenish soil moisture for the resumption next month of
spring planting. And steady rain in South America is expected to
help developing crops there.
   But ideas that some big export business may still be in the
offing, with the Chinese or Soviets most often mentioned as
customers, helped prices firm up a little bit.
   On the opening, wheat was unchanged to 1 cent higher, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.23{ a bushel; corn was } cent
to 1} cents lower, with March at $2.69 a bushel; oats were } cent to
1 cent lower, with March at $2.08 a bushel; and soybeans were 4\
cents lower to } cents higher, with March at $7.31 a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were lower on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle were .27 cent to .45 cent lower, with February at
74.47 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .35 cent lower,
with March at 81.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .03 cent to .30
cent lower, with February at 42.05 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .02 cent to 1.37 cents lower, with February at 37.80
cents a pound.

