<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-BritishAirways     02-15 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-British Airways,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Airways' Profit Up 44 Percent in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Airways PLC said its profit jumped 44
percent in the third quarter of its fiscal year, boosted largely by
its acquisition of British Caledonian Airways.
   British Airways reported Wednesday that its net profit in the
three months ended Dec. 31 rose to 33 million pounds, or around $58
million, from 23 million pounds, or $41 million, a year earlier.
Earnings per share for the quarter increased to 4.6 pence, or 8
cents, from 3.2 pence, or 6 cents.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 20 percent to 1 billion pounds, or
$1.77 billion, from 831 million pounds, or $1.5 billion.
   British Airways Chairman Lord King said British Caledonian has
been ``successfully merged and we can look forward to the benefits
of the acquisition being reflected in future results.'' British
Airways acquired the rival airline in 1987 for 253 million pounds,
or $448 million.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, British Airways'
profit was only slightly higher, however.
   Net profit for the nine months edged up 1.7 percent to 177
million pounds, or $313 million, from 174 million pounds, or $308
million, in the year-earlier period. Earnings per share rose to 24.6
pence, or 44 cents, from 24.2 pence, or 43 cents.
   Nine-month revenue increased 15 percent to 3.26 billion pounds,
or $5.8 billion, from 2.84 billion pounds, or $5 billion.
   King said the results for both periods were ``encouraging, with
the long-haul routes showing very satisfactory growth.''
   He said the outlook was good for passenger and cargo loads,
``particularly on long-haul routes, which remain high for the time
of year.''
   However, ``with increased competition, we must make sure that we
are competing effectively not only in terms of product and service,
but also on cost,'' the chairman said.
</TEXT>
