<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 1411EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BankOvercharges     02-15 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bank Overcharges,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wells Fargo Told To Pay $5.2 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has decided Wells Fargo Bank
overcharged its credit card customers $5.2 million in fees for
making payments late and exceeding credit limits.
   The Superior Court verdict Tuesday, in the first of several
similar suits against major banks, entitles holders of MasterCard
and Visa cards from Wells Fargo between July 1982 and May 1987 to
$4.1 million in refunds for late-payment fees and more than $1
million for over-limit fees.
   The jury agreed with lawyers for a group of bank customers that
Wells Fargo failed to make a reasonable attempt to set its fees no
higher than its costs. But jurors awarded less than half the $11
million the plaintiffs sought.
   Lawyers for the customers said Wells Fargo charged between $3 and
$5 for paying bills late while spending only $1.89 to process each
late payment. The lawyers said the bank charged $10 for exceeding
credit limits but spent only $1 to $2 for each excessive charge.
   ``We claimed you can't impose one of these charges (above costs)
as a penalty to get someone to comply with a contract. That's
illegal,'' said S. Chandler Visher, a lawyer for the customers.
   ``Other banks have been doing the same thing,'' he said. ``Each
case will be evaluated separately. But with this win, other banks
are going to start to think that this can happen to them. They may
want to settle out (of court).''
   Visher, who also represents customers in several other bank
suits, said similar suits are pending against Crocker National Bank,
Security Pacific Bank, Barclays Bank, Eureka Savings and Loan, and
First Interstate Bank. The Wells Fargo case was the first to go to
trial.
   Weyman Lundquist, a lawyer for Wells Fargo, said he and the bank
were not unhappy with the amount of the verdict but planned to
appeal.
   Wells Fargo believes its fees accurately reflect the total cost,
including indirect administrative costs, of handling late payments
and excessive charges, Lundquist said.
   Superior Court Judge Robert Dossee is to hear arguments next week
on whether he should order Wells Fargo to reduce its fees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
