<SECOND>AM-Nissan Ads,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car Maker Cancels Magazine Ads, Plans More TV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan is shifting $9 million in planned
magazine advertising for its 1989 models to television, the Japanese
carmaker's top U.S. ad man said Wednesday.
   Joe Opre, national advertising manager for Nissan Motor Corp.
USA, said the company already has spent $27 million on magazine ads
for 1989 and will resume magazine ads with introduction of the 1990
models in October or November.
   ``You get more visibility in the short term, a lot more reach a
lot faster,'' he said. ``It's an attempt or desire to get things
rolling maybe a little bit faster in terms of hitting our sales
goal.''
   In the first quarter of the 1989 model year, Nissan's share of
the import market dropped to 36 percent from 39 percent a year
earlier.
   The Magazine Publishers of America sent a contingent from its New
York headquarters to meet with Nissan officials in this Los Angeles
suburb this week seeking reassurances.
   ``We just want to find out what Nissan is thinking,'' said Jim
Gunther, executive vice president of the magazine trade group.
   Nissan will continue advertising in magazines aimed at car buffs
and at the black and Hispanic markets. The latter decision, Opre
said, grew out of a commitment to those magazines and to increasing
visibility in minority communities.
   On Feb. 3, Nissan settled a discrimination complaint before the
U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission by agreeing to pay
$605,000 and promote blacks, Hispanics, women and older workers.
</TEXT>
