<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue chips led the way as the stock market
rallied Wednesday, breaking out of a week-long slump.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had fallen 65.89
points over the five previous sessions, climbed 22.68 to 2,303.93.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
907 up, 556 down and 498 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 154.22 million
shares, up from 149.56 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 183.19 million shares.
   Interest rates, which have been climbing of late, pulled back a
bit in the credit markets Wednesday.
   Analysts said that evidently encouraged traders to do some
selective buying of stocks, especially in the blue-chip sector and
in issues involved in takeover rumors and speculation.
   In the economic news, the Federal Reserve Board reported a 0.3
percent increase in industrial production last month.
   The figure came in slightly below what most analysts had been
expecting, and thus didn't do much to aggravate the inflation
worries that have been dogging both the stock and bond markets.
   In the closing stages of the session, the market's advance
carried the Dow Jones industrials past the 2,300 level, which some
chart-watching analysts had suggested might be shaping up as a
psychological obstacle.
   Polaroid rose 1[ to 42|. Shamrock Holdings Inc., which is making
a hostile takeover bid for the company, said it plans to step up a
campaign to replace Polaroid directors.
   Tambrands gained 3 to 62{ amid takeover speculation.
   Claire's Stores, which estimated record profits for the quarter
ended Jan. 28, gained | to 7}.
   Gainers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, up 2\ at 127; General Electric, up | at 46\; American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up \ at 31\, and General Motors, up } at 89].
   Airline stocks, a hot group in recent weeks, added to their
recent gains. UAL rose 1~ to 127[; AMR 1\ to 60; Delta Air Lines }
to 56\, and NWA 1] to 67[.
   Analysts say investors have turned bullish on airlines in the
belief that the industry is emerging from a long period of
turbulence created by deregulation.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $20.93 billion, or 0.73
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
1.27 to 165.21.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 3.10 to 339.84, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up 2.43 at 294.24.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market gained
2.15 to 404.17. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 325.02, up 2.06.
