<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 2053EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Conrail     02-15 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Conrail,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conrail Names Longtime Railroader New Chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conrail on Wednesday elected a 77-year-old
railroader as interim chairman to succeed Richard D. Sanborn, who
died of an apparent heart attack after just six weeks as the freight
railroad's top executive.
   Philadelphia-based Conrail's board of directors said the
appointment of Stanley E.G. Hillman was temporary. The board set no
timetable for finding a permanent top executive but said it would
move quickly.
   Hillman was trustee of the Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul &amp; Pacific
Railroad in 1978-79 and served as chairman and chief executive
officer of Illinois Central Gulf Railroad from 1976-78.
   He has been a Conrail board member since 1980 and was on the
search committees that selected Sanborn and his predecessor, L.
Stanley Crane. Many analysts expected Conrail to appoint Crane
temporarily.
   Andrew Geller, a transportation analyst with Provident National
Bank in Philadelphia, said the election indicated Conrail will
``just go back to square one'' and search both inside and outside
the company for a permanent head.
   Conrail probably will seek ``someone with direct railroad
experience, direct marketing experience with railroads and someone
who is very tough with costs,'' Geller added.
   Sanborn, 52, died Sunday in Baltimore after an apparent heart
attack at his home. Services were Wednesday afternoon at Old St.
Paul's Episcopal Church in Baltimore.
   Sanborn was Crane's handpicked successor. Crane was credited with
leading Conrail to profitability and enabling it to be returned to
the private sector after 11 years of government ownership.
   Hillman was appointed trustee of the Milwaukee Road in January
1978 to oversee its reorganization plans under federal bankruptcy
laws. He proposed trimming the 9,800-mile railway system to 2,500
miles, a plan that was carried out in modified form before its sale
to the Soo Line in 1985.
   Hillman also served as president of the Illinois Central's parent
company, IC Industries, from 1971-77 and as vice chairman of IC
Industries in 1977-78.
   Conrail was formed by Congress in 1976 to reorganize six bankrupt
Northeast railroads, the Penn Central, Erie Lackawanna, Reading,
Central of New Jersey, Lehigh Valley and Lehigh &amp; Hudson River.
   It was sold in March 1987 for $1.6 billion in the largest public
stock offering in U.S. history.
   Conrail has been trying to build its traffic in such areas as
automobile shipping after concentrating on rebuilding track, gaining
clearance for double-stacked container cars and other equipment
needs.
   Under Sanborn, Conrail had been expected to try to expand into
such areas as hauling refuse and had discussed acquiring some
smaller rail lines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
