<DOCNO> AP890215-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 1741EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     02-15 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down Again But Above Its Lowest Levels; Gold Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar retreated across a broad front before
recovering some lost ground Wednesday in hectic dealings.
   Gold fell. The Republic National Bank of New York quoted a gold
bid of $383.60 a troy ounce late Wednesday, off 80 cents from
Tuesday's bid.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar endured a surprisingly
deep plunge early in the session as sellers acted aggressively. The
depth of the dive brought fresh buying by market operators
realigning their currency holdings.
   The result was the dollar finished Wednesday near its opening
levels and slightly below Tuesday's close.
   ``We had quite a wild day,'' said John McCarthy, chief dealer at
Amsterdam Rotterdam Bank. ``The violence in the movements were as
much generated by technical factors as by bearish sentiment.''
   Dealers also described the dollar's sell-off as an expected
correction after the strong advance it made earlier this year.
   They said the dollar has dipped over the past week because of
skepticism about the ability of the Bush administration to cut the
budget deficit and uncertainty about whether the Federal Reserve
intends to raise interest rates to combat inflation.
   In London, one British pound traded late at $1.7805, over 2 cents
more expensive for buyers than Tuesday's late $1.7588.
   Later, in New York, a pound cost $1.7743 compared with $1.77375
Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with levels late
Monday included: 1.8405 West German marks, down from 1.84325;
126.125 Japanese yen, down from 126.305; 1.56225 Swiss francs, down
from 1.56325; 1.1796 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1835; and 6.2637
French francs, down from 6.2715.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Tuesday's late
levels were: 1.8315 West German marks, down from 1.8615; 1.5565
Swiss francs, down from 1.5815; 6.2425 French francs, down from
6.3325; 2.0680 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1015; 1,339.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,355.05; and, 1.1800 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1835.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar dropped to 125.90 Japanese yen, down
from 127.20. In London late Wednesday, the dollar traded lower at
125.72 yen.
   Gold bullion prices fell in active trading, the weaker dollar
having no effect.
   Usually, when the dollar falls the gold price rises as it makes a
safer hedge for investors. But traders said gold market operators
are wary of pushing the price higher in case the dollar resumes its
recent rally.
   The late London bid price of gold was $382.00 a troy ounce, down
from $386.25. The late Zurich bid price was $381.60, down from
$385.50.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
declined to $384.60 a troy ounce from $385.40 Tuesday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $384.66 bid, down from
$388.68.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.79 bid a troy ounce,
down from $5.83.
   On New York's Comex, silver for current delivery finished at
$5.89 a troy ounce, up from Tuesday's settlement of $5.828.
</TEXT>
