<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Northrop     02-15 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Northrop,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secret Miltary Project Causes Large Fourth-Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northrop Corp. lost $86.1 million in the
fourth quarter of 1988 because of provisions for an expected $150
million loss associated with a secret military project, the
aerospace company said Wednesday.
   Company officials declined to identify the nature of the research
and development project but said it did not involve the B-2 stealth
bomber it built for the Air Force.
   The quarterly loss compared with a profit of $34.9 million, or 74
cents a share, recorded in the same period last year.
   Fourth-quarter sales also dropped, by 2 percent to $1.73 billion,
compared with $1.77 billion during the same 1987 quarter.
   The $150 million fourth-quarter charge ``resulted from the
company's conclusion that it will probably sustain a loss on certain
classified long-term fixed-price research and development
contracts,'' Northrop said in a statement.
   The company said it was negotiating with the Pentagon to make up
some of the unanticipated costs on the project. A company spokesman
refused to elaborate.
   For the full year, Northrop reported earnings of $104.2 million,
or $2.22 a share, an 11 percent increase over $94.2 million, or
$2.01 per share, in 1987.
   Northrop officials said the annual increase was made possible by
tax breaks related to the fourth-quarter loss. Because of the loss,
the company got a tax benefit of 42.7 percent in 1988, in contrast
to its tax rate of 31.4 percent the year before.
   The sales decline, which was 4 percent for the full year, was
largely the result of reduced research and development on several
classified projects and fewer deliveries of fuselages for the Navy's
F-A-18 Hornet fighter.
   Northrop makes the fuselage for the prime contractor, McDonnell
Douglas Corp.
</TEXT>
