<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     02-15 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Surge On News Of Cuts By Non-OPEC Members</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices broke through an important price barrier
and posted significant gains Wednesday after reports that non-OPEC
oil producers have proposed limiting their output of crude oil by
300,000 barrels a day, as well as rumors of contaminated oil stocks
in Louisiana.
   On other markets, soybeans added modestly to Tuesday's strong
gains; platinum surged despite a continuing gold slump; and cattle
and pork futures were off slightly in advance of a government report
that traders fear could show too many animals are already at feed
lots.
   Crude oil futures settled 83 cents higher in the spot month of
March, with the contract for delivery reaching $18.25 a barrel.
Gains ranging from 29 cents to 66 cents were registered in the back
months at the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   ``The crude (oil) market started off going nowhere, but once it
heard an offer was on the table for that kind of a cut, it pushed
through a lot of resistance at $17.85 level,'' said Peter Beutel, of
Elders Futures Inc.
   A report originating in London said a number of non-OPEC
producers ranging from Mexico to the Soviet Union have indicated a
willingness to cut their combined production before a meeting with
members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries set for
London sometime next month.
   ``Then the market stalled again at $18,'' said Beutel, ``and we
got a second boost from rumors of contaminated stocks in Louisiana.
No one pinned it down,'' he added, ``but in the absence of being
clear, we saw some very good buying.''
   Louisiana state officials said there was no contamination of
stocks. The rumors most likely were sparked by state environmental
officials' plans to adopt emergency rules for storage and handling
of oil field pipe that has been contaminated after use in
radioactive soil.
   The runup in crude oil helped heating stocks climb 1.29 cents to
1.64 cents higher, with March at 48.74 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline rose .45 cent to 1.44 cents, with March at 48.77 cents a
gallon.
   Soybeans, meanwhile, got most of their support from the nearby
soybean oil pit at the Chicago Board of Trade. Traders said export
business for the oils and fears of supply tightness because of a
decline in Malaysian stocks helped firm up prices in both pits.
   Weather, however, was again the market's dominant motivating
factor, and it was bearish on two counts. Traders said the rain and
snow in the Midwest would replenish soil moisture for the resumption
next month of spring planting. And steady rain in South America is
expected to help developing crops there.
   That dampened bean prices, as well as prices for the grains.
   Wheat was 1 cent lower to 1} cents higher, with the contract for
delivery in March at $4.25\ a bushel; corn was \ cent to 1\ cents
higher, with March at $2.71 a bushel; oats were \ cent to 1 cent
lower, with March at $2.08{ a bushel; and soybeans were 3\ cents
higher to 5} cents higher, with March at $7.38{ a bushel.
   Gold plummeted to a new low for the year in early trading at the
Comex, but recouped most of its losses for the day, settling 80
cents to $1 lower, with February at $384.60 a troy ounce.
   Silver registered rises of 5.8 cents to 6.7 cents, with February
at 5.89 a troy ounce, but platinum was the best performer among the
precious metals Wednesday, climbing $5.90 across the board, with
February at $536.20 a troy ounce.
   Platinum has been improving steadily since dropping sharply in
recent months following a Ford Motor Co. announcement that it had
developed a substitute for the metal in catalytic converter used in
automobiles.
   Livestock and pork futures were mostly lower at the Chicago
Mercantile as traders braced for the release Thursday of the USDA's
cattle-on-feed report.
   ``There's some apprehension the report will show plenty of cattle
on the feed lots,'' said Charlie Richardson of Lind-Waldock Inc.,
Denver. ``Cattle's been the strength of the whole meat complex
recently, and with those marking time, there wasn't much reason to
walk in and buy hogs.''
   Live cattle settled .50 cent lower to .18 cent higher, with
February at 74.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .43 cent lower
to .02 cent higher, with March at 81.82 cents a pound; live hogs
were .38 cent lower to .02 cent higher, with February at 41.82 cents
a pound; and frozen pork bellies were unchanged to a limit-down 2
cents, with February at 37.82 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
