<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     02-15 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Surge Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures surged Wednesday, fueled by a
report that non-OPEC producers may cut production.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, rose 83 cents
to $18.25 a barrel, breaking through what analysts said was a
crucial technical barrier at $18. The contract closed at $17.42 on
Tuesday. Other contract months also rose.
   The jump in crude prices helped pull up refined product prices,
traders said. Unleaded gasoline scheduled for release next month
rose 1.44 cents to close the day at 48.77 cents a gallon, while
heating oil increased 1.36 cents to 48.74 cents a gallon. Contracts
for delivery after March also rose.
   Traders said the market opened higher but slid early despite a
weekly American Petroleum Institute report showing that crude oil
stocks fell 7.6 million barrels a day last week. The report proved
neutral for the market because it offset the previous week's
statistics that showed a 7 million barrel rise in crude inventories.
   About midday, a report quoting a representative of a non-OPEC
observer nation rallied the market, said Nauman Barakat, vice
president of energy investments at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The report said a group of producers outside the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries is considering a 300,000 barrel-a-day
cut in output.
   ``The report indicated it's a deal already done,'' Barakat said.
He said such an agreement would be formalized at a meeting next week.
   The non-OPEC group is scheduled to meet in London on Monday and
Tuesday. A similar meeting last month adjourned without producing an
accord, but the group issued a statement saying it supported recent
cutbacks by OPEC.
   Wednesday's energy prices also got a lift from a report that
Louisiana oil field pipes are contaminated, said Andrew Lebow,
senior broker and analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc.
   Louisiana state officials said there was no contamination of
stocks. The rumors most likely were sparked by state environmental
officials' plans to adopt emergency rules for storage and handling
of oil field pipe that has been contaminated after use in
radioactive soil.
   The state's Department of Environmental Quality is enacting
emergency rules next week for the pipes until formal rules can be
adopted in about 120 days.
   Lebow said the report was bullish because it led to concerns
about possible production cutbacks.
</TEXT>
