<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Machinists 1stLd-Writethru   02-15 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Machinists, 1st Ld-Writethru,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Charges Illegal Union Slowdown; Both Sides In Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Machinists authorizing strike;
picks up 5th graf pvs bg'ng, Members of ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The militant Machinists union announced overwhelming
support Wednesday for a strike against Eastern Airlines next month
unless a contract is signed, while the carrier charged that an
illegal work slowdown has backed up 19 aircraft and delayed flights.
   In other developments, the union contended that Eastern
management has brought recruitment of possible strikebreakers to its
home turf.
   Charles Bryan, Machinists district president, told members at a
packed union hall meeting that 97.33 percent of the voting
membership authorized a strike if no contract is reached.
   The final ballots were cast Tuesday in Atlanta, the count was
completed late Wednesday afternoon, and participation was 77
percent, Bryan said.
   After announcing the vote, the union leader charged that Eastern
has been stalling talks.
   ``They have not moved in 16 months in their original opening
position,'' Bryan said. ``They are not negotiating. This strike vote
simply means that if they continue in that mode and do not
negotiate, there will be a strike on March 4.''
   Eastern responded that the strike authorization vote was easily
predicted and that the carrier has been focusing all efforts on a
negotiated settlement.
   Meanwhile, Eastern attorney David Ross charged that a ``very
serious slowdown'' and a sickout by union workers have caused a
backlog of aircraft that cannot fly until they pass mandated checks.
   But Bryan called the charge ``a smokescreen.''
   ``The work is being done,'' he said.
   Members of the Machinists union, representing around 8,500
mechanics and ground workers at Eastern, have been working without a
contract for 13 months. If there is still no solution by late next
week, federal mediators plan to bring both sides together in
Washington.
   If there is still no contract by midnight EST March 3, Eastern
will be able to impose its own work rules, and the Machinists will
be able to strike legally.
   Ross charged that the Machinists have caused the 19-aircraft
backup by taking twice the normal time to perform what he called C
and D checks, anything from routine mechanical inspections to major
overhauls.
   ``Historically we have had no backup. We always have planes in
C-check or D-check status, but we don't have 19 planes waiting to be
worked on,'' he said. ``We would normally only have a certain number
in being done and then put back in service.''
   But Bryan claimed that Eastern's recent performance refutes the
carrier's allegation of widespread work slowdowns.
   ``It is mind-boggling that the main line of (Eastern) advertising
right now currently is they're the No.1 on-time operator in the
entire airline industry,'' the union leader said. ``How could that
possibly be going on if our people are slowing down? We must perform
and perform quickly and do a good job for that to happen.''
   Meanwhile, both sides pressed their arguments in federal court
Wednesday, with the union trying to keep the carrier from farming
out work traditionally done by organized labor. Eastern said it has
no other choice.
   The airline has ``begun to subcontract certain work that it has
been unable to perform as needed due to circumstances beyond its
control,'' Eastern said in an amended complaint filed late Tuesday.
   If the Machinists are allowed to continue on the same course, the
union ``will continue to cause substantial and irreparable injury to
Eastern, the traveling public and the free flow of interstate
commerce,'' the complaint alleged.
   The airline also contended that slowdowns and sickouts ``have
caused and will continue to cause substantial flight delays and
disruptions during Eastern's normally heavy winter travel season.''
   U.S. Senior District Judge C. Clyde Atkins agreed to accept the
Machinists' case on subcontracting and directed Eastern to file a
response by noon EST Thursday. He said he will then set a hearing,
probably before the week is over.
   The Machinists asked U.S. District Judge James W. Kehoe on
Tuesday to send the case to a different judge, but Kehoe granted
Eastern motion's Wednesday to send the case to Atkins, who ordered
an end to a wildcat strike by ground crews last week.
   The union also charged that Eastern has started recruiting
strikebreakers in Miami with newspaper ads offering airport
opportunities for baggage handlers, agents and managers but listing
no employer. Similar ads ran in Atlanta and in Washington, D.C.,
last week.
   Eastern, based in Miami, is a subsidiary of Houston-based Texas
Air Corp.
</TEXT>
