<FIRST>r f AM-CaterpillarLogo     02-15 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Caterpillar Logo,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caterpillar Unveils New Corporate Logo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caterpillar Inc. unveiled a new corporate
trademark Wednesday, the second time in three years the
image-conscious company has changed its public identity.
   In 1986, Caterpillar dropped ``Tractor'' from its name and
launched an aggressive effort to diversify the products and services
it offers. Caterpillar is the world's leading manufacturer of
earth-moving equipment.
   The new trademark is actually two different logos to be used
interchangeably. One features the word ``CAT'' with a yellow
triangle underneath, the other uses the word ``Caterpillar'' in
block letters with a yellow triangle under the first three letters.
   The triangle is a graphic device designed to evoke thoughts of
stability, strength and technology, said John Hanson, the
Peoria-based company's vice president of marketing.
   ``No one is naive enough to expect these changes alone will
produce an immediate increase in sales or a renewed image,'' said
George Schaefer, chairman and chief executive officer.``But giving
the Caterpillar trademarks a new look is another important step in
company strategy. If identifies Caterpillar as a modern, progressive
company.''
   Caterpillar's current logo is an abstact black-and-white ``C''
introduced in 1968. However, it failed to increase the identify of
Caterpillar products and internal surveys showed poor recognition of
the symbol when it was not accompanied by the company name, company
executives said.
   Schaefer said the change is designed to capitalize on the
public's positive image of ``CAT'' and ``Caterpillar'' and provide
some uniformity to the growing list of Caterpillar subsidiaries and
their logos.
   Hanson said the company estimates it will cost upwards of $10
million over five years to convert all buildings, vehicles,
equipment, stationery, packaging and other items to the new logo.
   Caterpillar is coming off perhaps the best year ever in the
64-year history of the company, which employs 60,558 people
worldwide and consistently ranks among the top 50 U.S. industrial
corporations in sales.
   Caterpillar posted record sales of $10.4 billion and profits of
$616 million in 1988.
   Although earth-moving and construction equipment and engines
remain the foundation of Caterpillar's success, the company has
broadened its operations to include turbine engines, lift trucks,
high technology, parts distribution, financial services and
insurance.
</TEXT>
