<FIRST>r f AM-Obit-Brown 1stLd-Writethru f0320 02-15 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Brown, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0320,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Labor Representative Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with date and cause of death, other background;
no pickup. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Brown, longtime European representative of
the AFL-CIO, has died at the age of 77, the Paris office of the U.S.
labor federation announced Wednesday.
   Brown was buried Tuesday at the Montparnasse cemetery in southern
Paris. The AFL-CIO office in Washington said he died of cancer at
his home on Friday.
   Brown, born in New York City, helped organize strikes at the
General Motors Corp. and the Ford Motor Co. between 1936 and 1942,
and was assigned to Europe in 1945.
   He was known for his support for anti-communist causes, and was
barred from France in 1956 for supporting Algerian rebels. He was
allowed to return only after the North African country won its
independence in 1962.
   Brown was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom in October by
then-President Reagan for helping lead the resistance to communist
takeovers of trade unions in Western Europe after World War II.
   Brown continued working until 1986, when he suffered a stroke.
The AFL-CIO office said he was survived by his wife, Irene Brown,
and a son, Robert.
